<HEADLINE>
RECORDS FALL AT TRACK MEET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update.)  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ali Abiola of St. Peter's High School in Staten
Island starred at the 45th annual Bishop Loughlin Games in
Manhattan Saturday, setting a meet record in the boys 1,000 meters
and anchoring St. Peter's record-breaking 3,200-meter relay.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola's time of 2 minutes 31.07 seconds in the 1,000 meters and
his 1:53 anchor leg on the relay, which set a meet record of
7:56.69, earned him the most valuable athlete award in the largest
indoor high school meet in the country. More than 4,000 athletes
from 181 Eastern schools participated at the Armory Track and Field
Center in upper Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   St. Peter's finished second in the boys team scoring to
Philadelphia's Roman Catholic, 26-19. Lawrence of Long Island was
third at 18.
</P>
<P>
   The boys division produced two other meet records. Anthony
Ewers, a junior from Lawrence, lowered the 300-meter dash standard
to 34.66 seconds, and Campus Magnet of Queens posted a 1:30.28
while winning the 800-meter relay. Jason Morgan, Ewers' senior
teammate, missed the 600-meter mark by two-tenths of a second while
winning in 1:21.50.
</P>
<P>
   In girls events, which continued Saturday night, Danielle Jelley
of Clark High School in Westbury, N.Y., rallied to win 1,000 meters
in 3:00.61, Pilar Marini of St. Anthony's in Huntington, N.Y., was
first in the 3,200 meters at 11:15.07, Robin Mortel of A. P.
Randolph of Manhattan was the winner of the 600 in 1:36.10 and
Jennifer Donovan of Half Hollow Hills, N.Y., took the mile in
5:11.45.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
