<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SENATE-AZR </SLUG>
  
 ARIZONA'S SENATORS MINDFUL OF CONSEQUENCES (For use by N.Y. Times
News Service
 clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One faces re-election in 2000, and the other is
pondering a run for president.
</P>
<P>
   For Arizona's U.S. senators, the timing of the impeachment trial
of President Bill Clinton could have fateful political
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is to start in January, just as Sen. John McCain is
expected to be nearing an announcement on whether to seek the GOP
presidential nomination. His Republican colleague, Sen. Jon Kyl, is
among the one-third of the Senate up for re-election in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Although many lawmakers assert that impeachment is a vote of
conscience, it carries political risks regardless of which way they
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans have expressed distaste for the entire
impeachment procedure, creating a potential backlash against those
who prolong it by rejecting an alternative, such as a strongly
worded censure.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's most vocal critics are certain to lash out at any
solution that seems to let him off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their status as future ``jurors,'' neither Kyl nor
McCain would speculate on how they or their colleagues would vote.
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews they dropped some hints about their thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl appears to be in a camp with Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss. Both would like the trial to follow its course;
neither seems inclined to endorse a proposal by former Senate
Majority Leader Robert Dole, R-Kan., to wrap up impeachment in the
first week of January with a toughly worded condemnation of Clinton
rather than a trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that we ought to follow the constitutional procedure
wherever that takes us _ conclude the matter in that way,'' Kyl
said before the House vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, there are a lot of things you can do even in the middle
of a trial, obviously. You can dismiss the charges, technically. It
is even possible to go through this without having an actual vote
at the end of the process, although I think that (a vote) is
desirable.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyl disagreed with Clinton backers who argue that perjury
involving a sexual affair falls short of an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the most important point here is that perjury destroys
truth, which is at the heart of our judicial system. This is a
system which everybody is willing to put their faith in, even to
submit their life to the judgment of 12 people that they have never
met before because they know the system is fair,'' Kyl said. ``If
truth begins to suffer because we don't punish perjury, the entire
system could fail.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain is more of a maverick than Kyl and has bucked the GOP on
some big votes. For those reasons, McCain's vote will doubtless be
more closely scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is on a preliminary list compiled by University of
Virginia political scientist Larry Sabato of Republican senators
who might digress from the party line against Clinton. Also
included were Sens. John Chaffee of Rhode Island, Susan Collins and
Olympia Snowe of Maine, and Jim Jeffords of Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've shown an independence in the past and they come from
states _ McCain the exception _ that are moderate and do not reward
Republicans for being loyal to the party,'' Sabato said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a close friend of Dole's, McCain would not reject the
former senator's suggestion for censure out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pay very careful attention to Senator Dole, because I have
the utmost respect and affection for him,'' McCain said before
leaving for vacation a few days ago. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
