<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA LEARNED THE HARD WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Calls for resignation ring through the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The beleaguered chief executive stands defiant, declaring
himself a victim of a political railroad job.
</P>
<P>
   For Americans, it is now a painful reality.
</P>
<P>
   But for Arizonans, it happened 10 years ago in one of the most
bizarre events in state history. The nation watched as then-Gov.
Evan Mecham, a Republican, fell under the weight of charges of
obstructing justice and misusing public funds.
</P>
<P>
   Now, America is about to experience the political turmoil
Arizona went through in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business of the state ground to a halt at that point in
time,'' Attorney General Grant Woods said. ``It's hard to imagine
that won't be the case in Washington today.''
</P>
<P>
   The legacy of Mecham's political rise in 1987 and fall a year
later was a political war that ended in the downfall of the House
speaker, Joe Lane; the Senate president, Carl Kunasek; and other
Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Now the country is facing a similar situation but with higher
stakes: the fate of President Clinton and the public's confidence
in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public will question why we put the nation through this if
he's not going to be removed,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Tom Freestone, a Republican who was a Maricopa County
supervisor during Mecham's brief reign, said Republicans in
Congress ``better understand there's going to be an aftermath.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a price that's going to be paid, regardless of what
you do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, there are few things Mecham, a hard-line Republican
former car dealer, and Clinton, a former law professor, have in
common.
</P>
<P>
   But now, both have come together in the history books: Mecham is
the last governor in America to be impeached, and Clinton is the
first president to be impeached in 130 years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Mecham was convicted and removed from office in a
Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Clinton finds himself in the middle of an equally grave
dilemma, although he, unlike Mecham, has strong support within his
own party.
</P>
<P>
   One thing seems certain: America is about to undergo a kind of
political turmoil that Arizonans experienced 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Kunasek, now a member of the Arizona Corporation Commission,
said there might be an upside to be taken from Arizona's
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, did it paralyze Arizona? Temporarily perhaps,
but the long-term effect was the stabilization of government,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we don't have right now. We have a crippled
president whose credibility is always going to be questioned. It's
going to hurt his effectiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., said those who predict a paralysis in
government only give impetus to calls for Clinton's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will only accelerate calls for the president to resign
and spare the country this dire result,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl, though, does not believe the predictions of paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing fine apparently in the operation in Iraq,'' he
said. ``The stock market actually went up yesterday (Friday).
People are out Christmas shopping. The Supreme Court will get along
just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not something we should fear as a nation.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kyl, who lived through Arizona's impeachment battle, also
said: ``It is neither in the administration's or public's best
interest to have a long, drawn-out trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public doesn't want to drag it out . . . and it's a
political loser for us.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kyl and other senators, there is now no turning back.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment trial will run its course, and then everyone
will know just what price is to be paid. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
