<HEADLINE>
HISPANICS, BLACKS RALLY TO CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most African-Americans and Hispanics consider President Clinton
a champion for their cause, and they're planning to stand by their
man.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the impeachment proceedings ``wasteful partisan drama,''
Rep. Ed Pastor, D-Ariz., voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   Support for Clinton is so strong among African-Americans that
Nobel Prize-winning author Toni Morrison rallied to Clinton's
defense and called him ``our first Black president.''
</P>
<P>
   Voicing the support for President Clinton in the 17-member
Congressional Hispanic Caucus at a White House meeting, Rep.
Esteban Torres, D-Calif., had these words: ``We stand with the
president to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for their support, they say, goes beyond
partisanship. Black and Hispanic leaders say Clinton has done more
for them than any other president.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Clinton has worked to end racial disparities in
health care. The Clinton administration granted funds to establish
the Office of Minority Health Research and Alternative Medicine at
the National Institutes of Health.
</P>
<P>
   The president also has placed more time and money into civil
rights enforcement than has been allocated in the past 12 years.
More funding was provided to improve coordination among the
government's civil rights agencies and the Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Clinton promoted a national conversation on race
relations in the United States. As part of the initiative, he
established a Race Advisory Board, which traveled around the
country listening to cases of bias and looking for ways to end
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks and Hispanics also have heralded Clinton for opposing
Republican-led efforts to wipe out affirmative action and for
defending bilingual education.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps most important to many ethnic leaders is Clinton's
record on Hispanic and Black appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has one of the most diverse Cabinets and administrations
in history. African-Americans and Hispanics have been placed in
many non-traditional positions. A few include Rodney Slater as
secretary of Transportation, Bill Richardson as secretary of
Energy, Togo West as secretary of Veterans Affairs, and Maria
Echaveste, deputy White House chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, about 13 percent of Clinton administration appointees
are African-Americans, twice as many as any previous
administration, and about 8 percent have been Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many believe Clinton can do more. Raul Yzaguirre,
president of the National Council of La Raza, has called on the
president to make more favorable appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Black and Hispanic leaders say Clinton has done more than
his predecessors and certainly more than his opponents in the 1992
and '96 elections would have.
</P>
<P>
   For those reasons, Blacks and Hispanics stand behind Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In his re-election bid in 1996, Blacks and Hispanics played a
big role in the Clinton victory. Clinton received 88 percent of the
Black vote and slightly more than 70 percent of the Hispanic vote.
</P>
<P>
   A poll by the Pew Research Center for the People and the Press
released just before independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report was
issued showed Clinton with an 88 percent job approval rating among
African-Americans, compared with a 61 percent approval rating among
Whites.
</P>
<P>
   The poll didn't provide a breakdown for Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   For many Hispanics and Blacks, their support goes beyond
programs and appointments. The impeachment movement and Starr's
investigation become an issue of fairness.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's investigation of Clinton's sexual affair with Monica
Lewinsky reminds many of J. Edgar Hoover's infamous investigation
of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.'s sex life in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those of us with a history in the civil rights movement,
this is an issue of fundamental fairness,'' Rep. Sheila Jackson
Lee, D-Texas, has said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
