<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-SOUTHWEST-MISSOURI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAINOUS' LAST-SECOND LAYUP LIFTS TCU TO WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Mo. _ In his back yard, maybe 10 years ago, TCU
forward Marquise Gainous used to practice for a moment just like
last night's.
</P>
<P>
   The game was tied, only seconds remained and he had the ball in
his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``A layup,'' Gainous said. ``You always want to shoot a layup, a
game-winning layup.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what he had, the ball rolling off his fingers and
in with 0.2 seconds remaining to give TCU a 71-69 victory against
Southwest Missouri State last night in front of 9,114 screaming
fans at Hammons Student Center.
</P>
<P>
   The previous 39 minutes, 59.8 seconds had been a strange
back-and-forth game that led to TCU (10-2) in need of a shot at the
buzzer to win a game it had never trailed.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Missouri's Allen Phillips buried a pair of free throws
with 10 seconds remaining to bring the Bears even for the first
time since the opening tip.
</P>
<P>
   TCU had a timeout remaining but declined to take it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a scramble situation, we're good,'' Horned Frogs coach
Billy Tubbs said. ``That's our game policy. We don't want to give
them the opportunity to set up their defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs couldn't get the ball into Prince Fowler, so Shannon
Long dribbled to halfcourt. He then passed to Ryan Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only looked up once, the moment I got the ball, and I saw
there were five seconds remaining,'' Carroll said. ``I just figured
that I'd penetrate, get fouled, make something happen. Then I saw
Marquise just standing there by himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The pass went down to Gainous with about two seconds remaining.
He said he didn't have any idea how much time was left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just shot,'' said Gainous, who led the Frogs with 18 points.
``It feels good to sneak out of here with a win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sneak'' provides a pretty good assessment of a game that TCU
seemed to dominate but never seemed to control.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs outshot the Bears 56.4 percent to 35.3. Southwest
Missouri (7-2) especially struggled on 3-pointers, going 5-of-22.
The one place the Bears outshot the Frogs was from the free-throw
line.
</P>
<P>
   TCU attempted only four free throws, including two misses in the
final 45 seconds. Southwest Missouri shot 18, leaving TCU in foul
trouble all game. Frogs preseason All-American Lee Nailon fouled
out with 3:37 remaining and a season-low 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   None of this had Tubbs too pleased.
</P>
<P>
   He got a technical foul during the game for arguing with
officials and got in a couple of jabs after it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bye John, bye Jerry, bye Ed,'' Tubbs said, waving to officials
John Huggins, Jerry Petro and Ed Schumer as they left the building.
``Hope you make it back in the Big Eight someday.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the foul disparity and a game-high 26 points from Bears
big man Danny Moore, TCU had a seven-point lead with 1:14
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs had a two-point lead and the ball with 35.6 seconds
remaining. They immediately committed a turnover, and Phillips hit
the two free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure looked like it, didn't it?'' Tubbs said of the chances
for overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Said Carroll: ``If we had gone to overtime, we'd have lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was Southwest Missouri's largest since 1992 and 10th
largest ever. When the Bears tied it, the closest they had been all
night, the crowd was was so loud that Carroll said he could hardly
hear himself think.
</P>
<P>
   If he had been thinking, he probably would have taken the shot
himself.
</P>
<P>
   He, too, had been a youngster once. His back yard had also
provided practice for a moment just like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same except I passed instead of shot,'' Carroll
said. ``Hey, all that matters is that the good guys win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
