<HEADLINE>
THIS BASKET WAS FULL OF MIRACLES
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
As the clock ticked down to 6, 5, 4 seconds left, Coach Rodger Bur
row began going over the speech he'd deliver in the locker room.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We'd taken a timeout with 8 seconds left, down by two
points,'' he said. ``I told my point guard, who was having a great
night, to dribble coast-to-coast and take a shot. But he got
blocked and passed off, and the ball was getting bob bled around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagined telling the boys how proud I was of them for
getting close. It was a great learning experience. That was my
speech. The fact we'd actually made a game of it was one miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't dare ask for another.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen years ago, Burrow moved to the small town of San Manuel,
northeast of Tucson, with the idea of staying a year, maybe two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I knew it, I fell in love with the community,'' he
said. He's now a teacher, coach and athletic director at San Manuel
Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 14, his eighth-grade boys bas ketball team played at
home against the Hayden Lobos. In front of his players, Burrow
spoke of rising to the occasion, of fulfilling dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, he expected a nightmare. &QL; 
LESSONS TO LEARN
</P>
<P>
   The week before the game, six of Bur row's players were declared
ineligible be cause of grades. He filled out the roster with
seventh-graders. Then, the day of the game, he learned that two of
his remain ing eighth-graders had broken team rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terrible blow to the team, but we had to suspend
them, too,'' he said. ``There are lessons about behavior and
consequences boys this age must learn.''
</P>
<P>
   If not, they may grow up and act like NBA players.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the Lions starters was left to play. For a time,
Burrow considered forfeiting the game, but the Hayden coach wanted
to play. With all the distractions and the new players, Burrow
forgot to turn in an official lineup card before the opening
tip-off.
</P>
<P>
   The whistle sounded just after the game began and Hayden was
awarded 10 technical foul shots. They made six.
</P>
<P>
   ``From there,'' Burrow said, ``things went even further
downhill.''
</P>
<P>
   The visiting team ran up a 24-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was imagining what I could say to these kids to turn this
disaster into some thing positive,'' Burrow said, ``when they
started coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   His lone eighth-grade starter, Brandon Buzan, hit a
three-pointer. Then he hit an other. Then he made a steal, drove
for a layup, made it, got fouled and made the foul shot. By
halftime the Lions were within six.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the second half Hayden went on another
run,'' Burrow said. ``They maintained what seemed like a steady
lead of around 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Burrow's seventh graders began gain ing confidence, however, and
the score got closer. With 20 seconds left, Buzan was fouled and
made both shots. The Lions were behind by only one.
</P>
<P>
   It stayed that way until 8 seconds were left, when a Hayden
player was fouled and made one of two shots. The lead was 2. &QL; 
VALIANT ATTEMPT
</P>
<P>
   Burrow told Buzan to take the last shot. He was well-guarded,
though, and passed off. After getting batted around, the ball
landed in the hands of 5-foot-2 Brian Kaufman, a seventh-grader,
near mid-court.
</P>
<P>
   Losing makes you stronger. That's what Burrow planned to tell
his kids.
</P>
<P>
   Two defenders closed in on Kaufman, who whirled and flung the
ball. Burrow wasn't sure the boy could even reach the basket from
that far away.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all that's bad in the world,'' he said, ``you begin to
believe there's no such thing as poetic justice. Don't you?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he is told.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the story of a grade school basketball game from a
small town in Ar izona may be the most important news to be
published in months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching that ball fly toward the hoop I couldn't believe it
would go in,'' Burrow said. ``I thought to myself. Nope. Nope.
Nope.''
</P>
<P>
   Yep. &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at
 &UR; ed.montini &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
