<SLUG> BC-BKN-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-ARIZONA-STATE-TEX </SLUG>
 
AGGIES FALL SHORT IN 3 OTs 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Arizona State relied on the clutch
shooting of guard Eddie House to wrestle away a 96-91 victory
against Texas A&AMP;M last night in triple overtime.
</P>
<P>
   An eventually exhausted crowd of 4,023 witnessed a performance
by House that likely won't be equaled soon in new Reed Arena as the
junior poured in 34 points. His shooting was directly responsible
for sending the game into the first, second and third overtimes. He
scored 11 of the Sun Devils' 19 points in the third OT.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I've ever been involved in a game like that,'' A&AMP;M
coach Melvin Watkins said. ``Neither team had any quit in them.
This \RArizona State\S is the most talented team we've played so
far.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU is now 5-4. The Aggies fell to 7-2 and lost for the first
time in Reed Arena after five consecutive victories.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils also got 23 points and 18 rebounds from Mike
Batiste, a 6-foot-8 power forward who became eligible earlier in
the day after receiving a passing grade on his last final. The
Aggies, meanwhile, were without 6-9 starting center Paul Jacobs,
who sprained an ankle yesterday afternoon during shoot-around
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Shanne Jones led A&AMP;M with 26. Jerald Brown added 19.
</P>
<P>
   House, who was averaging 21.3 points at tipoff, hit 3-point
shots near the end of regulation and again in the second overtime
from both corners to prolong the contest. House clicked from the
left corner with 7.3 seconds left in the second OT to tie the game
at 77 and bring on the third extra period.
</P>
<P>
   ASU jumped out 65-62 in the first overtime, but Brown brought
the Aggies back with a 3-pointer. The teams exchanged free throws
until Batiste was called for walking and Clifton Cook hit a field
goal from the top of the key for a 69-67 Aggies lead with 1:15
left.
</P>
<P>
   House re-tied the score at 69 from the lane with 47.7 seconds
left. After two timeouts and the rebound of Chris Clayton's 3-point
attempt from the right corner _ a shot similar to the one he missed
near the end of regulation _ A&AMP;M set up the last shot off an
in-bounds with 7.7 seconds to play. Clayton again missed from the
same spot, and the teams went into their second extra 5-minute
period.
</P>
<P>
   The game was tied at 60 at the end of regulation. House knotted
the score with a 3-pointer from the deep right corner with 10
seconds left. A&AMP;M's Clayton tried almost the same shot downcourt,
but missed and Michael Schmidt's left-handed tip bounced off the
rim as time ran out.
</P>
<P>
   ASU had rallied from a 10-point halftime deficit to take a 45-44
lead and stretched that to 53-49 with 4:15 to play. But Cook hit a
three and Clayton scored from the lane to put the Aggies back up
54-53 at 3:38. Cook had two possible chances to ice it. But he made
only one of two free throws with 50 seconds left (59-57) and
followed suit at 23.3 _ making only one for a 60-57 cushion,
enabling ASU to tie on House's clutch shot.
</P>
<P>
   But looking surprisingly crisp despite a 10-day layoff for final
exams, the Aggies led 36-26 at halftime by closing with a 9-2 run
after ASU cut an 11-point lead to 27-24 with 5:51 remaining.
</P>
</TEXT>
