<HEADLINE>
UT-ARLINGTON MEN OVERCOME FOUL WOES FOR VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. _ With foul trouble, second-half
deficits and another loss looming last night for the UT-Arlington
men's basketball team, something different happened.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks battled through it for an 87-78 victory against
Air Force at Clune Arena.
</P>
<P>
   UTA coach Eddie McCarter said his team's first Division I
victory was enough to get excited about, but he was more pleased
with the way the Mavericks did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really needed this one,'' McCarter said. ``The guys fought
through adversity, and it was everybody. I could go down the list,
and everybody stepped up. That's the way we're going to win
basketball games this season.''
</P>
<P>
   UTA (2-5) shot a season-best 61 percent from the field, and
junior forward Bill Washington led four players in double figures
with 24 points and 11 rebounds. Senior point guard Jermaine Johnson
had a season highs with 17 points and six assists.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks erased a 57-50 deficit with a 13-5 run midway
through the second half, and they held off Air Force (5-2) despite
foul trouble the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   UTA, which has eight available scholarship players, had four
players with three fouls by halftime. Washington and Dewayne
Marable picked up their fourth fouls early in the second half.
Marable and Jared Hiple fouled out.
</P>
<P>
   When UTA took a 78-74 lead with 2:12 left, Washington said the
free throws that followed were taken with attitude. The Mavericks
were 8 of 9 down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like Air Force was able to do anything they wanted
inside,'' Washington said. ``Maybe we should be angry like that
from now on when we go to the foul line.
</P>
<P>
   Washington was 10 of 12 from the field and scored 18 of his 24
points in the first half, helping keep the Air Force halftime lead
to 39-35.
</P>
<P>
   A comeback attempt by the Falcons was stopped by consecutive
Keith Greene jumpers to push a four-point lead to 78-70 with two
minutes left. Greene finished with 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team chemistry is what we were lacking, and I think we
found it tonight,'' Johnson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
