</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTUAL-FUND-INVEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READY TO INVEST IN MUTUAL FUNDS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ So you want to start investing this year.
</P>
<P>
   The credit card debt is under control and you're finally
managing to save money. It's time to take the next step: invest for
the future.
</P>
<P>
   One of the easiest ways to start is to buy a mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   A mutual fund is a pool of investors' money managed by a
professional. Investors pay a fee and often a commission, too, to
buy into the fund. Money in the fund is invested as the fund
manager sees fit, within the limits of a strategy outlined in a
document called a prospectus.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual funds can be invested in stocks and bonds, whether
domestic or foreign, money market instruments and other assets.
Many people invest in mutual funds through a retirement plan at
work, such as a 401(k) plan.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a fund veteran, it's good to evaluate your fund
choices to make sure they're meeting your needs. What better time
than the start of the new year?
</P>
<P>
   Here is advice from two experts: Mary Rowland, author of ``The
New Commonsense Guide to Mutual Funds'' who writes a column for
Microsoft's www.moneycentral.com site, and George Shirk, associate
editor of Mutual Funds magazine in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 1: Buy a no-load or no-commission fund. There are plenty
of good funds to choose from that don't charge any commission, so
why pay it?
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have all the money working for you at the get-go,''
Shirk said.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 2: Look for a fund with low expenses and turnover, with a
consistent investment style. Different from loads or commissions,
fund expenses are charged every year as a percentage of your
investment to pay the fund manager, marketing costs and others.
Rowland recommends looking for a fund with a 1 percent or lower
cost.
</P>
<P>
   A low turnover of less than 25percent a year is favorable. It
means the fund manager isn't changing investments in the portfolio
too rapidly _ shifting strategy in a way that will generate a
greater tax burden. You want a manager to be consistent, not to
waffle. For instance, Rowland says that the Vanguard Windsor II
fund has stayed with a consistent strategy for decades.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 3: Don't invest in the hot fund of the moment. Returns are
usually based on short-term performance. Instead, look for
consistent performers that always land in the top 20 percent of
their mutual fund category, Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 4: &UR;  &LR; Spread your money around. Don't buy into only one kind
of fund, but diversify to spread your risk. For instance, Rowland
said investors might want to start with a core index fund, such as
Vanguard Total Market, and supplement it with different funds, such
as international and funds that invest in specific sectors of the
market.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 5: Invest consistently, perhaps weekly, monthly or
quarterly, Shirk said. You'll buy at various prices, instead of
trying to time the lowest point.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 6: Pick a fund that beats its peers. While history doesn't
always repeat itself, a fund that's outperformed its peers over 10
years still is a good bet, given the same manager and investment
style. You want to compare a growth and income fund against the
same type of funds.
</P>
<P>
   Be skeptical of fund ads that tout wonderful returns. It's easy
to manipulate those figures by dropping off a weak month or quarter
in the calculations. Read the prospectus to see the actual
performance.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 7: &UR;  &LR; Index funds rule. In the past five years, only 5
percent of actively managed funds beat the market, Rowland said.
Active funds are those whose managers analyze the market and make
investments accordingly. Index funds are those that automatically
invest in the stocks of a particular index, such as the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 or Wilshire 5000 Index.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 8: &UR;  &LR; Leave a fund if the manager quits, the investment
style shifts or it hasn't performed up to expectations after three
years, Rowland said. But don't jump in and out of funds often.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 9: Forget bond funds unless you're retired or you want to
reduce volatility. If you buy a bond fund, buy a no-load.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 10: Don't blindly follow a tip on the Internet or jump
into a fund because you feel you've been left out of a bull market.
Take your time to do your research. A good source is Morningstar, a
mutual fund publication found at the public library, or on the
Internet at www.morningstar.net.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
