<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-20 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9076 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WATERHAUL-AZR &LR;      12-20 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATERHAUL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATER HAULING A PRACTICE THAT WON'T DRY UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KATHLEEN INGLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Whitley headed his pickup down the pitted dirt road, towing
a 500-gallon fiberglass tank mounted on a trailer. He stopped at an
overhead pipe and fitted one end into his tank. Then he let it rip.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, the tank was full and Whitley flipped off the
switch. He hopped into his truck and returned to his home north of
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Another day, another tank of water.
</P>
<P>
   On the verge of a new century and at the edge of booming
metropolitan Phoenix, hundreds of folks aren't hooked up to a water
system and don't have wells. Instead, they haul water to their
houses.
</P>
<P>
   Whitley has been doing it for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   He can get by with two trips a week in the winter, but he goes
almost daily once the weather heats up.
</P>
<P>
   It's no hardship, Whitley insists, ``it's just a chore, like
taking out the garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   People haul water for the same reason they did a century ago:
They want to live in a rural area that water service hasn't reached
and perhaps never will. Drilling a well is expensive, and in many
parts of Arizona, there's no guarantee of hitting water at a
reasonable depth.
</P>
<P>
   Hauling is the trade-off for putting people where there isn't
any water. And thousands of people across the state are willing to
put up with it.
</P>
<P>
   The Ash Fork area, east of Flagstaff, received all its water by
train until 1975. Now, there's a community well, 1,700 feet deep,
serving both customers on a conventional pipe system and others who
have to haul.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the few successful wells in the area, said Lewis
Hume, manager of the Ash Fork Development Association, the area's
non-profit water company.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, someone went down more than 1,000 feet without any
luck. And with a layer of volcanic rock to go through, ``it's tough
drilling,'' Hume said.
</P>
<P>
   Water hauling isn't limited to Arizona. The American Water Works
Association doesn't keep count, but it's ``a fairly common practice
throughout the country,'' said Dallas Post, who works for the
association.
</P>
<P>
   The local water supply may be full of sulfur, or a farm pump may
freeze in winter.
</P>
<P>
   You can use any kind of tank to haul water: metal, fiberglass,
plastic. Some people go as small as 55-gallon drums. Practically
speaking, it's hard to pull more than 1,000 gallons. As everyone
who hauls water knows, the stuff weighs 8 pounds a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   You load up on water at a standpipe, a tall inverted U of pipe
that's hooked up to a big storage tank.
</P>
<P>
   A few water companies run their standpipes on the honor system,
by which people write down how much they take. Others are
coin-operated. But like almost everything else these days, the
business is going high-tech, and many standpipes take electronic
cards.
</P>
<P>
   Southeast of Phoenix, in Queen Creek, you can get 144 to 160
gallons for a quarter, or use a card for $5 a month, plus $1.75 per
1,000 gallons. Of course, that price doesn't include the wear and
tear of driving back and forth over country roads. And there's
always the danger of a blowout.
</P>
<P>
   That's why John Whitley keeps close watch on the tread on his
tires.
</P>
<P>
   He's fortunate to live just 3{ miles from the standpipe in New
River, in a stretch of desert north of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Once Whitley gets home with a load of water, he hooks up a hose
to the tank and lets gravity transfer the water to his 1,000-gallon
underground storage tank.
</P>
<P>
   The whole routine takes about a half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   To him, it's a small price for living in quiet country with
spectacular views of distant mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The water tastes great, Whitley added. And with a pump and a
pressure tank, the water in his two-story wood home runs no
differently than in the city. The family has a washing machine, a
dishwasher and even an evaporative cooler, a notorious water
guzzler. The property has desert plants and no grass, but Whitley
has trees that get daily drinks in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just turn it on like everyone else,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   But there was one time when he soaped up in the shower just as
the water ran out.
</P>
<P>
   Whitley's water bill runs $35 a month in winter, $60 to $65 in
summer. He figures a well would cost at least $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, there's a brisk business in rural Arizona
hauling water for people who don't want to pick it up themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deliver to people that are in manufactured homes all the way
to people with million-dollar houses,'' Rob Ingram said of his
one-man operation.
</P>
<P>
   He hauls to about 60 regular customers around New River,
charging $45 for a standard 2,000-gallon load.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix, by comparison, charges a basic monthly fee of $5.16 in
the winter, which includes 4,500 gallons of water; above that,
water is $1.06 per 748 gallons.
</P>
<P>
   Ingram's average customer, a family on an acre-plus lot, takes
two loads a month. That's a third less than just one Phoenix
resident uses in a month.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he also has customers with swimming pools and
lawns. He jokingly offers to buy everybody a pony for Christmas.
Horses can drink 30 gallons a day in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Tary Taylor says her two horses polish off even more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Hauling water is part of the daily routine since the Taylor
family moved five years ago from downtown Mesa to southeastern
Maricopa County.
</P>
<P>
   On the way back from picking up her daughter at school, Taylor
stopped at the Queen Creek standpipe to get another 425-gallon
load. The water mains are being extended around Queen Creek, but
her house isn't yet in the path of pipes.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Taylor doesn't even bother to unhook the water
trailer from her truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need milk. Might as well get a load of water,'' she
explained. ``Pick up parts? Get a load of water.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder. She and her husband have four children, plus an
employee living on their property. Then there's the grass she
planted this year because she was tired of the desert look. And, of
course, the horses.
</P>
<P>
   In October, they used 21,000 gallons, ``a lot of hauling,''
Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   When the Queen Creek standpipe was coin-operated, the lines were
endless. Now, there's rarely much of a wait.
</P>
<P>
   The Taylors don't take radical steps to conserve water, although
some haulers go as far as reusing bath water. But they try to hold
down how much they use, such as switching off the shower while
soaping up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I'll treat myself to a full shower,'' Tary Taylor
said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest headache is turning on the hose and forgetting it.
Just that morning, Taylor had stuck the hose into a tree well to
give some flowers there a good soak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forgot, and it was going down the driveway,'' she said
ruefully. ``I probably ran 50 gallons over. You want to kick
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Water hauling may seem like a relic of the pioneer past to city
folks. But Mary Ripplinger, owner of Desert Hills Water Co., said
tartly, ``This is only an amazing thing to those who have never
done it.''
</P>
<P>
   If everyone had to do it for a year, she added, ``we wouldn't
have any water conservation problems.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Kathleen Ingley can be reached at 444-8171, or at
kathleen.ingley &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
