<HEADLINE>
AVENGING BRUINS CUT DOWN RED WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It had only been three days since they had seen each
other. Wednesday night, the Bruins had been in Detroit to face the
Red Wings and the result was a disappointing but not unpredictable
5-3 loss to the two-time defending Stanley Cup champions.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit was deeper, more talented, and on home ice. Saturday
night, with that defeat as a burning source of motivation and
familiarity breeding the kind of contempt that makes for compelling
games, the Bruins dug deep and gutted out a 4-1 victory at the
FleetCenter in the rematch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really special, especially that they beat us in a tough
game a couple of nights ago and it was fresh in our minds,'' said
goalie Byron Dafoe, who had 23 saves. ``They're the Stanley Cup
champions and they're one of the best teams in hockey and it was a
very good test for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston's attack consisted of two power-play goals, a shorthanded
goal, and an empty-netter, all scored after Detroit had taken a 1-0
lead into the first intermission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard-fought battle all the way through, it wasn't
just the special teams that won the game,'' said coach Pat Burns.
``What won the game was the grit that we showed, especially in the
second and third periods. We came out with more emotion and emotion
caused turnovers because we were a little more physical down in
their end.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first period we lacked that a little bit. Our power
play (which finished 2 for 5) is coming to the way we had it
before. We're trying to be less fancy. We're getting the puck at
the net. Detroit's a big team. They can throw speed at you and
skill at you, size at you. They can throw a lot of things at you. A
lot of people maybe don't expect us to win, but if we go out there
with the grit and the emotion, we're going to win. I thought
everybody did a great job tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the Bruins played the Red Wings evenly in the
first period, with both teams generating nine shots. Left wing
Brendan Shanahan put the Wings on the board at 13:27. Center Igor
Larionov attempted a back-door pass from the right-wing side with
Shanahan dashing down the left toward the net. The relay would have
been on target were it not for Bruins defenseman Grant Ledyard. The
puck caromed off Led-yard and went behind the net. Shanahan, who
had four shots in the period, chased it down and, from a position
behind the cage to Dafoe's right, banked it off the netminder and
into the net.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins tied the game midway through the second period on a
shorthanded strike by Chris Taylor. P.J. Axelsson banked the puck
off the boards after a Wings defenseman was caught pinching and
Taylor took off after the loose puck and motored in on the
breakaway, beating goalie Norm Maracle with a wrist shot from the
right circle at 9:06.
</P>
<P>
   Boston took the lead for good with a power-play goal at 18:33.
Jason Allison, at the top of the left circle, dished the puck down
low to Sergei Samsonov. Samsonov, off to Maracle's right, fired the
puck and it went off the netminder's right arm and into the net for
the 2-1 advantage. Ray Bourque picked up his first of three assists
on the score, moving past Gordie Howe into sole possession of third
place on the NHL's all-time list. The three helpers give him 1,052.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins sealed it on the power play at 15:11 of the third.
Detroit center Sergei Fedorov became aggravated with Allison and
cross-checked him to the ice and punched him in the head. To his
surprise, Allison was whistled off for interference and Fedorov got
a double minor for interference and cross-checking, setting the
stage for Darren Van Impe's slapper from the right point that
zipped past Maracle. Anson Carter closed out the scoring with an
empty-netter at 19:07.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just frustrated,'' said Allison of Fedorov. ``I
would've probably hit him if I knew I was getting a penalty. The
reason I didn't was because I thought we were getting a four-minute
power play and there was (5:48) left in the game. If I hit him when
he comes back, I get one and it's even. He came back and I let him
hit me again. I don't know how I got (a penalty). But we scored on
the power play and that was the biggest punishment for him, I
guess. He ruined any chance of his team winning by being stupid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
