<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SAMSONOV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMSONOV HAS KNACK FOR KEY GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He went into Saturday night's game having scored either
the winning or tying goal in four of the Bruins' last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   You can now make that five of the last nine because once again
Sergei Samsonov was the right man in the right place at the right
time.
</P>
<P>
   His second-period goal, in which he threaded the needle to beat
Detroit goaltender Norm Maracle, snapped a 1-1 tie and lifted the
Bruins past the two-time defending Stanley Cup champions, 4-1, at
the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   It came at 18:33 on a power play and Jason Allison and Ray
Bourque drew the assists. Bourque passed the puck from the point to
Allison inside the left circle and he steered it to Samsonov.
</P>
<P>
   Maracle moved across to cut down the angle and Samsonov didn't
have much to shoot at. But he picked his spot and softly lifted the
puck over Maracle and into the near corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to put the puck on the net, I really couldn't see
where I was shooting,'' said Samsonov. ``I knew there wasn't much
of an opening, so I just shot and hoped that it would go in and it
did.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal had some extra meaning for Samsonov because by drawing
the assist, the 1,050th of his career, Bourque moved into third
place ahead of Gordie Howe on the NHL's all-time list. Later,
Samsonov and Bourque teamed up again, this time assisting on a goal
by Darren Van Impe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit of history and it's nice to be a part of
it,'' said Samsonov. ``It's something special. I guess now I can
tease him about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov, who won last year's Calder Trophy as the NHL's top
rookie with 22 goals and 25 assists in 81 games, is ahead of that
pace this season with 11 goals and 17 assists after 29 games. Five
of those goals have been winners.
</P>
<P>
   But Samsonov shrugged off the importance of the goals,
preferring to talk about the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's important, I guess,'' he said. ``But it's just
another goal. I don't know how they count game-winning goals, how
they determine them, but it's a team thing and a team goal, so
they're really not special. There's nothing personal in it. It's
all about team.''
</P>
<P>
   He wanted, also, to talk more about the win, and what it meant
to the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the Stanley Cup champions and it's really nice to get
a win like that, especially at home,'' he said. ``This is probably
going to be good for our confidence and other teams coming in here
will have to look at us a little differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not winning much at home but now we've won two
straight here and it's nice to get those points here. They're
really important to this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we didn't win that much at home, but it looks like
we might be ready to go on a roll. It seems like we're playing a
little better than we were at the beginning of the season. It's
nice to have all the guys back.''
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov may have scored the winner but he thought the tying
goal, a shorthanded tally by Chris Taylor, was the spark that
ignited the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so important, especially coming at the beginning of the
second period,'' Samsonov said. ``It got us going. Obviously, we
had some chances but just couldn't score. We started to be a little
sharper after that. That goal was the key.''
</P>
</TEXT>
