<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA SWATS AWAY CSUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The rumblings began Thursday in the Cal State
Northridge gym, floated east along the 101, turned south over the
Sepulveda pass and _ here's where the Matadors got into trouble _
settled in a certain locker room in Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Matadors guard Jason Crowe called it CSUN's ``best chance'' to
beat the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Higgins predicted it would be ``one of the hardest
games'' of UCLA's season.
</P>
<P>
   And Markus Carr theorized that CSUN and UCLA have ``the same
talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, not close.
</P>
<P>
   Staggering out of exams and pre-dawn practices, the bleary-eye
Bruins awoke in time to slap some sense into the Matadors with a
114-97 victory Saturday night at Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel they can beat us,'' UCLA coach Steve Lavin said
Friday. ``When I watched the tape, they looked really dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I explained to our guys that a majority of (CSUN's) kids are
from Southern California and they would have loved to opportunity
to play at UCLA. Because of that, there's a natural built-in edge
to the underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   That edge lasted just over 10 minutes, as the Matadors matched
UCLA basket-for-basket and grabbed a 25-24 lead with 9:50 remaining
in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (6-2) responded with a devastating 20-0 surge that
spanned 4:26 and ended with a dazzling pass from Baron Davis to Dan
Gadzuric for a three-point play, giving UCLA a 44-25 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' display didn't stop there. In his most effective game
since returning from knee surgery, he slashed through CSUN's
defense time and again, collecting six assists against one turnover
in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors (6-4) played without talented forward Rico Harris,
who missed his fourth consecutive game with a hip pointer. It
showed, as they scored eight points in the final 10 minutes of the
half and shuffled to the locker room with a 24-point deficit.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA shot 64.5 percent in the first half, and most of its
baskets in the 20-0 surge were layups and dunks. CSUN had neither
the size, speed or stamina to stay with the Bruins once they broke
a sweat. The Matadors compounded their problems with horrendous
ballhandling, committing 20 turnovers in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first game in a week for both teams because of exams.
To maintain timing and conditioning, the Bruins practiced at dawn
and held three full-scale scrimmages, complete with uniforms,
timeouts and Pacific-10 officials. Tuesday's practice began at 5
a.m., meaning the Bruins arrived at Pauley Pavilion at 4:15 for
taping and stretching.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found out who the morning guys were,'' Lavin quipped.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was rapidly-improving freshman guard Ray Young, who
played well in practice and finished with 14 points Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a three-game winning streak, Lavin had a plethora of
problems to address. Against Nevada-Las Vegas, for instance, UCLA
played well for the first five minutes and again for the final 13.
In between, the Bruins struggled with impatience, court balance and
transition defense. They took too many quick shots and gave the
Runnin' Rebels too many easy baskets.
</P>
<P>
   The scrimmages failed to correct the problem, as the Bruins
played passively and allowed CSUN to score at will in the opening
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Larry and Jeff Paris took turns dunking over UCLA freshmen
Dan Gadzuric and Jerome Moiso, surprising the Bruins and silencing
the crowd. When Greg Minor drained back-to-back 3-pointers from the
818 area code, UCLA's lead had dwindled to 18-16.
</P>
<P>
   The teams exchanged baskets for several minutes, until Brian
Heinle's 10-foot leaner gave CSUN its 25-24 lead. Two minutes
later, the game was over.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Watson started the blitz with a crisp bounce pass to Travis
Reed for a layup. A minute later, reserve Ryan Bailey sliced
through the appropriately-named Matadors for an uncontested layup.
JaRon Rush buried a 3-pointer from the right corner, and Bailey
teamed with Gadzuric for a nifty give-and-go layup.
</P>
<P>
   By the time CSUN coach Bobby Braswell called timeout, UCLA had a
37-25 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
