<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEASON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUGHTERS OF MIGRANT WORKERS GET TASTE OF SCOUTING
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KARINA BLAND  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AGUILA, Ariz. _ At one of Brownie Troop 2285's first meetings,
troop leader Barbara Smith tried teaching the girls how to play red
light-green light, a child's game where players run when the leader
shouts, ``Green light!'' and stop at the call of ``Red light!''
</P>
<P>
   But they ran when she called ``Red light!'' and stopped for the
green. Smith was perplexed by their confused faces until she
realized that the girls, mostly the daughters of Mexican farming
workers, had never seen a traffic light.
</P>
<P>
   There's not one traffic light in this small rural community of
about 600 people. There's no Circle K, department store or even a
movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   But, for the first time, there is a Brownie Troop, a program of
the Girl Scouts of America for girls ages 6 to 8, though here in
Aguila there are some 9-year-olds in the troop.
</P>
<P>
   Smith moved to Aguila _ an hour and a half drive northwest of
metro Phoenix, just past Wicken burg _ with her husband, Harry, a
pilot for Continental Airlines, and young daughter about four years
ago. The family, which now in cludes 2-year-old Michael, owns and
runs Sampley Airport, a dusty landing strip and hangar.
</P>
<P>
   Until a year ago, Barbara Smith drove Heather, now 7, to Wicken
burg _ about a half-hour each way _ for weekly Brownie meetings and
events. She decided to start her own troop closer to home, figuring
there would be plenty of little girls from the nearby school who
would be interested in joining.
</P>
<P>
   But a majority of the girls are first-generation Americans.
Their parents were not familiar with Girl Scouting, and newfangled
ideas _ though Girl Scouting dates back to 1912 _ are regarded with
some suspicion in Aguila.
</P>
<P>
   Smith doesn't speak Spanish, so the troop got off to a slow
start with three or four girls showing up each week. Smith sent
Heather to school in full uniform to drum up interest.
</P>
<P>
   She recruited Nena Gutierrez as her co-leader, and Gutierrez,
who speaks Spanish, won over reluctant mothers. Now, the troop is
14 girls strong, and there is a waiting list long enough to make up
another troop.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1997, a national study assessing the effect of Girl
Scouting on girls' lives reported that the longer a girl stays in
Scouting, the less likely she is to fail at school, abuse drugs or
alcohol, or commit juvenile crime.
</P>
<P>
   Eagle Produce, Aguila's major employer, donated $500 for the
troop to buy Brownie uniforms. Instead, they bought material, and
the Wickenburg chapter of the American Sewing Guild and the Tuesday
morning sewing class at the Youngstown Arizona Discount Sew and Vac
made their brown skirts and vests.
</P>
<P>
   There was enough money left over to buy start-up materials such
as Girl Scout handbooks and scis sors, construction paper and glue
for craft projects. Still, the girls share scissors and even
pencils.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent meeting, the girls were making Christmas candles out
of empty toilet paper rolls. Con struction paper and girls spread
out over the cement floor of Smith's workroom.
</P>
<P>
   Heather is the only native English speaker, but she fares well
in both languages. The other girls speak both English and Spanish,
and they all talk at once as they eat an afternoon snack of
pudding, fruit and hot chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Their vests are spotted with badges.
</P>
<P>
   There are no dues, though many troops do collect weekly fees
rang ing from 50 cents to a few dollars. Smith didn't want cost to
keep any of the girls from joining.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, they would be attending a free puppet show in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much for little girls to do here, and they need to
have exposure to things outside of little Aguila,'' Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the families own cars, so Smith, Gutierrez and another
mother pick up the girls after school using two station wagons and
a truck. They take them home after ward.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the girls live in houses; the rest live in trailers.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than making the rounds in town, the troop went to Sun
City _ an hour and a half away _ and sold Girl Scout cookies
outside a grocery store there every weekend for five weeks. They
made $200.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we spent more on gas,'' Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   She took a handful of the girls to Arrowhead Mall while they
were in the city to pick up more supplies, again not realizing this
was a big adventure to children who thought Wickenburg was a
metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   For Leslie Herrera, 8, it was the first time she ever rode on an
elevator. She watched the glass contraption go up and down a few
times before venturing onto it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would break, and I would be hanging from up
there,'' Leslie says.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother is pleased that she joined the troop, she says,
adding, ``She thinks Brownies are better than staying home and
seeing the television.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie says she likes being a Brownie, going camping for the
first time and roller skating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody fell down like 100 times,'' she says, laughing. ``I
just fell down two or three times.''
</P>
<P>
   She has a badge to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the troop went to camp in Prescott, sleeping in
cabins and building fires and cooking their dinner outside. It was
a first for almost all of the girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so fun,'' Sarai Diaz, 8, says.
</P>
<P>
   On the way back to Aguila, it started to snow, another first for
Diaz and many of the other girls. They stopped at a rest area and
made snowballs, pelting one an other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really neat when you are there for one of their firsts,''
Smith says. &QL; 
 &UR; Karina Bland can be reached at 444-8614,
 &UR; or at karina.bland &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
