<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT PROCESS AGAINST CLINTON FAIR, JUST
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The following editorial appeared in Sunday's Arizona Republic: &HT;     
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Saturday's vote in the House, William Jefferson Clinton is
now only the second president in this nation's history to be
impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who as a youth dreamed of becoming president and
leaving a legacy of greatness, now occupies a lowly place in
history. His name will forever be linked with impeach ment.
</P>
<P>
   But this ignominious chapter is not yet closed. The president
could be convicted and removed from office by the Senate, action
that would be unprecedented in Ameri can history.
</P>
<P>
   This is an occasion of sadness, but one whose momentousness is
still not felt or realized by many Americans. Even the president
seemed to go about his business Saturday as the House adopted two
of four articles of impeachment, finding that Clinton obstructed
jus tice and lied under oath about his sexual affair with White
House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The sharply partisan vote, Rep. Bob Livingston's surprise
resigna tion as speaker-to-be over extramari tal affairs and
anguished questions over the timing of military attacks on Iraq
have left many wondering just how we got to this painful juncture.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the blame rests with Clinton. His actions shaped his
fate. The president violated his oath of office and misled the
American people. Clinton's efforts to conceal his affair with
Lewinsky began in January, but his downfall began many years ago
with his penchant for deceit.
</P>
<P>
   We will leave it to historians and others to sort out the roots
of Clinton's personal failings. Our con cern is with the future.
Now what? Where do we go?
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to take up Clinton's case in early
January. The matter could be disposed of quickly, with a reprimand
or censure, or the trial could last for months.
</P>
<P>
   We pray for the former.
</P>
<P>
   Both political parties and the country want to get this over
with. But for that to happen, the president must separate himself
from the highly partisan remarks of Demo crats like House Minority
Leader Richard Gephardt, who railed Satur day against Republicans
and de clared that the ``politics of smear and slash and burn must
end.''
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, surrounded by Democratic supporters, Clinton
also portrayed the matter as one of Republicans vs. Democrats and
called for an end to the ``politics of destruction'' and the
``poisonous venom of excessive partisanship.'' That may play to the
Democratic faithful, but Clinton must drop the attacks and fully
acknowledge his wrongdoing if he expects Senate Republicans to show
mercy and resolve this in an expeditious man ner.
</P>
<P>
   We agree with the president that there is important work to
tackle over the next two years, including saving Medicare and
Social Secu rity, improving our schools, ensuring a strong economy
and maintaining America's military might.
</P>
<P>
   We did not join the chorus of newspapers that months ago called
for Clinton's resignation or ouster. We see no reason to do so now,
believing that the process we are embarked on is fair and just. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
