<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CSUNSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH EXILE OVER, CSUN'S WELCH GETS TO PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jermar Welch remembers the loneliness and the
self-pity.
</P>
<P>
   His memory of sitting inside the midcourt circle, alone, is
still vivid. Even a 1,600-seat gym like Cal State Northridge's can
be eerie when it's 8 p.m. and no one else is around.
</P>
<P>
   It was hours after coach Bobby Braswell's yelling stopped, and
long after every Matador left the practice. The silence broken only
by the `thud' of the ball pounding the court.
</P>
<P>
   It was Welch's punishment for being a nonqualifier out of Canyon
Springs High, and those traumas cost him 1{ years of basketball.
For that, the stinging will never end. Even as of late Friday he
was awaiting word of his sociology final, a test he was certain he
passed though he tortured himself nonetheless because he feared the
worst.
</P>
<P>
   His grade was fine, though his game a bit rusty. However, he
played Saturday against No. 12 UCLA. He finally played.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't seem like this was ever going to get here,'' Welch
said. ``I missed the intensity. That's the part I missed the most.
It's been such a long time, and I made it longer on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Welch, an architecture major, was expecting to be eligible at
the beginning of this season. But he lapsed during the spring
semester and his grade-point average dipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being ineligible because of grades, that's hard,'' Welch said.
``Everybody looks at you. But I'm more confident in myself now.''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, it's been nearly 20 months since Welch played a
game, so it'll take time to understand what type of impact he'll
have on CSUN. Or whether he'll have one.
</P>
<P>
   However, he's perhaps the Matadors' most athletic player on what
is tabbed as CSUN's most athletic team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so doggone athletic and such a great rebounder,''
Braswell said. ``There's a lot of things he still doesn't know, and
he doesn't know all of our plays. It's going to be nice to have an
extra post body, and he runs like a deer. He runs as well as
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   That oversimplifies what the Matadors expect from Welch, and
what he offers.
</P>
<P>
   In CSUN's helter-skelter defensive style, Welch's athleticism
should help. Offensively, he can shoot the jumper and slash to the
basket. As a senior at Canyon Springs, Welch averaged 14 points
10.2 rebounds per game.
</P>
<P>
   The rebounding is particularly important considering power
forward Rico Harris missed his fourth consecutive game with a hip
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings so much because of his size and how athletic he
is,'' CSUN guard Jason Crowe said. ``He can bang and he's a strong
kid. That's going to help our rebounding. I believe he makes us a
much better team, especially after he gets a few games
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Which works perfectly for CSUN. While the UCLA game served as an
opportunity to gain community respect, the more important aspect is
for Welch to get ready for the Big Sky Conference season, which
begins Jan. 2 at Northern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can play, but I have to put it all together,'' Welch
said. ``I didn't get to practice at all last year, and with limited
practice this year I know it's going to take time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
