<SLUG> BC-GEN-VOLLEYBALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG BEACH CAPS PERFECT SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Wis. _ Call it the perfect ending to a perfect season.
Can you say 36-0?
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most dramaticamazing
</P>
<P>
   NCAA Division I volleyball championship matches ever, Long Beach
State went the distance Saturday to culminate a perfect season and
become the first national championship team to go undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a 2-0 lead in the match, the top-seeded 49ers
rallied from an 8-4 deficit in the rally-scoring fifth game to
defeat No. 2 seed Penn State, 15-3, 15-10, 13-15, 14-16, 15-12, in
the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-six and 0, the first NCAA undefeated team the best team
in my 14 years I've seen play volleyball,'' Long Beach coach Brian
Gimmillaro said. ``It was a glorious moment to see that ball go
down and the pure joy of the team. I jumped up there with them and
the joy in their eyes and their faces, it was really great. One of
the other things about volleyball is it happens suddenly. The clock
is running out, it's that last point. It's really an incredible
feeling that you go through when that last ball goes down.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for the 150 or so Long Beach fans who came along to
witness the end of a spectacular season, the 49ers silenced the
pro-Big 10 Conference, NCAA-record crowd of 13,194 at Kohl Center,
just like it did here in 1993 when it defeated the Nittany Lions in
the championship at the old University of Wisconsin Field House.
The 49ers also won the NCAA title in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Junior outside hitter Veronica Walls played the match of her
life, leading all 49ers with a career-high 19 kills and five
blocks.
</P>
<P>
   With two-time1998
</P>
<P>
   National Player of the Year Misty May serving match point, Walls
got the set from May right of center net and sent an off-speed shot
into an open right corner of the Nittany Lions' court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the opening,'' said Walls, who hit .455. ``I didn't hit
it really hard, but I saw the opening and I hit it to the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it was time to celebrate, at least for the 49ers, who piled
on one another in the customary fashion teams do when they win
championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd was certainly a Big 10 crowd, which it should be,''
Gimmillaro said. ``I'm very excited they got a good show to see.
For our players to win under these circumstances is great.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first two games, the 49ers completely dominated Penn
State. Then they fought back from two consecutive game losses to
rally from four-point deficits twice in Game 5, in which points are
scored on each serve. They hit a whopping .556 in that game,
committing only one hitting error on 18 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   It was an incredible comeback for the 49ers, who outplayed the
Nittany Lions, while dealing them their first defeat in 36 matches.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers, ranked second in the nation in hitting percentage
behind Penn State, outhit the Nittany Lions, .328 to .166,
outblocked a supposedly better blocking team, 15 to 12, and outdug
them, 82-60. The 49ers had 17 more kills than Penn State and 10
less attack errors.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't a done deal until Walls' final hit.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State made a valiant comeback to force the fifth and
deciding game. Lauren Cacciamani, who had a match-high 33 kills,
took the match into her own hands and nearly succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions and took a 10-5 lead in the third game and
held off the 49ers' late surge. In Game 4, Cacciamani had 11 kills
to pace Penn State. The score was tied, 14-14, when Carrie
Schonveld and Emily Stout combined to block Benishe Dillard to make
it 15-14 and, four sideouts later, Lindsay Anderson solo-blocked
Anja Grabovac for game point.
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions went up 6-2 and then 8-4 in Game 5 before the
momentum shifted back to the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach benefited from Anderson's attack error, then Jessica
Alvarado served three unanswered points to tie the score, 8-8.
</P>
<P>
   The score stayed close until the 49ers took their first lead on
a kill by Dillard. After Cacciamani tied the score for the fifth
time, the 49ers took the lead for good on a kill by Alvarado, who
followed up with another one to give Long Beach a two-point lead,
one point away from match point.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State called a timeout to try to slow the 49ers' momentum,
but it was too late as Walls ended the match with her 19th kill.
</P>
<P>
   It was an especially sweet victory for the three 49er seniors
who didn't want their careers to end without a championship ring.
Losing to Stanford in a national semifinal last year, of course,
was all the motivation May, Alvarado and Dillard needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming in as a freshman, it's always been our goal to win,''
said Dillard, who had 16 kills. ``We expected it but didn't know
when it was going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely learned a lot from last year,'' said May, who
finished with nine kills, 11 digs, and 70 assists. ``The feeling is
flipped around. We're on the winning side now. I knew we would do
it, but we just didn't know when. This was our year.''
</P>
<P>
   That last line unofficially served as the 49ers' motto this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set lofty goals in the beginning,'' said Alvarado. ``We
wanted to go 36-0. That was our goal and we attained that goal and
I don't think it's hit home yet. It's going to take a little time.
But this is what we set out to do... and we've done it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
