<SLUG> BC-BKC-ASU-TEXASA&AMP;M-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN DEVILS THRILLED BATISTE MADE TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ No wonder Mike Batiste couldn't wait to
play.
</P>
<P>
   In a game for the ages, Arizona State beat Texas A&AMP;M, 96-91, in
triple overtime Saturday night, just the second three-overtime game
in school history.
</P>
<P>
   And Batiste was there. He took a plane, a car and a bus, but it
didn't matter. He would have run, walked or crawled to Reed Arena
if he had to.
</P>
<P>
   Batiste, academically ineligible for the first eight games of
the season, left Tempe in the morning and was in the starting
lineup. The 6-foot-8 forward scored 23 points and had 18 rebounds
in 50 minutes. But the real hero was junior guard Eddie House, who
scored 34 points, 31 after halftime and 11 in the third OT. He tied
the score in regulation. He sent the game into the second and third
overtimes. Then he broke an 86-86 tie with a three-pointer with 47
seconds left after ASU blew a nine-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   House's resurgence was due to ``not wanting to lose the
ballgame,'' he said. ``We prepared so hard and we wanted to come in
and make history because Texas A&AMP;M hadn't lost at their new
arena.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies were 5-0 at Reed, a 12,500-seat arena completed in
April.
</P>
<P>
   House, who played 53 minutes, said he didn't think he was
playing hard enough in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't competing,'' he said. ``I was lagging a little on
defense. Coach (Rob Evans) talked to me about it at halftime. I
thought I picked up my defense in the second half and the offense
came easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Batiste, meanwhile, surmounted deficiencies that threatened to
wipe out his senior season at ASU and got the necessary grades in
all six of his courses _ 18 credit hours _ during the fall
semester. In summer school, he had taken 12 hours. Batiste's last
final exam, in a justice class, was Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Batiste waited all day Friday in Tempe but heard nothing. The
team left without him. Finally, at about 11 a.m. Saturday, he got
the call. The grade was officially posted, and he was eligible.
Coaches found Batiste a flight to Austin, where assistant Dan
O'Dowd met him for the drive to the team hotel. They arrived at 6
p.m., 2{ hours before the game.
</P>
<P>
   A short bus ride to the arena later, Batiste had reached the
destination he had been thinking about since last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when I slept (Friday night), I was thinking about it,''
he said. ``I got up at 7 a.m. and I just waited. When the call
came, I was so relieved.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the only one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good for Mike,'' said Evans, who interviewed for the
A&AMP;M job when it was vacant and thought he might get it. ``The kid
did everything he said he was going to do to rectify the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU (5-4) came out looking like a team that hadn't played in 11
days while trying to fit somebody new in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Batiste missed his first two shots and tumbled over the press
table chasing a loose ball. Then he got hot. He scored 11 of ASU's
next 13 points, and when House hit a three-pointer, the Sun Devils
trailed, 29-26, with 4:43 left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the last points of the half for ASU. Texas A&AMP;M (7-2)
scored seven straight to take a 36-26 lead into halftime. Aggies
Coach Melvin Watkins, waging a battle with Pac-10 officials Charlie
Range and Terry Christman, was hit with a technical foul as the
teams left the court.
</P>
<P>
   House made one of two free throws on the technical to start the
second half. Keyed by its defense, ASU went on an 18-5 run to take
a 45-43 lead with 7:58 to go.
</P>
<P>
   ASU went up by four on three occasions, but it went no further
than that, and the Aggies took a 54-53 lead with 3:28 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   A shot clock violation gave the Aggies the ball and Shanne Jones
scored to make the score 56-53. But House scrambled for a loose
ball and scored to get ASU within one with 2:04 to go. Then it was
Jones again, inside, for a three-point A&AMP;M lead. Lazor's put-back
made it 58-57, Aggies, with 58 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Cook made one of two free throws and A&AMP;M led by two with 50
seconds remaining. Alton Mason missed on a leaner in the lane with
30 seconds to go and Cook made one of two free throws. The Aggies
led by three, but House drilled a three-pointer with 10 seconds to
go and it was 60-60. A&AMP;M missed two chances to win and the game
went into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   House's basket with 47 seconds left in the first overtime tied
the score at 69 and Clayton missed a pair of three-pointers,
setting up a second extra period.
</P>
<P>
   And it was House again, hitting a three-pointer with seven
seconds left to create a third overtime. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
