</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA ROUTS CSUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jason Crowe's comment originated in the Cal State
Northridge gym Thursday afternoon, floated east along the 101,
turned south over the Sepulveda Pass and _ here's where he found
trouble _ settled in a certain Westwood locker room Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our best chance to beat UCLA,'' said Crowe, a CSUN guard
and Inglewood native. ``We feel we're just as talented as they
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruins coach Steve Lavin, searching for every morsel of
motivation after a tough week of final exams and pre-dawn
practices, immediately informed his players of the comment.
</P>
<P>
   They did not take it well. Not well at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us know Jason, and we took it personally,'' UCLA
guard Rico Hines said. ``We wanted to jump on them early to prove a
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Travis Reed was more succinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a slap in our face,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 12 Bruins responded by slapping the Matadors around with
a 114-97 victory Saturday in front of 8,584 at Pauley Pavilion, a
game more lopsided than the score indicated. UCLA held a 33-point
lead with 2:32 remaining before a late CSUN rally made the final
margin respectable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very, very poor showing for our program,'' said
Matadors coach Bobby Braswell, whose team committed 20 turnovers in
the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin was just as upset and spent his postgame oxygen yelling at
his reserves, who played well for much of the game but lapsed in
the closing minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Lavin had little to complain about. The Bruins
trailed 25-24 with 9:50 remaining in the first half, then unleashed
a devastating 20-0 surge that broke the game open. It spanned
nearly five minutes and ended with a dazzling pass from guard Baron
Davis to center Dan Gadzuric for a 44-25 lead that quieted the
mouthy Matadors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I was mad at Jason Crowe,'' said Reed, who scored a
career-high 21 points. ``I don't want to get into any of that
stuff, but we were mad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors (6-4) played without talented forward Rico Harris,
who missed his fourth consecutive game with a hip pointer. It
showed, as they scored just eight points in the final 10 minutes of
the first half and shuffled to the locker room with a 24-point
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it not becoming a track meet by taking bad
shots,'' Braswell said. ``Then we took bad shots.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, UCLA shot 65.2 percent from the field _ most of its
baskets in the 20-0 surge were layups and dunks _ and 53.8 percent
from 3-point range. CSUN had neither the size, speed nor stamina to
stay with the Bruins once they broke a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Seven Bruins scored in double figures, but Davis and freshman
guard Ray Young made the greatest impressions. In his most
effective game since returning from knee surgery, Davis slashed and
dashed through CSUN's defense time and again, tying his career-high
with nine assists against two turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   The rapidly improving Young scored a career-high 14 points and
credited his play, in part, to Lavin's pre-dawn practices.
Tuesday's workout began at 5 a.m., meaning the Bruins arrived at
Pauley Pavilion at 4:15 for taping and stretching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind it,'' Young said. ``It's better to know that by 8
a.m. you have your whole day to go to class, study and sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   To maintain timing and conditioning during exams, the Bruins
held three full-scale scrimmages, complete with uniforms, timeouts
and Pacific-10 officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three (scrimmages) we played this week carried over to
tonight,'' Lavin said. ``It's something I'm going to do for my
whole career. Now we've basically played five games in seven
days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (6-2) needed a few minutes to adjust to playing after
breakfast and allowed CSUN to score at will in the opening minutes.
Andre Larry and Jeff Paris dunked over Gadzuric and Jerome Moiso,
respectively, and when Greg Minor drained back-to-back 3-pointers,
UCLA's lead was 18-16.
</P>
<P>
   The teams exchanged baskets for several minutes until Brian
Heinle's 10-foot leaner gave CSUN its 25-24 lead. Two minutes
later, the game was over.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Watson started the blitz with a crisp bounce pass to Reed
for a layup. A minute later, reserve Ryan Bailey sliced through the
appropriately-named Matadors for an uncontested layup. JaRon Rush
buried a 3-pointer from the right corner, and Bailey teamed with
Gadzuric for a nifty give-and-go layup.
</P>
<P>
   By the time CSUN coach Bobby Braswell called timeout, UCLA had a
37-25 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
