<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CSUNSIDE-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATADORS MUST EAT THEIR WORDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: New lead) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cal State Northridge players talked the past few
days about having as much talent as UCLA, which the Bruins used as
bulletin-board material.
</P>
<P>
   Not even a lopsided loss could make CSUN rethink those thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the ease in which UCLA repeatedly and embarrassingly
undermined the Matadors' defense would change CSUN's mind. None of
that held any bearing.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the wake of the 12th-ranked Bruins' 114-97 throttling of
CSUN at Pauley Pavilion on Saturday, the Matadors continued to say
things would be different if the teams met again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't affect anything,'' CSUN point guard Markus Carr
said. ``We still believe that if we got another chance to get
ourselves together and keep our focus, it would be a better game
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The one person who did take a different stance was CSUN coach
Bobby Braswell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious I didn't have this team prepared to play this
game,'' Braswell said. ``I take responsibility. There's a reason
UCLA is ranked where they are, because they're a very good
basketball team. I think our guys took that for granted, and that's
my responsibility, my fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had a chance to at least make this thing
competitive and we didn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The carnage was masked only by the Matadors (6-4) scoring 20
points in the final 2:21. It made the final gaudy instead of
obscene, but that matters not at all.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a benchmark victory that would give the program fame,
as the Matadors had talked about, CSUN experienced a meltdown that
will most likely make the next two days of practice hellish.
</P>
<P>
   And keep the Matadors an afterthought on the Los Angeles sports
scene.
</P>
<P>
   But the non-preparedness speaks more of what happened 10 minutes
into the game rather than the pregame, because CSUN held a 25-24
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Matadors defense became literal. An ole' here, an ole'
there. Transition defense didn't exist and UCLA put up 20 straight
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost our enthusiasm and intensity and will to play
defense,'' Matadors forward Jeff Parris said. ``We lost our will.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't be fooled. CSUN lost a lot more. Like an opportunity to be
considered more than an early-season throw-away game for the
Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN may have juniors and seniors on its roster, but it proved
it's still a young team; there are seven first-year Matadors. And
CSUN also proved its immaturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't take us out of focus. We took ourselves out of
focus,'' Carr said. ``We took quick shots, didn't play our pressure
defense and we let them get easy buckets. We have to maintain our
focus through that and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN won't get another chance to earn respectability by beating,
or even being competitive with, UCLA for a few seasons. The two
teams aren't expected to meet again until the 2000 season. And it
just so happens the Bruins figure to be loaded then, with most of
its now-freshman talent set to be juniors.
</P>
<P>
   And when the time comes, perhaps CSUN should downplay any such
future meeting with the Bruins.
</P>
</TEXT>
