</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORSDOEUVRES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Party from the Pantry
 &HT;    WITH PANTRY-TIPS
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Well, hey there!'' you beam as the unexpected arrivals
show up at the door.
</P>
<P>
   They're in town for the holidays. They wanted to bring by a
little gift. They hope it's not an inconvenient time.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no! Of course not! C'mon in,'' you beckon. You grab their
coats. You pour a glass of wine. You put on a pot of tea.
</P>
<P>
   They spy the bowl of holiday nuts on your coffee table. They
look vainly for a nutcracker. They don't find one. They don't know
the nuts have been there since Christmas 1996.
</P>
<P>
   You offer to get some cheese and crackers. You run to the
kitchen. You don't have crackers. You find a block of unwrapped
cheddar as cracked and creviced as desert clay.
</P>
<P>
   They drain their wineglasses. They shift in their seats. They
crack open your coffee-table book.
</P>
<P>
   You go on a tear through the fridge. You locate capers,
mayonnaise and a bowl of clam dip that's still there?? You think
about scraping the crusty top off. You decide against it.
</P>
<P>
   But then suddenly you recall a few simple tricks. Roasting
olives with dried rosemary. Thawing tortellini to dip in a quickly
made pesto.
</P>
<P>
   There are other nifty ideas as well. Onion toasts made with
sandwich bread and mayo. Parmesan cheese crisps. Baked artichoke
balls. With a few everyday ingredients in the pantry, you can feed
drop-in guests in style.
</P>
<P>
   As you get started, they wander into the kitchen. They bring
their empty wineglasses. They offer to help.
</P>
<P>
   You say, ``Let's have another glass in the kitchen,'' and offer
them a seat at the counter. You say you're just going to throw
together a few nibbles. Little do they know.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
