</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANTRY-TIPS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Instant hors d'oeuvres
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   STUFFED DATES: Pitted dates can be stuffed with cream cheese, or
most any other kind of cheese _ a good way to use up leftover bits
of cheese. They also can be stuffed with most any kind of nut.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD STICKS: Wrap with slices of salami or prosciutto.
</P>
<P>
   BITE-SIZE ROASTED VEGETABLES: Arrange on a platter and sprinkle
with a variety of olives.
</P>
<P>
   LEFTOVER CHEESE: Combine bits of compatible cheese in a food
processor. Add a little cream and process until smooth. Stir in
some chopped nuts, if desired. Use as a spread for crackers or
place a little dollop on slices of red pepper or apples.
</P>
<P>
   LEFTOVER BREAD: Slice bread thinly and cut into approximately 2-
to 3-inch pieces. Brush with olive oil and bake until barely crisp.
Spread with bottled olive or artichoke paste or tomato or basil
pesto. Always be generous with the bread, it stretches out whatever
else you serve. Or serve baskets of bread with bowls of flavored
olive oils for dunking. Garnish with a sprig of whatever the oil is
flavored with.
</P>
<P>
   LEFTOVER TURKEY: Arrange slices in a deep platter. Combine olive
oil, lemon juice, chopped basil and a little garlic. Pour over the
turkey slices. Cover and refrigerate for a couple of hours.
</P>
<P>
   HUMMUS: Surround a small bowl of hummus with a
Mediterranean-style cocktail buffet of olives and other pickled
foods.
</P>
<P>
   LEFTOVER HAM: Combine ham with some celery and onion in a food
processor. Stir in a little chopped parsley and sweet pickle relish
and black pepper to taste. Serve with crackers or slices of
baguette.
</P>
<P>
   SPICED NUTS: Toss nuts with butter, sugar, cinnamon and cayenne
pepper. Bake until lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   ARUGULA: Wrap around smoked mussels, clams or oysters.
</P>
<P>
   BOILED EGGS: Cover while still warm with the juice from a jar of
pickled beets. Let stand in the refrigerator overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
