<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-20 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9157 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     12-20 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 27)  
(lb) 
 By SCOTT VEALE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; CASANOVA: THE MAN WHO REALLY LOVED WOMEN &LR;  By Lydia Flem.
Translated by Catherine Temerson. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $13. A
Belgian scholar argues that Casanova was far more than a sexual
athlete _ in his high-spirited virtuosity he was the embodiment of
the Enlightenment. ``Perpetually captivated by Casanova, as lover,
adventurer or wanderer, Flem makes us determined to seek out his
company,'' Jonathan Keates wrote in The New York Times Book Review
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PFITZ &LR;  By Andrew Crumey. Picador USA, $12. In this slender
novel, an 18th-century German prince mobilizes the collective
mental powers of his subjects to create an elaborate imaginary
city. Unfortunately, reality creeps into his vision of aesthetic
purity, in the form of a young cartographer who falls in love with
another worker. ```Pfitz' is a surprisingly warm and likable book,
a combination of intellectual high-wire act and good traditional
storytelling,'' Andrew Miller wrote in 1997. The author ``develops
his story with admirable rigor, seizing on both the comic and the
philosophical potential of a world in which the actual and the
imagined have become fatally blurred.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TAKING WING: ARCHAEOPTERYX AND THE EVOLUTION OF BIRD FLIGHT &LR;  By
Pat Shipman. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $15. When the fossilized
skeleton of a prehistoric creature that was half bird and half
reptile was discovered in Bavaria in 1861, it touched off a
long-running debate about the dinosaurian ancestry of birds. The
author of this account makes a strong case for such a link.
``Shipman brings to her excellent book the authority of a
paleontologist and the talent of an accomplished writer on science
for popular audiences,'' John Noble Wilford wrote earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFTER MAN: A ZOOLOGY OF THE FUTURE &LR;  By Dougal Dixon. St.
Martin's Griffin, $15.95. This envisions the species on earth 50
million years from now, like the vortex, a giant whalelike creature
descended from penguins. In 1982 in The New York Times Book Review,
Timothy Ferris found this illustrated book full of ``endearing and
plausible specimens'' that ``engender reflection about the
mysterious forces at work beneath the skin of real animals.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PANTHER IN THE BASEMENT &LR;  By Amos Oz. Translated by Nicholas de
Lange. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $11. A patriotic boy is accused of
treason after befriending a gentle British soldier in Jerusalem
just before Britain's departure from Palestine in 1947. In 1997 Lee
Siegel called this ``an insightful, inventive and lyrical'' novel
that uses ``the theme of betrayal to explore the status of the
individual in a country where public and private landscapes are
constantly merging.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FAR EUPHRATES &LR; . By Aryeh Lev Stollman, Riverhead, $13. A
first novel about a lonely rabbi's son growing up in Ontario during
the 1950s and '60s and the extended family of troubled adults
around him. ```The Far Euphrates' is remarkable both for Stollman's
eloquently understated prose and for the ease with which he
constructs his artful plot,'' Margot Livesey wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SEA OF TREES &LR;  By Yannick Murphy. Mariner/Houghton Mifflin,
$12. Set in Indochina during the 1940s, this first novel is
narrated by a girl who comes of age in a Japanese internment camp
and in postwar Saigon. ``Her story unfolds through a dreamlike
progression of glinting surfaces, telling gestures and precisely
rendered moments, in which matter-of-fact horror butts up against
absurdist hilarity,'' Catherine Bush wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AT RISK &LR;  By Alice Hoffman. Berkley, $13. A middle-class
family's comfortable world is shaken to the core when their
11-year-old daughter contracts AIDS from a blood transfusion. ``In
its simplicity and directness and restraint there is very often a
compelling power'' to this novel, Jim Shepard said in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GERSHWIN &LR;  By Edward Jablonski. Da Capo, $17.95. The author
maintains that the brash optimism of George Gershwin's music was
emblematic of a vibrant young America rising to its potential in
the arts and business. In 1987 the reviewer Francis Davis said this
biography features ``a wealth of pertinent detail and fresh
musicological insight.'' The same publisher has reissued  &UR; THE
COMPLETE LYRICS OF IRA GERSHWIN &LR; , edited by Robert Kimball ($35),
which tracks the artistic growth of George's older brother and his
search for fresh ways to avoid cliches. In 1993 Sheldon Harnick
said this book should be ``in the home of everyone who has an
interest in the art of the musical theater.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EMPIRE OF LIGHT: A HISTORY OF DISCOVERY IN SCIENCE AND ART &LR;  By
Sidney Perkowitz. Joseph Henry, $16.95. A physics professor
explores the nature of light and the complex human responses to it,
as well as various theories of the phenomenon through the ages. In
1996 one critic called this a ``smoothly written, comprehensive and
thoroughly enjoyable'' overview written with ``a fine awareness of
light's appeal to our aesthetic senses.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SKULL SESSION &LR;  By Daniel Hecht. Signet, $6.99. An out-of-work
teacher with Tourette's syndrome, hired to fix up a vandalized
Hudson Valley estate, finds that the damage may be linked to some
missing high school students. This is ``an accomplished first novel
... that keeps the reader guessing till the very end,'' Charles
Salzberg wrote this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
