<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-20 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9190 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSPAPER-FINANCES-ME     12-20 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-FINANCES-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSROOMS LITTLE AFFECTED BY CUTS AT PAPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Iowa, N.Y.)  (mk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The financial news bulletins from the newspaper industry since
the summer have had a depressingly familiar ring to journalists who
lived through the brutal advertising recession of the early 1990s
or the run-up in newsprint prices three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since September, staff reductions have been announced at The
Wall Street Journal, at The Dallas Morning News and twice over at
The Los Angeles Times. From midsummer on, advertising revenue was
down unexpectedly in markets like Boston, Dallas, Los Angeles and
San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago _ even three years ago _ bulletins like these sent
shivers through newsroom executives, many of whom were forced to
reduce both their staffs and the space dedicated to news, features
and editorials. In 1995, Wall Street analysts sent the price of
Times Mirror Co.'s stock up 70 percent in the first three months
after the company's chief executive, Mark Willes, closed New York
Newsday and cut newsroom staffs at The Los Angeles Times and The
Baltimore Sun.
</P>
<P>
   There was not much evidence to contradict the popular belief
that Wall Street was the newsroom's enemy.
</P>
<P>
   But, for a change, the financial community that once seemed
indifferent, if not downright pleased, about the budgetary squeeze
on journalists is emerging as the newsroom's ally. For the moment,
at least.
</P>
<P>
   Even those newspapers cutting their work forces are barely
grazing their newsrooms. At The Los Angeles Times, there have been
cutbacks in regional editions, but increases in staff in other
areas, like financial news coverage. All told, perhaps 5 percent of
the 750 jobs being eliminated at The Los Angeles Times affect the
newsroom. At The Wall Street Journal, 136 people took advantage of
the recent buyout offer; 11 of them were in the newsroom and some
of them may be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Newsrooms have a bottom-line function, analysts said. Stronger
news coverage may help stem circulation declines. And in the
cacophony of the Internet, a distinctive editorial voice may be a
crucial advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``journalism'' was notable for its absence during
interviews with financial analysts at a Paine Webber media
conference this month. Still, Douglas Arthur of Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter &AMP; Co. acknowledged, ``If you invest in color presses and you
invest in editorial, it sells papers and drives circulation, and
that's the point.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur, who reads three papers daily _ The New York Times, The
Wall Street Journal and The New York Post _ is the brother of John
Arthur, managing editor for regional editions at The Los Angeles
Times.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur reads the industry's recent history as a tale of
companies undergoing a fundamental restructuring on the fly, and
sometimes overreacting. After the recession, he said, ``there was a
lot of cost-cutting, asset restructuring and union negotiations in
an effort to get labor costs under control; now there's a renewed
focus on the product.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Kevin Gruneich's first jobs was delivering The Des Moines
(Iowa) Register to his neighbors. When his old paper was bought by
Gannett Co., and its prized role as a statewide voice was trimmed _
along with distribution costs _ Gruneich, now an analyst with Bear,
Stearns, felt a twinge of regret. ``I hated to see the pullback
from full statewide distribution,'' he said. But the decision to
limit distribution to the areas closer to Des Moines, he said, made
financial sense.
</P>
<P>
   If forced to choose between the old, more expensive statewide
focus and the current plan, ``I'd probably come down on the
hard-eyed side,'' he said. ``There are 1,500 daily newspapers in
the country. I don't think there's any civic obligation for The Des
Moines Register to deliver everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to investment in journalism, as opposed to
distribution systems, he makes finer distinctions. Asked if Wall
Street was more sensitive to the value of newsrooms, he said,
``Absolutely.'' Why? ``In a more electronic future, the infinite
fragmentation that is the Internet means that you're really going
to have to have a brand that stands out,'' he said. ``If you keep
moving it down to the lowest common denominator, you're going to be
lost in the clutter.''
</P>
<P>
   When Lauren Rich Fine of Merrill Lynch Global Securities talks
to newspaper company executives, the first question she says she is
asked is, ``What does Wall Street think about Pulitzer Prizes?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The quick response I usually give is, `For the most part, they
don't care, unless it involves the paper they're reading,''' she
said. ``Then they care a lot.'' New York Times Co., she added,
``has been able to get away with lower margins because it's
universally accepted that we don't want the paper to cut back on
the newsroom because it offers in-depth analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fine is not averse to newsroom spending _ if it can be done
efficiently. ``The culture of the newsroom,'' as she sees it, is
that journalists ``have historically held themselves apart, that
they are doing something for the good of mankind.'' But, she added,
``if you've chosen to be a public company, shareholder and God
aren't always perfectly aligned in terms of what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Willes, a lightning rod for controversy since the cuts he made
as the chief executive of Times Mirror, is cautious about the idea
that financial analysts were once hostile to news budgets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a lot of question, initially, about whether
there was discipline on the cost side,'' Willes said in a recent
interview. ``As organizations increasingly demonstrate discipline
on the cost side, but also say, `We're going to continue to
maintain and improve the editorial quality' _ that's the message
they want to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, we're financial analysts,'' William
Drewry of Donaldson Lufkin Jenrette said, who ``tend to be
reflecting more quantitatively than qualitatively.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not recommending one stock over another because you
think their newspaper is better,'' he said. ``You're recommending
it because the earnings growth is better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
