<HEADLINE>
OVERCROWDED E-STORES 
E-MAILS IN OUTER SPACE 
SCHWAB GETS NET SHY 
DEPARTURE FROM I-VILLAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consumers dreaming of an e-Christmas free of the hassles of
crowds have been rushing online to shop in record numbers. While
Internet merchants are delivering plenty of convenience, they are
offering up plenty of e-reality as well. In the past weeks, some of
the best-known sites have experienced slowdowns and even service
outages.
</P>
<P>
   Among sites with traffic troubles was BarnesandNoble.com, the
Internet outpost of the retail book giant Barnes &AMP; Noble. The site
was processing orders at a snail's pace on Tuesday, and the company
blamed surging holiday traffic. Another site that has faltered
under holiday demand was IBM's much advertised Startrekstore.com,
which went out of service for several days almost as soon as it
went online just before Thanksgiving. And Macys.com has repeatedly
had troubles processing customer orders since its relaunch on Nov.
18.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Sanger, vice president of corporate affairs for Federated
Department Stores Inc., which owns Macy's, said the Macy's delays
had been caused by an ``incredible'' interest in the site. ``We've
been receiving 10 million hits a day,'' she said. ``So for us, this
is kind of a good news-bad news story.''
</P>
<P>
   David Baltaxe, an Internet commerce analyst with Current
Analysis, which gathers industry intelligence for private clients,
says companies that advertised heavily should have anticipated such
problems: ``It is amazing that all these companies hyping
electronic commerce have run face-first into capacity problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The sheer volume of holiday shoppers was not to blame for all
the more notable failures. E-Bay, the popular Internet auction
service, experienced three system outages over the last two weeks,
one because of a hardware failure and two because of software
problems that Mike Wilson, the company's vice president for product
development and site operations, said were ``completely unrelated
to demand.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Leslie Kaufman
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   ASTRONAUTS GET MAIL; MICROSOFT GETS A FOOTHOLD
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail revolution has breached another frontier _ space.
</P>
<P>
   The space shuttle Endeavour finished a 12-day mission last
Tuesday that was the first on which crew members could routinely
send and receive e-mail, using notebook computers and ``smart
modems'' developed by NASA engineers to overcome problems in data
communications from space.
</P>
<P>
   The five astronauts and one cosmonaut could send e-mail to
colleagues and family much as they would on Earth. The 620 messages
they sent were mostly personal, dealing with Christmas preparations
and the like, says John Grunsfeld, chief of NASA's astronaut
computer branch.
</P>
<P>
   Many messages were sent up as well. In one, a crew member, James
Newman, received snapshots of his wife and two young children from
Grunsfeld, who had scanned them and sent them as e-mail
attachments.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail was restricted to family, other astronauts and NASA
mission personnel. ``The last thing I'd want in space is to have to
wade through all my terrestrial e-mail,'' Grunsfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   But he says the astronauts have been pushing NASA hard to have
``our workplace in space mirror our workplace on earth in terms of
access to information technology.''
</P>
<P>
   The software technology they use is largely supplied by
Microsoft Corp. and includes the Windows operating system with its
Outlook Express e-mail program.
</P>
<P>
   Is NASA concerned about extending what another branch of the
government terms the ``Microsoft monopoly'' into space? ``Despite
the Justice Department's case, we don't really worry about that
here on Earth,'' Grunsfeld said. ``Now if I were running a software
company on Mars, I might be concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Lohr
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   SCHWAB BACKS AWAY FROM SOME INTERNET TRADES
</P>
<P>
   In the volatile and warp-speed world of online trading, Charles
Schwab &AMP; Co. has blinked.
</P>
<P>
   Saying it wants to protect overzealous investors from market
volatility _ and from themselves _ Schwab, a discount broker based
in San Francisco, is no longer accepting trades over the Internet
for stocks of some companies on the first day they are available
for public trading.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for example, it would not accept online trades on
Tuesday for Infospace.com, an Internet content aggregator that went
public that day. Schwab customers were still able to purchase the
shares over the phone on their first days of trading, and online
trading resumed for the stock on the day after its initial
offering.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab officials said the policy was implemented at the end of
November to protect clients and the company's own bottom line. Tom
Taggart, a Schwab spokesman, said that in the case of some
offerings, investors place online orders to buy the stock at the
market price, but by the time the trades are actually executed, the
stock costs significantly more than the investors had expected to
pay.
</P>
<P>
   Taggart said that even when investors specified a price, market
volatility resulted in ``an inordinate amount of changing and
canceling of orders.''
</P>
<P>
   Taggart said the company would restrict trading on only a
handful of stocks it identified as likely candidates for volatility
_ among them Marketwatch.com and Pacific Internet, which are
expected to go public shortly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Matt Richtel
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   AN OLD HAND AT START-UPS MOVES ON FROM I-VILLAGE
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When photographers took pictures of the three
founders of I-Village, the New York Internet service for women,
they often tried to place Robert Levitan in the center. This proved
to be a repeated annoyance to Candice Carpenter, the company's
chief executive, and Nancy Evans, its editor in chief.
</P>
<P>
   Levitan, 33, was decidedly the junior partner, but he provided
some visual variety in a company of, by and for women.
</P>
<P>
   No more. Earlier this month, just as I-Village was preparing for
an initial public stock offering, Levitan quietly departed.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, after selling his first start-up, Levitan was
recruited by Ms. Carpenter to help with a consulting assignment for
America Online. Later she invited him to join in starting
I-Village.
</P>
<P>
   Levitan brought in the revenue, selling advertising sponsorships
to big consumer products companies _ $20 million worth by his own
count. But last May, Ms. Carpenter hired John Glascott, a former
top sales executive with Hearst, to take over sponsorship sales,
and Levitan moved over to run the company's health information
site. When his stock holdings vested last fall, he began making
plans to leave the company.
</P>
<P>
   He said last week that he was eager to move on to another
start-up, which he described as involving electronic gift
certificates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready for another challenge,'' he said. ``I will go on
to do things that are as big or bigger than I-Village.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Saul Hansell
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
