<DOCNO> NYT19981220.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-20 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9250 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-US-1221-COX     12-20 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-US-1221-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH LITTLE KNOWN ABOUT THE DAMAGE, IRAQIS CLAIM VICTORY
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QORNA, Iraq _ It seems that the first thing rebuilt after four
nights of U.S. and British missile attacks was the famous Iraqi
house of mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   Relieved that the barrage was called off the night before,
Iraqis Sunday claimed their victory but kept information and access
to the damage to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi officials still released no casualty figures, though
civilian casualties appear to be around 35. They took a few
reporters to see damage to this city a five-hour drive south from
the capital of Baghdad, then barely gave them access to the sites.
</P>
<P>
   But, on the impoverished streets here, the chants were in good
form and the slogans nearly uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saddam, Saddam, your name means fear for America,'' chanted a
street crowd waving flags near a tent set up to focus support for
the regime.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi officials say that near here one of the country's only
three oil refineries was badly damaged. Reporters were twice taken
to the oil company offices, but not allowed to see the refinery,
which is heavily guarded by tanks and anti-aircraft guns.
</P>
<P>
   The officials also said a hospital in the area was badly
damaged, but that did not make it on the tour either. They did show
reporters two small destroyed compounds that served as postal and
telephone centers.
</P>
<P>
   But, while witnesses initially spoke of military officers being
killed at one of the sites they soon, with encouragement, said the
two casualties were civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Iraqi President Saddam Hussein declared victory
Sunday in a televised statement to his people.
</P>
<P>
   ``God will repay well and crown your heart with clear victory,''
Hussein, dressed in military garb, said in his short speech.
</P>
<P>
   The comments were echoed among his people.
</P>
<P>
   In Qorna, a town of Shiite Muslims who have faced persecution
under Hussein and formed an underground opposition movement, the
military presence is daunting. Small, whitewashed compounds with
machine-gun mounts and sometimes armored cars are spaced every few
hundred yards on the highways, often directly across from poor farm
villages.
</P>
<P>
   But, the Shiites that gathered on the streets Sunday glorified
Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iraq won. We had a victory because we held steadfast and
patient and Saddam survived,'' Khadum Rezak, a 30-year-old driver
said.
</P>
<P>
   Just who did win after this four days of flashing and rumbling
in the night skies will not be known for some time. The United
States and Britain began the assault after Hussein stopped
cooperating with the United Nations weapons inspections begun after
a U.S.-led military coalition forced Iraq out of Kuwait in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Iraq has faced eight years of inspections and
crippling economic sanctions. After the recent bombings, Iraqi
officials say they will no longer allow weapons inspectors into the
country and that could, indeed, be a victory for Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   But the ultimate effect of the air strikes is shrouded, which
may be appropriate for a country under attack that does not want to
let attackers see their specific impact. There were at least a few
clues on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said the 70-hour offensive hit nearly 100
targets and involved 650 aircraft missions, with more than 400
cruise missiles launched on Iraq -- more than in the five-week
Desert Storm operation after the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said the attacks inflicted ``significant
damage'' on Iraqi weapons programs, command structures and military
and security infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Among targets U.S. officials said were hit: 20 command and
control facilities, 18 facilities providing security for weapons
programs, seven or eight of President Saddam Hussein's palaces and
posts of the elite Republican Guard.
</P>
<P>
   While most areas of Baghdad and the major southern city of
Basra, near Qorna, do not show any signs of damage, the damage that
is visible or acknowledged by Iraqis illustrate the U.S. goals --
reportedly to weaken Saddam's ability to build chemical and
biological weapons of mass destruction, and to soften up his regime
for a possible coup.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqis say that the major Neba factory complex near Baghdad was
hit.
</P>
<P>
   That factory is suspected to be used in making missile casings
and has been monitored by the weapons inspectors' cameras. The
attack appears to be based on the assumption that, since the air
strikes have given Saddam a pretext for forever rejecting the
weapons inspections, weapons production will be stopped instead by
force.
</P>
<P>
   The two destroyed centers for postal and telephone services that
reporters were shown in Basra and Qorna appeared to fit U.S. goals
to cut communications between the north and south, making it easier
for opposition groups to form in those areas.
</P>
<P>
   Two people -- the soldiers or civilians, depending on when
witnesses were asked -- were crushed at one site. At the other, two
people were killed at the postal center and two children were hurt
when two rooms of a house near the center were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   It left the owner of the house, Moveid Salah, 51, to interpret
American goals on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to kill the people here. They want to destroy our
civilization,'' he said as he stood in the street amid the mixed
rubble of his house and the postal center. ``Iraq won because we
have a mind and dignity and we believe in God.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-98 1709EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
