<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   E-MAIL VIRUS SPREADING
</P>
<P>
   Security experts are warning clients about a new software virus
that is spread by e-mail, infects Microsoft Word files and has
already caused several networks to crash.
</P>
<P>
   The ``MS Word Macro 97 Class Virus'' creates a pop-up box in
Microsoft Word 97 files that addresses the recipient of the e-mail
by name and informs the user that he or she ``is a big stupid
jerk.'' The virus contains no programming that would cripple a
network server, but experts said that a huge infection of document
files could start a chain reaction on a computer network that in
turn can cause a general system failure.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAUTIOUS TURNAROUND FOR ADOBE
</P>
<P>
   After a bruising year and a large-scale reorganization, Adobe
Systems delivered higher-than-expected earnings and strong revenue
for its fourth quarter. But while praising the company's improved
management and new products, analysts generally retained a cautious
outlook on Adobe's stock.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REMARKS ABOUT STOCK STIR DEBATE
</P>
<P>
   James J. Cramer, the money manager, columnist and television
commentator, has spurred a debate on the ethics of commentators in
the financial media. After Cramer appeared on CNBC's ``Squawk Box''
program and said he had talked with a broker about the possibility
of short-selling the stock of Wavephore, an Internet broadcasting
company, the network said Cramer would not be allowed back pending
an investigation of complaints made by the company and the
Securities and Exchange Commission.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN TO BUY LEFTOVER THAI LOANS
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs Group, in conjunction with GE Capital, has agreed
to pay 23.6 billion baht, or $645 million, for about a third of the
loans left over from Thailand's unsuccessful auction last week of
assets seized from defunct financial companies.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NO LINES, BUT SHOPPERS STILL WAIT
</P>
<P>
   Consumers hoping to beat the holiday crowds have been rushing on
line to shop in record numbers. While Internet merchants are
delivering plenty of convenience, they are offering up plenty of
E-reality as well. Some of the best-known sites have experienced
slowdowns and even service outages.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SILICON ALLEY AIDS NONPROFIT GROUPS
</P>
<P>
   There is a growing commitment among Silicon Alley companies to
share time and cash with nonprofit groups founded to distribute the
benefits of technology.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BANKING ON INDEPENDENT FILMS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a quest to duplicate the success of ``The Full Monty,'' which
grossed $256 million worldwide, players better known as financiers
than auteurs have set up three independent film companies. Artisan
Entertainment is bankrolled by the venture capital firm Bain
Capital, Stratosphere Entertainment was founded by the corporate
raider Carl C. Icahn and Lions Gate Entertainment, whose year-end
hopes rest with ``Affliction'' with Willem Dafoe and Sissy Spacek,
is headed by Frank Giustra, an investment banker in Canada.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN PREDICTS GROWTH NEXT YEAR
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government said it expected the nation's economy to
grow by five-tenths of a percent in the next fiscal year as tax
cuts spurred a mild recovery in consumer purchases and public works
spending lent support to the economy.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
