<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RHODES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UGA student not your `average' Rhodes Scholar
 &HT;    By Plott Brice
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ There probably is a profile and resume that fits
the conventional image of a Rhodes Scholar.
</P>
<P>
   And then, there is Beth Shapiro. Beth Shapiro, the University of
Georgia's 18th Rhodes Scholar. Beth Shapiro, UGA's first female
Rhodes Scholar.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rhodes image is simply one of academic excellence
achieved by burrowing through a rigorous tunnel of narrow academic
pursuits, then you wouldn't picture Beth Shapiro. She's briefly
traveled the academic map at UGA.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro, who sings a bit of jazz and enjoys a little Wild
Turkey, is a blaze of energy. She's witty and poised, and she
probably never will be accused of being an intellectual snob.
</P>
<P>
   Her goal is to one day connect scientific work and its
importance to the everyday person and she believes her journalism
background will prove useful. Currently a teaching assistant in
ecology/biology, she sees herself as a teacher and researcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``She definitely deserves this,'' said John Pickering, Shapiro's
major professor. ``She has a great career ahead of her. It's hard
to say anything less than glowing comments about her work and
dedication.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro, whose home is in Lindale, near Rome, said it still has
not registered with her completely that she will soon walk on
sidewalks and in halls of colleges where some of the best and
brightest have tread.
</P>
<P>
   This year's 32 Rhodes Scholars were chosen from 909 applicants.
The scholarships, created in 1902 by the will of British statesman
and philanthropist Cecil Rhodes, provide two or three years' of
study at Oxford University in England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really in awe of going to Oxford,'' Shapiro said. ``It is
astonishing to be in the atmosphere where so many incredible and
interesting people studied.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is no sign that the 22-year-old is intimidated by the
experiences ahead. She may even get an early start next summer
using the third of her Foundation Fellows trips abroad to begin her
work in Edinburgh, Scotland, also noted for evolutionary biology,
her main interest. Her Oxford experience begins Sept. 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two speeds,'' she said. ``One hundred miles per hour
and zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro spends long hours in the lab in the Biological Sciences
Building, where she is working on her thesis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here about 24 hours a day,'' she said. ``At least, right
now I am.''
</P>
<P>
   When she arrived on the UGA campus in 1994, she wasn't thinking
of the Rhodes. She left Rome High School with a 4.0 grade point
average and some experience in broadcast journalism she picked up
at a local station.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when I was a freshman, I knew exactly what I wanted to
do,''she said. ``I wanted to go into broadcast journalism and I was
very glad I was at the University of Georgia, because they have one
of the best broadcast journalism schools.''
</P>
<P>
   She even worked as news director of a local radio station.
</P>
<P>
   But after one quarter, that certainty gave way to the expansive
horizons of a major university.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I was in a big place that had a lot of
opportunities available. So I started taking lots of different
courses,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There was Chinese, and Spanish. Then there was a second choice
of majors and a third. And a fourth. Many students have traveled
that route. But when Shapiro found her niche, she went at it full
tilt. Next spring she will graduate with an unblemished record with
a joint bachelor of science and a master of science degree in
ecology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are extremely pleased and excited that with Beth's
selection, UGA has produced Rhodes Scholars three out of the last
four years,'' said UGA President Michael Adams. ``Certainly Beth is
representative of the quality of students that we believe are in
place at the University of Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro considers herself ``just a normal student.'' She has
been known to bark with fellow Dawgs at UGA football games. When
she has time, she enjoys hiking, a night out dancing or eating
pizza with friends. Her sister, Meghan, is a junior at UGA.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz is one method of relaxation she really likes. Despite being
declared ``tone deaf'' by her mom, Shapiro tried out for a spot as
a jazz vocalist a few years ago. Her music background consisted of
violin and drums in the high school band.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I auditioned and got the (job) as vocalist and I have been
singing ever since,'' she said. ``I think I am quite good.''
</P>
<P>
   Jazz is also an escape. When the phone calls and requests for
interviews got to be too much for her this month, she ``went home
and put on some jazz and turned it up loud so I couldn't hear the
phone.''
</P>
<P>
   BETH ALISON SHAPIRO
</P>
<P>
   Age: 22
</P>
<P>
   Home: Lindale (Rome), Ga.
</P>
<P>
   High school: Rome High School
</P>
<P>
   UGA degrees: Bachelor of science and master of science in
ecology. Primary interest is evolutionary biology.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbies: Hiking and jazz music. Favorites are Louis Armstrong
and Ella Fitzgerald. She is a vocalist in a jazz band.
</P>
<P>
   Work: She is a teaching assistant in ecology/biology.
</P>
<P>
   Parents: Robert Shapiro, of Naples, Fla. Mother Kathy Shapiro
and stepfather, Tony Ezzell.
</P>
<P>
   Siblings: Meghan, a junior at UGA
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
