<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL COLUMNIST'S COMMENTS START DEBATE 
ANTI-DRUG GROUP TO QUESTION DISCREDITED WRITER 
EX-REPORTER FACES JAIL FOR PROTECTING SOURCE
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the money manager, columnist and television commentator
James Cramer spoke about the fledgling Internet data broadcasting
company Wavephore on the Dec. 2 episode of the CNBC stock-market
program, he probably did not intend to spur a debate on the ethics
of commentators in the financial media.
</P>
<P>
   But that has been the result of his ``Squawk Box'' appearance,
after CNBC, a cable broadcast unit of General Electric Co., said on
Wednesday that Cramer would not be allowed back on the program,
pending an investigation of complaints that Wavephore made to the
network and the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``Squawk Box'' segment, Kramer referred to Wavephore,
whose share price had soared 60 percent the day before, as an
example of what he termed ``Fraud-U-Net companies.'' And he said
that he had talked with a broker that morning about the
possibilities of short-selling Wavephore's stock _ that is, placing
a bet that the share price would fall.
</P>
<P>
   The day before Cramer's comments, Wavephore's shares had closed
at $15.25 in Nasdaq trading. Since his television appearance, the
shares have fallen, closing Friday at $8.0625.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ma and Pa Kettle, anyone with a Net connection, can buy and
sell stocks, which puts a certain responsibility on the sector of
financial journalism,'' Glenn Williamson, chief operating officer
for Wavephore, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Cramer declined to be interviewed about the controversy. But on
Friday he wrote at length about it in his daily column that appears
on Thestreet.com, a financial news service in which he is a
co-founder.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I was trying to do was explain why Wavephore stock had
recently soared _ I never had any intention of shorting the
stock,'' Cramer wrote.
</P>
<P>
   George Jamison, a spokesman for CNBC, said the issue had forced
the network to review its own processes with regard to guest
analysts, who already are required to disclose whether they have a
financial stake in any of the companies they discuss during
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cramer did disclose he had no position in Wavefore,'' Jamison
said. ``Our job is to root out the facts and root out the details
and to put the details on the air for our viewers so they can make
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   In his Friday column, Cramer defended his approach to stock
market commentary: ``Saying that a money manager must never discuss
stocks because it is hopelessly conflicted is a head-in-the-sand
mentality that would deny investors substantive information from
those actually in the business.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lisa Napoli
</P>
<P>
   EMBATTLED WRITER TO MEET WITH ANTI-DRUG GROUP
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to settle the $10-million libel lawsuit filed
against him by the drug prevention group DARE over articles he
wrote about the organization for Rolling Stone and The New
Republic, Stephen Glass has agreed to tell the group what he knows
about the two publications' editing and fact-checking processes.
</P>
<P>
   Glass, whom The New Republic dismissed earlier this year after
determining that he fabricated material for articles he wrote for
the magazine and for other publications, is expected to meet with
representatives of DARE on Jan. 5 for a formal interview that will
stop short of a legal deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Miller, a lawyer for DARE, an acronym for Drug Abuse
Resistance Education, said Glass would be questioned with an eye
toward legal action against the two magazines. Miller said the
group was also seeking an admission from Glass that could be used
to refute contentions in his articles that DARE intimidated critics
into silence.
</P>
<P>
   Miller declined to elaborate on DARE's legal strategy, but Karen
Frederiksen, a First Amendment lawyer in Los Angeles, said that
building a libel case typically involved trying to determine a
publication's conduct from the inception of an article until it
appeared in print.
</P>
<P>
   Gerson Zweifach, a lawyer who has represented Glass on other
issues, said the writer had no agreement spelling out specifically
what he would tell the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lane, editor of The New Republic, declined to comment on
the agreement between Glass and DARE. An editor at Rolling Stone,
the flagship publication of Wenner Media, did not return calls
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Christian Berthelsen
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   FORMER JOURNALIST CITED WITH CONTEMPT
</P>
<P>
   A former reporter for a Southern California newspaper has been
cited with contempt and sentenced to jail for refusing to disclose
a source to authorities. If an appeals court upholds the citation,
he would be the first journalist jailed for protecting a source in
more than two decades in California, a state generally seen as
having the strongest so-called shield laws for journalists.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, as a reporter for The Inland Valley Daily Bulletin, an
Ontario, Calif., newspaper with a circulation of 67,000 that is a
member of the Donrey Media Group, John Rezendes-Herrick wrote a
series of articles about how a small agribusiness concern called
Cadiz Land Co. was able to get financing to acquire a much larger
company; he based his reporting in part on tips and documents
provided by a confidential source.
</P>
<P>
   In September of that year, Rezendes-Herrick, who is now a
seventh-grade social studies teacher, was subpoenaed to appear
before a grand jury and asked to identify his source for the Cadiz
articles. The district attorney's office declines to say exactly
what the grand jury is investigating.
</P>
<P>
   After he invoked the state's shield law, Rezendes-Herrick was
found in contempt by a San Bernardino Superior Court judge, and
sentenced last month to five days in jail and a $500 fine. The
sentence has been postponed pending review by a state appeals
court.
</P>
<P>
   Rezendes-Herrick's case may depend on the outcome of another
case being considered by the California Supreme Court. In that
case, an appellate panel found in August that government may have a
law enforcement interest that outweighs a reporter's right to
protect a source. As a result, an exception to the state's shield
law would be extended to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   If the state's Supreme Court upholds the finding that
prosecutors can subpoena journalists, it could considerably weaken
the shield law and lead courts in other states to decide the issue
the same way, said Thomas Newton, a lawyer for the California
Newspaper Publishers Association.
</P>
<P>
   The last journalist to be sentenced to jail over a confidential
source in California was Bill Farr, a reporter for The Los Angeles
Herald-Examiner who spent 46 days behind bars rather than identify
a source for a story on the Charles Manson case in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Rezendes-Herrick, who became a teacher in January, said he was
torn between his commitments to his students and to his previous
career as a reporter. But he said he remained opposed to
identifying his sources, even if that stance meant spending time in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   _ Christian Berthelsen
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
