<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUCK-DEFECT21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Charges dropped against woman in fatal wreck after truck defects
discovered
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A Cherokee County prosecutor says he will drop charges
filed against a woman in a January chain-reaction wreck on I-575
that killed a legislator's secretary because he cannot refute her
claim that a mechanical defect caused the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   Solicitor Channing Ruskell plans to drop vehicular-homicide
charges against Karen Brackett, whose Chevrolet Suburban crossed
the median of I-575 during rush hour in southern Cherokee and
initiated a nine-vehicle crash. Ruskell said an 11-month
investigation lends credence to Brackett's claim that she lost
control when her seat collapsed without warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, with the information I have, I do not believe I
could successfully prosecute this case,'' Ruskell said.
</P>
<P>
   The solicitor said he plans to tell a judge Tuesday or on Dec.
29 of his decision not to prosecute Brackett. Ruskell said the
decision follows ``the most thorough investigation I've ever had in
a wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   Brackett was driving south on I-575 during rush hour Jan. 16
when she lost control of her vehicle. It crossed the median near a
bridge that carries Ga. 92 over I-575 and smashed into a
tractor-trailer. The tractor-trailer then lost control and also
crossed the median, slamming into other cars heading toward Atlanta
about 7:10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   One of those cars, a 1991 Acura Integra, was driven by Vickie
Bell, a 49-year-old mother of two from Woodstock who was driving to
her job as a secretary for Rep. Bob Holmes (D-Atlanta) in the state
capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Nine people were injured in the chain-reaction crash, but Bell
was the only fatality.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was just the greatest person. You can ask anybody,'' said
Anna Boggs, her sister, who also works at the Capitol. ``Not a day
goes by that somebody at the Capitol doesn't come by and just break
down in tears just talking about her.''
</P>
<P>
   Brackett, 44, told state troopers investigating the wreck ``she
was driving down the road and, basically, her seat collapsed and
that caused her to lose control,'' Ruskell said.
</P>
<P>
   He said troopers confirmed that Brackett's seat had collapsed,
but they could not tell whether it collapsed before or after she
hit the tractor-trailer. He said Brackett's insurance company has
hired forensic experts to test the car to determine when the seat
collapsed. A report is expected soon, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months after the wreck, on Aug. 28, state troopers charged
Brackett with second-degree vehicular homicide, failure to maintain
lane and driving too fast for conditions. The vehicular-homicide
charge is a misdemeanor that carries a maximum penalty of a year in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   To convict Brackett of second-degree vehicular homicide, Ruskell
said he would have to prove ``beyond a reasonable doubt'' that
Brackett violated a traffic law that led to Bell's death. Ruskell
said he cannot do that because he cannot disprove that Brackett's
claim that seat collapse caused her to lose control.
</P>
<P>
   The solicitor said he can refile charges up to two years after
the crash if new evidence disputes her claim.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
recalled Chevy Suburbans manufactured from August 1984 to January
1991 - Brackett drove a 1987 Chevy Suburban - because of a problem
that the recall said ``would allow the seat back to suddenly
recline and could result in loss of vehicle control and a vehicle
crash without prior warning.'' Dan Hubbert, a spokesman for General
Motors Corp. in Detroit, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Brackett still faces two lawsuits as a result of the wreck. The
estate of Vickie Bell has sued, claiming that Brackett was driving
too fast, driving recklessly and that she ``failed to maintain a
proper lookout for other known and reasonably foreseeable
automobiles.'' The other lawsuit filed on behalf of Bell's
passenger Annabella Marsano makes the same allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Jean E. Johnson Jr., an attorney representing Marsano and Bell's
estate, said he has been told that attorneys for Brackett will
argue that a mechanical problem caused the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   W. Curtis Anderson, the attorney defending Brackett against the
lawsuits, said another issue that needs ``to be explored further''
is a Georgia Bureau of Investigation laboratory report that Bell
had marijuana in her blood at the time of the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   The accident report lists the presence of marijuana in Bell's
blood as a ``contributing factor'' in the wreck, but State Trooper
Leamon Hughes, who investigated the wreck, and Ruskell said they do
not know whether marijuana played a role in the wreck. Ruskell said
alcohol or marijuana can delay a person's response time, but he
does not know if that happened in this case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say that it absolutely didn't contribute to the
accident or not,'' Ruskell said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Horton McCurdy, a GBI toxicologist, said the amount of
marijuana found in Bell's blood indicates that she had probably
smoked marijuana within 12 hours of the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   It is against the law for people to drive with any amount of
marijuana in their blood.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the attorney for Bell's estate, said he thinks the
drug-test results are wrong. But even if they are accurate, he
said, they show such a small amount of the drug that it would not
have affected Bell's reaction time or ability to drive.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two months after the wreck, legislators named the
bridge over I-575 the ``Vickie E. Bell Memorial Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chuck Scheid (R-Woodstock) said he introduced the measure
to name the bridge for Bell because she was ``well liked and
respected.'' He said he was surprised to hear about the test
results.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Boggs said she did not know about the test results and does
not believe her sister used the drug. Boggs said her sister, who
had worked at the Capitol for 24 years, was kind, raised flowers
and loved antiques.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was everybody's friend. She was the kind of person who
would almost always remember your birthday,'' said Boggs. ``She'd
send you a card or write a letter for no reason at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
