<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-US _ BAGHDAD _ With four days of air strikes by U.S. and
British forces over, the Iraqi government claims victory as
President Saddam Hussein is still standing and United Nations
weapons inspectors gone. Iraqi officials take foreign journalists
on a tour of Basra in southern Iraq, where cruise missiles damaged
precious oil fields. As U.S. and British defense officials begin to
assess just how much damage they may, or may not have done, the one
thing becoming immediatelt clear is the anger on the part of Arabs
_ and not just in Iraq. Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RHODES _ ATHENS, Ga. _ There probably is a profile and resume
that fits the conventional image of a Rhodes Scholar. And then,
there is Beth Shapiro. She is the University of Georgia's 18th
Rhodes Scholar and its first female Rhodes Scholar. If the Rhodes
image is simply academic excellence achieved by burrowing through a
rigorous tunnel of narrow academic pursuits, then you wouldn't
picture Beth. Shapiro, who sings a little jazz and enjoys a little
Wild Turkey, is a blaze of engery going in a lot of directions.
(Brice, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 24. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TRUCK-DEFECT _ ATLANTA _ The Cherokee County Solicitor says he
will drop charges against a woman who caused a Jan. 16 fatal wreck
on on I-575 because he cannot disprove her claim that a mechanical
problem with her 1987 Chevy Suburban caused the wreck.
Investigators have spent 11 months looking into the wreck, which
killed a secretary for Rep. Bob Homes (D-Atlanta). They have
discovered that the National Highway Safety Traffic Administration
recalled the 1987 Chevy Suburban because its front seat could
``suddenly recline'' and cause a ``loss of vehicle control and a
vehicle crash without prior warning.'' The woman who caused the
wreck says her car seat collapsed without warning during rush hour
on I-575 in southern Cherokee County Jan. 16. (Bixler, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 35. MOVED
</P>
