u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-TERRORISM-REVIEW-N     12-20 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TERRORISM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEATH TO AMERICA': WONDERING ABOUT VICTORY IN THE WAR ON
TERRORISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you have lost track, amid the unfamiliar names and murky
allegations of who is supposed to have done what in the year's
terrorist bombings in East Africa, Monday night's ``Investigative
Reports'' provides a sketchy guide. Drawn mainly from U.S. sources,
``Death to America: The Terrorism Trail'' lays out the evidence and
suspicions of what has become the case of the United States of
America vs. Osama bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   In the months since the August explosions, bin Laden, the Saudi
millionaire who fought the Soviet Union in Afghanistan before
turning to preaching the murder of Americans, has been described by
one investigator as ``a financial godfather'' of international
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   This hourlong program, which begins with pictures of stunned and
bloodied survivors, mostly Africans, moves like an exotic-locale
paperback mystery, from a seemingly suspicious patient in a Nairobi
hospital to a Jordanian in Karachi, Pakistan, to a
Lebanese-American in the United States. The FBI says it can connect
these plotters with bin Laden, whom it also credits with playing a
part in driving U.S. troops out of Somalia in 1992 and in the
bombing of the World Trade Center in Manhattan in 1993. He has been
indicted in New York, with a reward of $5 million for anybody out
there who can bring him in.
</P>
<P>
   The charges have yet to be tested in court, but there has
already been controversy over a retaliatory strike by the United
States on what was advertised as a factory in Sudan that produced
nerve gas. The Sudanese deny it, and the program's reporter says
there are signs that the demolished factory was what they say it
was, a pharmaceutical plant. However that dispute turns out, no one
claims that America's response is likely to do much to discourage
terrorism. An investigator, who might have been commenting on last
week's headlines, says, ``You can't fight terrorism with a cruise
missile.''
</P>
<P>
   This brisk hour leaves open the question of whether even the
capture of bin Laden would make life safer for Americans. The
publicity spotlight has given the man the aura of a mastermind of
terrorism, but the program leaves the caution that such is the
nature of terror and fear that the war against them may be
unwinnable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-98 1832EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981220.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-20 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REAMS-CABARET-REVIEW-     12-20 0308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAMS-CABARET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GOTTA SING, GOTTA DANCE': A SINGER-DANCER'S IMPERATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)  (lb) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Can a limber, starry-eyed boy from Covington, Ky.,
find happiness as a dancer and singer on the stages of Las Vegas
and on Broadway? Lee Roy Reams' autobiographical cabaret show,
``Gotta Sing, Gotta Dance,'' at the Firebird Cafe, answers that
question with an emphatic yes.
</P>
<P>
   Telling the story of his journey from Kentucky to Broadway via
Las Vegas (where he worked as a dancer for Juliet Prowse), Reams
has an anecdote for every turn in the road. Ann Miller, Bob Fosse,
Gwen Verdon, Gower Champion, David Merrick, Dorothy Fields and
Prowse, among others, are remembered in revealing backstage
reminiscences.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most touching stories recalls Champion, shortly
before his death, explaining his decision to direct the hit musical
``42nd Street.'' ``I didn't want to be remembered as a has-been,''
he said bluntly. Ms. Verdon's fear of singing and Ms. Miller's
salty tongue are also remembered.
</P>
<P>
   The show skillfully interweaves stories and songs into a
surprisingly intimate personal history that evokes the exhilaration
and uncertainty of show business. Its happy ending arrives with
Reams' last-minute selection for the young lead role of Billy
Lawlor in ``42nd Street'' after having been told he was too old for
the part.
</P>
<P>
   Reams may not be an especially commanding vocalist (he suggests
a Broadway equivalent of Neil Sedaka), but he imparts a touching
sincerity to a program whose high point is an extended medley from
the 1966 show ``Sweet Charity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gotta Sing, Gotta Dance,'' which plays through Jan. 2,
concludes with a winningly heartfelt version of that ultimate
Broadway gypsy anthem ``What I Did for Love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
