<HEADER>
A9328 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIGNS-SFCHRON-SIGNS &LR;      12-20 1441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIGNS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLBOARDS CARRY HIGH-TECH MESSAGES 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - SIGNS   By Dan Fost 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The giant trout leaps off the billboard on Highway  &LR; Interstate
880 in San Jose. But the company behind the billboard isn't selling
trout.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to tell what American Microsystems Inc. is selling,
unless you work in a semiconductor plant. The billboard exhorts:
``Catch a Cutthroat Gate Array. Convert Your FPGA to a
PCI-Compliant 66 MHz ASIC.''
</P>
<P>
   Huh?
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Incomprehension Highway. The AMI billboard is just
before the interchange with Highway 101, Silicon Valley's billboard
boulevard, where signs that wouldn't fly anywhere else thrive in a
climate that loves its geek-speak.
</P>
<P>
   If you're driving through the epicenter of the technology world,
you need an engineering degree to decipher some of the billboards.
``No Vectors, No Worries!'' reads one. Or this: ``17.7 million
transistors. 0.25 micron. Verified in 19 hours. Only with
Calibre.''
</P>
<P>
   Some ad experts say the billboards reflect the tech industry's
love affair with itself. ``We live in a special place. We are
really techno-centric here,'' said Fred Schwartz, creative director
and partner of Left Field, a San Francisco ad agency that serves
Web-based clients like Infoseek and Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you live and work in the industry, you can get really
absorbed in it,'' Schwartz said. ``You can think everyone has your
knowledge set. It's easy to get deluded.''
</P>
<P>
   The techno-billboards run all the way into San Francisco. Unlike
the signs along the Peninsula, however, those in and around the
city are easier for the average computer-using commuter to
comprehend. They tend to tout things like search engines, Sony
PlayStations, hot Web sites and cool computer games. A giant
inflatable iMac on the roof of the MacAdam computer store on Folsom
Street speaks for itself.
</P>
<P>
   American Microsystems Inc.,  &LR; AMI, the company with the trout
billboard, isn't aiming for the average person. ``It's a product
targeted toward a very focused market,'' said Vince Hopkin, a
director at the Pocatello, Idaho, company. The product _ AMI's &LR; 
 &LR; the Cutthroat gate array _ is a computer chip the company can
custom-make for specific users, such as cell phone manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Thanks to the billboard, AMI drew 250 surfers over three
months to a Web site about its chip, said AMI's  &LR; spokeswoman Tamera
Drake, and the company is pleased with that.
</P>
<P>
   Drake said the the billboard is strictly for the Bay Area's
``in'' crowd: It wouldn't play in Pocatello.
</P>
<P>
   All along Highway 101, billboards reflect the wired
sensibilities of the region. They promote products to sort through
companies' e-mail, to manage their  &LR; networks and to deliver
high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``ET did not `phone' home,'' exclaims a billboard for Wavepath,
the Mountain View subsidiary of Montreal's  &LR; Groupe Videotron ltee
of Montreal, Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; That may be so, but it's not especially likely that Steven
Spielberg's adorable extraterrestrial used Wavepath's high-speed
wireless data network _ ``ET'' was a hit in 1982, and Wavepath was
established this year.
</P>
<P>
   Geek-speak billboards cluster, not surprisingly, around
high-tech companies' corporate headquarters _ and their
competitors. The database software company Informix maintains a
billboard near its archrival Oracle's headquarters in Redwood
Shores, although the message is a little more muted than in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Informix's billboard almost obnoxiously taunted, ``You
have just passed Redwood Shores. So did we. Informix.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the billboard merely alludes to Informix's comeback after
one of the toughest years in technology: ``Damn the torpedoes, full
speed ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the more obtuse billboards irritate Schwartz, the San
Francisco ad-man.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way they can be there for advertising purposes,''
said Schwartz, talking from his car phone while he drove up Highway
101, taking in the signs. ``They're for PR, for recruiting, and for
the egos of the higher-ups of the companies. ... We've been in big
boardrooms where the chairman insists on a billboard on 101. It's
purely vanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz said the companies posting what he labels ``gibberish''
are victims of the cloistered world in which they operate.
</P>
<P>
   He said it's inefficient to post a narrowly targeted ad on a
road like Highway 101, which at some intersections averages more
than 200,000 vehicles per day, according to Caltrans.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Eller Media Co., the biggest billboard
company in the country, contend that the big signs work well even
when their messages seem murky.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Coca-Cola or Marlboro, which sell relatively inexpensive
products to the masses and have simple, easy-to-understand
billboards, companies selling computer products can afford to
target fewer customers, because each customer may represent
thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   A billboard can cost from several hundred dollars a month to
tens of thousands of dollars, depending on how elaborate it is and
how wide-reaching the media buy is, said George Broder, Eller's
Oakland-based vice president of public affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix-based Eller made an estimated $66 million from high-tech
billboards last year. That figure was double the previous year's
and should double again next year, said Stephen Freitas, Eller vice
president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outdoor is the best place to advertise an Internet address,''
Freitas said. ``Web site addresses have high levels of recall.
People are seeing the boards, remembering, and going to the Web
sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Which would explain billboards that say simply,
`` &LR; www.donatefood.org &LR; ,'' or, ``Where cows and cyberspace collide:
 &LR; www.gotmilk.com &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Heading north past San Francisco International Airport, tech
signs continue to dominate, although they're somewhat more easily
understood.
</P>
<P>
   Apple has one of its successful ``Think Different'' billboards
in San Mateo, but the face on it is hardly a household name:
Richard Feynman, the late Caltech Nobel Prize-winning physicist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Julio Solorzano Jr., who was unloading a truck at Attachments
International, a dental supply company underneath the Feynman
billboard, had no idea who loomed above him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one I've seen with Einstein, that was pretty cool,''
said Solorzano, 30. ``Some of them, though, it's like, `Who in the
hell is that?'''
</P>
<P>
   Further north, search engine companies Excite and Infoseek try
to tempt Web surfers stuck in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   In Brisbane, Imagine Media, which publishes a range of computer
magazines, posts a billboard that is often hard to figure out. But
the company likes it that way.
</P>
<P>
   The billboard says ``Last Great Media Company For 3,000 Miles,''
with an arrow pointing in the general direction of Imagine's
headquarters, three miles away. At first, the sign didn't say
``Imagine,'' but now it does. Weed-whacked into the hillside near
the sign is a ``B2'' _ an apparent reference to Business 2.0,
Imagine's newest magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,000 miles refers to the media capital of New York, and not
to any company in particular, said Diane Carlson, marketing
director for Business 2.0.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to be cheeky,'' Carlson said. She wouldn't
comment on the mowed ``B2,'' which is on public land, but she did
discuss the billboard. ``One of the No.1 reasons we have that
billboard is for recruitment. ... We work hard, play hard and have
fun with things.''
</P>
<P>
   The billboards themselves are more fun once they cross San
Francisco city limits. In an ad for the game Tomb Raider on the
side of a South of Market building, a two-story cartoon character
showing off ample cleavage announces, ``The name's Croft. Lara
Croft.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Lara Croft confuses most of the
non-computer-game-playing (and non-13-year-old-male) populace.
</P>
<P>
   But such simple tech ads still assume some level of computer
savviness. Even in San Francisco, which Yahoo Internet Life
anointed as the most wired city in America, only one-quarter of the
population is online. ``There are people who aren't on the
Internet, and I wonder what they think,'' said Melinda Whitehouse,
a San Francisco writer who has a paean to area billboards posted at
 &LR; www.posthoc.com/billboards.htm. &LR;  cq &LR; ``Probably the same thing as
when they see the Spanish language ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Billboards, said ad-man Schwartz, are a difficult medium. ``I
love them and hate them at the same time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While he checks out the billboards along Highway 101, he
acknowledged that he does sometimes take an alternate route down
the Peninsula. ``Highway 280 is beautiful,'' he said, ``for its
absence of billboards.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-98 1930EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981220.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-20 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9330 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-XILINX-SFCHRON-XILINX     12-20 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XILINX-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON - XILINX  
 XILINX'S TINY CHIPS GET WITH THE PROGRAM  &HT;     By Dan Fost 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Xilinx stock may not seem like a big winner compared to many
Internet issues. After all, it only doubled in the past three
months.
</P>
<P>
   But the San Jose company, which makes cheap, tiny chips that can
be programmed to do almost anything the customer wants, is poised
for ``explosive growth,'' said Mark Edelstone, a semiconductor
analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Xilinx's chips don't go into personal computers, but they do go
lots of other places _ into networking, telecommunications and
factory equipment and medical instruments, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a Xilinx chip in a German coffee-maker that's
networked to a milk dispenser and an electronic cash terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Xilinx's products are known as field programmable gate arrays,
or FPGAs, and complex programmable logic devices, or CPLDs.
Customers can program these chips to do all sorts of things, making
them much more flexible than preprogrammed chips sold by companies
like Intel or LSI Logic.
</P>
<P>
   Xilinx chief executive Willem ``Wim'' Roelandts, 53, said the
chips cost about $10 apiece, which is making them affordable for
more and more uses.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 10 years, every electronic device will contain programmable
chips,'' Roelandts predicted.
</P>
<P>
   When he joined the company in early 1996, after a 30-year career
at Hewlett-Packard, Xilinx ``felt like Intel in the early 1970s,''
the Belgian-born Roelandts said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts share his view of Xilinx's  &LR; the company's potential.
</P>
<P>
   Xilinx's earnings for fiscal 1999, which ends in March, are
expected to be around $1.60 per share _ about the same as last
year. But Edelstone forecasts earnings of $2.20 per share in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Xilinx stock is up 100 percent since August 31, outperforming
chip giant Intel, which is up 68.5 percent in the same time frame.
Shares in Altera Corp., a Xilinx rival also based in San Jose, is
up 91 percent _ reflecting broad interest in programmable chips.
</P>
<P>
   Edelstone expects Xilinx stock, which closed at $61.25 Friday,
to climb as high as $80 in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the company has laid the foundation for the last two
years that should give it a springboard to accelerated growth over
the next two or three years,'' Edelstone said. Xilinx will be
cutting expenses at the same time, he said, improving profit
margins.
</P>
<P>
   Roelandts' task from the moment he arrived has been to recover
market share Xilinx lost to Altera.
</P>
<P>
   Xilinx invented the FPGA, and Altera invented the CPLD, which
have similar uses. According to Roelandts, Altera did a better job
of moving in on Xilinx customers than Xilinx did stealing business
from Altera.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took our eyes off the ball,'' Roelandts said. ``We were not
as aggressive as we could have been.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies are also locked in an intellectual property
lawsuit that's dragged on for four years. Edelstone said no
resolution is near, and even if it is resolved, it's not likely to
have a major impact on either company's business.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Roelandts said he wanted the company to focus on developing
new products rather than the court case.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the company unveiled its Virtex product line, which
puts 1 million tiny gates &UR;  &LR; on a chip, twice as many as its previous
product. The more gates, the more functions you can program onto a
chip.
</P>
<P>
   But Xilinx has only sold $1 million worth of Virtex chips since
they hit the market in October, and Roelandts said it will take a
while before the new product takes hold.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; By 2002 or 2003, Roelandts expects it  &LR; the chip to bring in
more than $500 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Roelandts has relocated his office twice in the past three
years, moving from building to building at Xilinx, in order to stay
close to the employees and the production process.
</P>
<P>
   ``By being among the troops, I get a first-hand feel for how
they enjoy themselves, how they feel. You don't have that if you
create the isolation of paneled offices.''
</P>
<P>
   Edelstone praised Roelandts' leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wim has done a great job of helping take the company to the
next level,'' he said. ``He's got a good team around him, and
that's played a big part of helping the company refocus its
energy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-98 1931EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981220.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-20 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9331 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-XILINX-SFCHRON-XILINX     12-20 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XILINX-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON - XILINX  
 XILINX'S TINY CHIPS GET WITH THE PROGRAM  &HT;     By Dan Fost 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
