<DOCNO> NYT19981220.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-20 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9332 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERNIE-SFCHRON-BERNIE     12-20 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERNIE-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON - BERNIE  
 TV PIONEER STILL CHIPPING AWAY  &HT;     By Dan Fost 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bernie Vonderschmitt just bought nine television sets to furnish
his newly built home, but none of them are high definition TVs.
</P>
<P>
   This is only noteworthy because Vonderschmitt was one of the
pioneers of color television technology, holding 13 patents.
</P>
<P>
   But Vonderschmitt is a little more skeptical of the tube's next
frontier.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  People wanted color television, he said. The demand is not
yet there for HDTV: The sets cost too much, he said,  &LR; there's not
much programming yet, and the untrained eye can barely detect a
difference unless it's side-by-side with a regular TV, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take some time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as television has changed, so too has Vonderschmitt. Now
75, he'd much rather talk about his second career as co-founder and
chairman of the San Jose semiconductor company Xilinx.
</P>
<P>
   He launched the company 15 years ago when he was 60, an age when
many people are retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still very sharp, let me tell you,'' said Wim Roelandts,
who has succeeded Vonderschmitt as chief executive of Xilinx.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Forbes ASAP magazine included Vonderschmitt on its list
of the 100 wealthiest people in technology, although he slipped off
the list this year.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes noted Vonderschmitt's reputation as ``one of the true
gentlemen in the chip business.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Mark Edelstone of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter called him
``a phenomenal individual, one of the true class acts in the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Vonderschmitt grew up in Indiana and earned his electrical
engineering degree from the Rose-Hulman Institute of Technology in
Terra Haute, Ind., in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   He went straight to work at RCA in New Jersey, where the
legendary David Sarnoff was leading the early charge into
television, but three months later Vonderschmitt joined the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   He worked as an electronics officer for two years, &LR;  and returned
to RCA in 1946. The company soon began working on broadcasting in
color, and Vonderschmitt was on the team.
</P>
<P>
   RCA, which was then the parent of NBC, flopped with its early
demonstrations of color TV. The pictures featured green lips and
blue bananas, according to Joel Brinkley in the book ``Defining
Vision.'' But CBS had an even worse solution, Vonderschmitt
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``CBS wanted to put a big disk in front of the set,'' he said.
``It would spin, and you'd get virtual color. But if that got away
in the house, people would get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   The adoption of color took many years, finally catching on in
the 1960s. Around that time, Vonderschmitt moved to the solid state
division, in which transistors replaced clunky old vacuum tubes in
TV sets.
</P>
<P>
   By 1973, he was running the division. When RCA was sold to
General Electric, his division was a $500-million-a-year operation,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; At age 58, he could easily have retired. But Vonderschmitt
decided not to let the picture fade out.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he went back to school, earning a master's in business
administration from Rider University in Lawrenceville, N.J. He also
earned the chartered financial analyst designation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just a scientist and engineer,'' he said with
characteristic humility. ``That's a terrible introduction to the
business world.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduation he moved to California and joined Zilog, then a
small chipmaking division of Exxon. Within three years he and two
colleagues split from Zilog to form their own chip firm, Xilinx.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind Xilinx was programmable logic _ chips that
engineers could tweak for their own purposes. Vonderschmitt was
inspired by the success that Wilf Corrigan was having at LSI Logic.
Xilinx co-founder Ross Freeman, a brilliant engineer, put his own
spin on it.
</P>
<P>
   They raised some money and, in February 1984, launched the
company. Freeman died five years later, at age 40, of complications
from a disease he originally contracted serving in the Peace Corps
in Africa. Jim Barnett, the other founder, left the company six
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Vonderschmitt relinquished the chief executive title in 1996.
``I had served my term in purgatory,'' he said. &UR;  &LR; He hired
Hewlett-Packard veteran Roelandts as president and CEO, and stayed
on as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Vonderschmitt also serves on about eight other corporate boards
and remains active with his alma mater, Rose-Hulman. He has a
condominium in Silicon Valley, but is putting the finishing touches
on a house he's built on 280 acres near Evansville, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   He leases out most of the land, which is farmed for corn, wheat,
beans and hay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contrast between here in Silicon Valley and there is day
and night,'' he said. ``In the valley, there's still a frenzy.''
</P>
<P>
   But for this septuagenarian, even the tranquility of rural
Indiana isn't exactly relaxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got so many things to do there,'' he said. ``A conference
call, preparing for a board meeting, watching the stock market.
Retirement is hardly retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of BERNIE21 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
