<SLUG> BC-NETFILES-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NET FILES/JON SWART 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - NET FILES   Web's Force Just Keeps On Growing 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet continued to magically weave its way into the
American fabric in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Online stocks soared, millions logged on and lawmakers embraced
the medium with Web-friendly bills. There were problems, to be sure
_ free speech took some body blows and several startups bit the
dust _ but the Web remains a remarkable societal force whose
influence will grow.
</P>
<P>
   Here is one person's take on the year's winners and losers.
</P>
<P>
   WINNERS
</P>
<P>
   _America Online. From Web pariah to powerhouse in just two
years, AOL emerged as a dominant force. With its $4.2 billion
acquisition of Netscape Communications, the world's largest online
service is in position to lord over the multibillion-dollar market
for e-commerce and online advertising.
</P>
<P>
   _Internet stocks. A conga line of Net ventures struck it rich on
Wall Street _ many by simply showing up. Inktomi, eBay and
Broadcast.com have made nary a dime, but their combined market
value is a stratospheric $12.6 billion. One analyst even predicted
that Amazon.com could top (gulp) $400 per share. Indeed, the market
was so receptive that even a pair of companies that postponed their
IPOs _ Xoom.com and theglobe.com _ eventually made off with a
bundle.
</P>
<P>
   _Matt Drudge. Reluctantly, we nod our notepad to the Net's
nattering nabob of nastiness. Unconstrained by pesky journalistic
standards, the Drudge Report ``broke'' the Monica Lewinsky scandal
after Newsweek had done all the reporting. Drudge was the first to
disclose the ``cigar'' story and, hey, he got his own TV show on
Fox.
</P>
<P>
   _Legislation. The Internet gladly read Congress' lips this fall,
when legislators passed a three-year moratorium on no  &LR; new Net
taxes. What's more, it approved a three-year increase in the number
of foreign workers who can be hired under H-1B &LR; H1-B visas and
rubber-stamped a digital copyright act.
</P>
<P>
   _Web performance. It withstood the Starr Report and a citywide
blackout, and just kept chugging away. The Internet grew to more
than 100 million users worldwide this year, while avoiding
wide-scale brownouts that many skeptics had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   _Salon. The plucky Net zine consistently scooped its traditional
media brethren with insightful, hard-hitting pieces. Special kudos
for exposing hypocritical House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., who bayed for President Clinton's head while
conveniently overlooking his own extramarital fling in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   _Infoseek. The Wonderful World of Disney, indeed. The Internet
media company, overshadowed by South Bay neighbors Yahoo and
Excite, quickly made a splash by selling a 43 percent stake to Walt
Disney Co. to create a super site of dynamite news, sports and
e-commerce content. Nothing Mickey Mouse about this deal.
</P>
<P>
   LOSERS
</P>
<P>
   _Microsoft. The software behemoth and its CEO, megabillionaire
Bill Gates, were vilified in a landmark antitrust lawsuit filed by
the Justice Department. By then, however, Microsoft had carved up
Netscape like a Christmas turkey, essentially forcing its premature
sale to AOL. Congrats on helping kill an Internet pioneer, Mr. Bill
&AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   _Netscape. Self-inflicted wounds and tough competition
accelerated the downfall of cyberspace's Camelot. It's a pity. The
company that made ``Web browsing'' a household phrase deserved a
better fate than becoming the West Coast operations of AOL,
nicknamed ``the cockroach of cyberspace'' by the digital elite.
</P>
<P>
   _Atbigger.net. The dysfunctional Internet service provider,
wracked by money and management problems, left thousands of
subscribers without Web access when it abruptly pulled the plug on
operations this fall. Brigadoon.com _ itself a victim of Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection _ acquired the remnants in a bankruptcy fire
sale. Atbigger.net had promised a lifetime Internet account for
$60: It lasted two years.
</P>
<P>
   _Free speech. They trampled the First Amendment in a Sacramento
courtroom last month, and seriously endangered free speech on the
Internet. A superior court judge barred Ken Hamidi, a disgruntled
ex-Intel employee, from sending thousands of e-mails critical of
the chipmaker. The decision has sent a chilling message to
cyber-rights activists. Funny, I thought the Internet was supposed
to be a major new source of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   _Legislation. For all the high-tech gains on Capitol Hill, there
was The Child Online Protection Act. &UR;  &LR; It imposes criminal penalties
on commercial Web sites that allow anyone under 18 to access
pornographic material deemed ``harmful to minors.'' Violators would
face up to $50,000 in fines and six months in jail. Civil-liberties
groups immediately challenged the constitutionality of the law in
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   _Healtheon. The third time wasn't necessarily the charm for Jim
Clark, the high-tech legend who founded Silicon Graphics and
Netscape. A planned IPO for his latest venture, online health care
service resource Healtheon, was pulled at the 11th-hour in October.
At the time, the Santa Clara company blamed a sickly market for the
delay. The prognosis for &UR;  &LR; another offering? Cautious.
</P>
<P>
   _PointCast. This wasn't a fall from grace: It was a free-fall.
From the toast of the Internet, hyping ``push'' technology, to the
subject of an unflattering Ken Auletta piece in The New Yorker.
Can't get more dire than that.
</P>
<P>
   _Zapata. An oil-exploration-company-turned-fish-oil-concern
founded by former President George Bush decided to dive into the
Internet market with two dozen acquisitions to pump up its stock.
The hair-brained &LR;   &LR; harebrained scheme soon devolved into stitching
those Web sites into a super portal site like some Frankenstein
monster. The plan was ditched within months. Calling Dr. Kevorkian.
</P>
<P>
   _Digicash. OK, let me get this straight. Anyone who used the
company's electronic cash for an online transaction _ whether
customer, bank or merchant _ needed to use special software. That's
an enormous obstacle for a high-tech startup, and a big reason
Digicash filed for Chapter 11 last month.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Site of the Week
</P>
<P>
   For a rip-roaring time, go to
 &LR; www.wwwvoice.com/bud/crazyjoe.html &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
