</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-BRONCOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLPHINS STILL NEED A WIN AGAINST BRONCOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Some of the marquee value of Monday night's game between
the Denver Broncos and Miami Dolphins is gone, courtesy of last
week's upset of the Broncos by the Giants. Yet the game is not
lacking for drama, at least with the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   With Denver's first loss after a 13-0 start, members of the 1972
Dolphins no longer have to put a hex on the Broncos to remain the
only team in National Football League history to go through a
season unbeaten.
</P>
<P>
   Miami must win Monday night to assure itself a wild-card playoff
spot because the New York Jets clinched the American Football
Conference East title last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Miami (9-5) has been dealing with the effects of its loss to
those same Jets a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one has stuck with us a while,'' linebacker Robert Jones
said. ``But we realize if we beat Denver, that's what everybody
will be talking about, and the loss to the Jets will be
forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Broncos have clinched home-field advantage throughout
the playoffs, Monday night's game for them has been reduced to one
of pride and momentum contrasted to Miami's urgency.
</P>
<P>
   Denver Coach Mike Shanahan has shown no inclination to ease off
the throttle, though he most likely will not take any chance with
the standout defensive end Neil Smith, who is healing from an
abdominal pull.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Broncos said they felt the loss lifted a burden off
their shoulders and that the team could now focus more on repeating
as Super Bowl champions than challenging the 1972 Dolphins' 17-0
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure was building each week,'' Smith said. ``I'm glad
it's over. We have to go on with business.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be only the second regular-season meeting between the
teams, and the first here. Miami won by 30-26 in 1985 when John
Elway and Dan Marino were mere third-year pros.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, they are two of the most decorated quarterbacks
in league history. Never before has there been an NFL game between
two quarterbacks who have compiled such glittering statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Marino (58,238) and Elway (50,986) are the only two 50,000-yard
career passers. They have combined for 699 passing touchdowns,
including Marino's 403, and have totaled nearly 9,000 completions.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the fanfare about their matchup, Marino comes into
this game dragging some not-so-subtle shackles. He is acutely
mindful that he must temper his passing to accommodate Miami's
sporadic running game. After Marino threw 57 times in the loss to
the Jets, Coach Jimmy Johnson bluntly said that forsaking the
running game had been a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Miami, which has used nearly an equal split between running and
passing this season, is 2-8 in games in which Marino has thrown at
least 51 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the year, people talked about us winning ugly, but
those games look pretty now,'' the offensive coordinator Kippy
Brown said. ``We're going to get back to doing what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is Denver that will offer the game's top runner. Terrell
Davis needs 199 yards in the last two regular-season games to
become only the fourth NFL rusher to reach 2,000 in a season,
joining O.J. Simpson, Eric Dickerson and Barry Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``On film, you can see why he has so many yards,'' the Dolphins'
Jones said. ``He can see from tackle to tackle, and that's why his
change of direction is so good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins built up some anger for this game late last week
after Denver had nine players named to the Pro Bowl against only
one for them _ defensive tackle Tim Bowens, a mystery pick since
even he acknowledged he did not deserve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little extra motivation, because we can get a little
respect here,'' said linebacker Zach Thomas, whose 149 tackles lead
Miami. ``But we had a meeting to throw a lot of that behind us.
What it comes down to, our total focus is we need to win this
game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
