u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PRAYERS-BOS &LR;      12-20 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PRAYERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIRITUAL ADVISER ASKS PRAYERS FOR CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER AND DANIEL VASQUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Mass. _ Less than 24 hours after the US House of
Representatives marked the Clinton presidency with the stain of
scandal, his spiritual adviser stood in a house of worship Sunday
and implored heaven for help.
</P>
<P>
   His head bowed and his eyes shut, the Rev. Gordon MacDonald,
senior pastor of Grace Chapel, said the impeached president and the
country he still leads need prayers, not partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pray for the president, for his wisdom, and for those who
advise him that they may understand what steps to take in the
coming days that will be best for our country,'' said MacDonald,
one of three clergymen on the spiritual team Clinton assembled in
the wake of the Monica S. Lewinsky scandal that culminated in
Saturday's impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pray for those in the Senate and the House, for those who
will have to sit in judgment in the coming weeks about the future
of our president and we ask, oh God, that men and women will rise
to the highest possible level of statesmanship; that partisanship
of any kind will be set aside and that wisdom will prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Divine guidance was sought from pulpits and church lecterns
throughout the region Sunday after the House's historic
condemnation of Clinton, whose friendship with MacDonald stems from
the 1988 book the pastor wrote about his own adultery and his
repentance for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``All around us there is anger, chaos, and destruction,''
Cardinal Bernard Law said Sunday during a crowded Mass at the
Cathedral of the Holy Cross, referring to the bombing of Iraq and
what he termed character assassination on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Law spoke of the pain and costs associated with the prolonged US
embargo against Iraq and recent bomb attacks, but also focused on
the Clinton crisis, saying there is no room for polarized
bipartisan politics. He asked Americans to have faith in a
political process ``that allows us to deal with these serious
charges.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Impeachment is now a fact,'' Law said. ``This is a painful
time for us as a nation. But we can survive it and be strengthened
by it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Oxford, the Rev. Gerard P. Walsh, pastor of St. Roch Roman
Catholic Church, urged his parishioners to use the Christmas season
as a salve for the healing of the national spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's turmoil in Washington and we should draw together,''
Walsh said after services. ``People need to be reconciled. We are
now a splintered nation. People feel very strongly one way or the
other on this and we need that process of healing, especially at
this point when people have become so polarized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas is a time to heal. We need to put this behind us. .
.''
</P>
<P>
   After an hour-long service of Christmas music in a brightly lit
sanctuary decorated with holiday greens and poinsettia, MacDonald
said his congregation of 2,500 _ New England's largest evangelical
church _ has been ``torn up'' by the scandal and its fallout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fabric of unity of our country is under great threat,''
MacDonald said. ``We're a people who believe in prayer, so we've
got to pray that God is going to allow this process over the months
to provincially work out to the best for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald, who said he has spoken with Clinton ``quite
frequently'' in recent weeks, added: ``I'm just heartbroken this
weekend watching the lives of people broken _ and the hatred. I
don't like the partisanship and I just feel that a lot of things
are out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald, a much sought-after motivational speaker, is joined
in Clinton's accountability circle by the Rev. Tony Campolo, a
professor at Eastern College in Pennsylvania, and the Rev. J.
Philip Wogaman, pastor of the United Methodist Church where the
first family frequently worships.
</P>
<P>
   ``On both sides of the aisle, we're watching the consequences of
people's philosophies and the tragedy of the consequences of
people's acts,'' MacDonald said. ``It's a great theological lesson
to me. Some day we'll be able to talk about this and see the end of
the story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
