<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-VOTE-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  PA LAWMAKERS MIRROR CONGRESS IN VOTES TO IMPEACH CLINTON
</P>
<P>
   By Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec. 19, -- Pennsylvania Republican Congress members
voted to impeach President Clinton, despite protest from embattled
Democrats in the state delegation, who walked out briefly with
their party in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Mirroring Congress, lawmakers from the state voted essentially
along party lines to impeach President Clinton for obstruction of
justice and lying under oath about his relationship with Monica
Lewinsky. Rep. Chaka Fattah, D-Philadelphia started the tumultuous
day by speaking out against character assassination-style politics.
His remarks followed Speaker-designate Bob Livingston's resignation
at the heels of admitting extra-marital affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are seeing is the politics of personal destruction,''
Fattah said. ``How many other speakers have to resign? It is an
example of the hatred that eats at the Republican party that led us
to this impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Philadelphia, who voted to impeach Clinton,
said it was as a ``sad day for the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a difficult day for me and my colleagues,'' Weldon
said. ``I am not convinced that the President's act of perjury mean
that he should be removed from office.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he believes under the constitution, the House of
Representatives does not have the power to censure a president.
</P>
<P>
   Fattah was joined by Reps. Bob Borski, D-Philadelphia, John
Murtha, D-Johnstown, and Bob Brady, D-Philadelphia, when members of
the party walked out after Republican House leaders denied
considering a censure alternative to impeachment. The Democrats
streamed outside the Capitol and walked in front of onlookers,
cheering visitors and television cameras. Shortly after that, they
returned to the House floor to vote on the articles of impeachment.
``It was the only way to visually show our displeasure,'' Fattah
said. ``Many from our state delegation joined me out there.'' With
one member bucking party lines, several remaining undecided until
the final hour, and others adhering fiercely to party loyalty,
Pennsylvania's delegation became a cross-section of Congress in the
impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, outgoing Rep. Paul McHale, D-Lehigh Valley, who
was the first Democrat in the House of Representatives to call for
the resignation of the president, said the right thing was done for
the nation. ``The system worked today as our founding fathers
intended,'' said McHale, who voted for impeachment. ``On a personal
level, I'm drained. I voted for Clinton twice. I had few policy
differences with him. Had he admitted what he had done and come
forward with it, I would have perhaps voted differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Bud Shuster, R-Everett, supported impeachment for the second
time in his Congressional career.
</P>
<P>
   As a freshman Congress member in 1974, Shuster intended to vote
to impeach Republican President Richard Nixon, had he not resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty four years later, Shuster, who waited until the last
minute to make up his mind, voted to impeach Clinton. ``[This] I
believe demonstrates my belief that a constitutional issue of this
gravity should not be decided on a partisan basis,'' Shuster said.
-30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-98 1959EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
