<DOCNO> NYT19981220.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-20 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9361 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-GOP-BOS &LR;      12-20 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-GOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISSUES IMPACT GOP PRESIDENTIAL HOPEFULS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two conflicting messages about sex and politics
have emerged from the extraordinary events of this past weekend,
and they could have a direct effect on Campaign 2000, particularly
the Republican presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   First, members of both parties seemed to agree that they wanted
to put the ``politics of personal destruction'' behind them. That
led some analysts to conclude that candidates in the next election
should have less fear that their opponents will try to make an
issue out of their personal and sexual lives.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, the resignation of Speaker-designate
Robert L. Livingston indicated conservative Republicans may insist
that GOP candidates pass a ``marital fidelity test,'' as one party
member put it. While plenty of Republicans decried Livingston's
resignation, it was widely hailed within the party as necessary
because he had committed adultery.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying these crosscurrents are polls showing the vast
majority of Americans are upset with the Republican Party for the
way it pushed the impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be retribution and the retribution is going
to be at the polling place,'' Clinton politicalstrategist James
Carville said Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press.'' ``We are going to
storm the polling places in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   While Carville's prediction was partisan, there are GOP fears of
a backlash, particularly against those who led the impeachment
effort. That may improve the chances of the party's presumed
presidential front-runner, Texas Governor George W. Bush, whose
``outsider'' credentials may be enhanced because he can argue that
he played no role in the impeachment fights.
</P>
<P>
   But some Republicans privately wonder whether these same events
will convince Bush to stay out of the race. He has said he doesn't
know whether he wants to subject his family to the scrutiny and
pressure that would inevitably follow. While the odds are still
good that he will run, surprises seem the order of the day and
prognostication is becoming an increasingly tough business, given
what happened with Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we going to have a new test if someone wants to run for
public office: Are you now or have you ever been an adulterer?''
Representative Jerrold Nadler, a New York Democrat, asked during
the impeachment debate, reflecting a growing concern among many
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   These questions are not new. They began in earnest when a
reporter asked Democratic presidential candidate Gary Hart in 1987
whether he had committed adultery, and Hart declined to answer. But
such questions utimately drove Hart from the race and played a
major role in the 1992 presidential campaign, when Gennifer Flowers
said she had an affair with Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton denied the story until last January, when he admitted
having had sex with Flowers, once. At the same time, however,
Clinton said in a January deposition in the Paula Jones sexual
harassment case that he did not have sexual relations with former
White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky, a statement which set in
motion the events leading to his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you think it can't get worse, it does,'' said Paul
Taylor, the former Washington Post reporter who asked Hart the
adultery question, and who now runs the nonprofit Alliance for
Better Campaigns. ``It has to be a frightening prospect if you are
a candidate for high office in this country to have to calibrate
how intrusively the popular media culture is going to probe in your
private life.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony of all this is that polls show the vast majority of
voters have taken Clinton's misleading statements about
extra-marital affairs into account and still support him, even as
GOP leaders on Capitol Hill have taken the same information and
decided to make it the centerpiece of their agenda. While
Republicans point out that they impeached Clinton for perjury and
obstruction of justice, and not for having sex outside his
marriage, the party's conservative wing underscored its concern
about adultery by hailing Livingston's decision to resign.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is important for the GOP presidential race because
the party's candidate is expected to be chosen during a compressed
primary campaign in February and March 2000, which is likely to be
controlled by the party's conservative base.
</P>
<P>
   As the impeachment effort and the resignation of two Republican
House speakers in the past two months demonstrated, conservatives
hold sway over the party. Some have already raised questions about
Bush's ideological credentials, which they consider too moderate.
He has called himself a ``compassionate conservative,'' a label
likely to be more helpful if he gets to the general election than
it would be during a primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush were to pull out of the race, it would create a
free-for-all among other contenders, most of whom stand to his
right. These include Senator John Ashcroft of Missouri, former vice
president Dan Quayle, publisher Steve Forbes, and former Reagan
aide Gary Bauer of the Family Research Council. Another likely
candidate, former education secretary Lamar Alexander, calls
himself a conservative but is not arguing too strongly with those
who see him as a moderate, acknowledging he prefers not to discuss
abortion unless he is asked about it.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, in a recent interview, said Republicans did poorly in
the 1998 midterm elections because they focused too much on
Clinton. While he said Clinton should be impeached, Quayle added
that the party has to stand for much more. As it stands now,
however, Republicans may spend months focused on the president's
trial, leaving even less time to push a GOP agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost this last campaign because we did not focus on the
issues,'' Quayle said. ``We did not communicate directly what we
are willing to do. To compound that, there is a tendency to draw
the wrong lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle said one wrong lesson is that the GOP only needs to be
more pragmatic in order to be successful. ``Pragmatism is not a
platform,'' Quayle said. ``Pragmatism is not an agenda. We need to
be conservative. We are a conservative party.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, the events of the past weekend could
help Vice President Al Gore, who is seen as loyal to Clinton's
policies while not having many of his personal problems. Already,
Senator Bob Kerrey of Nebraska has dropped out of the race, in part
due to Gore's political and fund-raising strength.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John Kerry of Massachusetts, meanwhile, plans to ponder
the matter during a Christmas vacation at his Sun Valley home,
combining a ski trip with family discussions about whether he
should run for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry said in a recent interview that he is considering setting
up an exploratory committee, which would enable him to raise money
for a presidential campaign, and he plans to visit the first-caucus
state of Iowa in January. He said he expects to make a decision in
January or early February at the latest.
</P>
<P>
   Former senator Bill Bradley of New Jersey and Senator Paul
Wellstone of Minnesota also are exploring bids for the Democratic
nomination. House minority leader Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri
is expected to pass so he can focus on a party takeover of the
House in 2000 and his own dream of becoming speaker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
