<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GASOUTHERN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite tough loss, Eagles' future bright
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The morning after his top-ranked team suddenly became
fumble-prone and more porous than usual on defense in suffering a
55-43 loss to Massachusetts in the Division I-AA championship game,
Georgia Southern coach Paul Johnson was trying to put the past
behind while looking to the future.
</P>
<P>
   According to Johnson, who guided Georgia Southern to a 14-0
record and to the brink of the school's fifth national title before
Saturday's collapse at Finley Stadium in Chattanooga, offseason
efforts will be made to strengthen the defense.
</P>
<P>
   But against UMass (12-3), which converted seven Georgia Southern
turnovers into 31 points, no big defensive stops likely would have
helped bail out an offense that self-destructed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get to the point where we're more balanced _
where our defense is more in line with our offense,'' Johnson said.
``I'm not saying that because of Saturday. We've been inconsistent
(on defense) all season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, younger and more inexperienced on defense, were
particularly vulnerable at the linebacker spots. Because of
injuries, only one linebacker called upon to start the last few
games was on the two-deep chart at the top of the season. And it
never stopped UMass tailback Marcel Shipp, who gained 244 of UMass'
303 rushing yards.
</P>
<P>
   With the return of starters Daryl Morrell and Larry Rogers, the
growth and development of freshman Michael Youngblood, and the
addition of two players who were redshirted this season, that part
of the defense will be much improved next season, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lose only three starters on defense,'' Johnson said.
``We'll get those young linebackers, three defensive linemen and
two secondary players we redshirted.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Southern's offense, spearheaded by junior quarterback
Greg Hill and fullback Adrian Peterson, was its usual high-octane
self. But what was different for the Eagles on Saturday were the
turnovers. Hill's 228-yard, two-touchdown effort, along with
Peterson's 161 yards and two-TD performance, was overshadowed by
the collective seven turnovers between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like a psychiatrist down there on the sidelines talking
to those guys,'' Johnson said. ``Greg was looking like he was about
to cry any minute. I told him, `Hey, if it wasn't for you, we
wouldn't be here.' '' While Peterson set nearly 40 national,
conference and school records in rushing for 2,606 yards and 34
touchdowns, Hill accounted for 1,587 yards and 24 TDs on the ground
and passed for 1,638 yards and 11 TDs. They are two of seven
starters who will return to the Eagles offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told our players that we'll be back (in the championship
game),'' Johnson said. ``I think we've laid a pretty foundation.
We've got a good nucleus and we should be pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
