<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-MAYWEATHER-DISPUTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 FIGHTERS ARE FURIOUS WITH REFEREES IN DEFEAT
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Hasim Rahman and Angel Manfredy both claimed to be
victims of crimes in the ring here last Saturday night. They both
believe they were robbed. But they would have a better chance of
getting assault charges filed against their opponents than theft
charges against the referees.
</P>
<P>
   Rahman, pinned between the second and third ropes, was being
pummeled by David Tua when the referee, Telis Assemenios, stepped
in to stop the heavyweight bout at 35 seconds of the 10th round.
Manfredy, also pinned against the ropes, was being battered by
Floyd Mayweather Jr. when the referee, Frank Santore, stopped their
bout at 2 minutes 47 seconds of the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Rahman (29-1) feels more victimized than Manfredy (24-3-1) does
because Rahman was leading on all three judges' scorecards when the
bout was stopped. And he had the presence of mind to react angrily
when Assemenios called a halt to the fight, although Rahman did a
zigzag stagger as he walked back to his corner. Manfredy seemed
dazed as he headed back to his corner. Later he said politics and
the desire to see Mayweather retain his World Boxing Council super
featherweight title played heavily in the referee's decision to
stop the bout.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a strong argument, considering that Mayweather
(19-0), a bronze medalist for the U.S. boxing team in the 1996
Olympics, landed 56 of 120 punches he threw in the two rounds and
landed 45 of 86 power punches, according to CompuBox statistics.
Manfredy landed just 19 of 86 punches thrown and connected with
just three jabs.
</P>
<P>
   The Rahman stoppage caused a greater furor among the fans, who
threw ice and debris into the ring after the bout was stopped.
Rahman was in control until a heavy-handed assault by Tua (33-1) in
the ninth round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Rahman was a premature stoppage,'' said Ron Scott
Stevens, a matchmaker for Rahman's promoter, Cedric Kushner. ``The
referee should have given Rahman a standing 8-count. If Rahman
didn't respond or couldn't go on, then the referee still would have
been in a position to stop it. It was a little league call in a
major league fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Nelson, Rahman's co-manager, said he planned to file a
protest with the International Boxing Federation, which sanctioned
the bout, on the grounds that the stoppage was premature and
because Tua had hit Rahman after the bell in the previous round.
That blow hurt Rahman, and it carried over into the next round. Had
Rahman's corner vehemently protested the late blow, it could have
got a five-minute rest for its fighter. After the punch, Tua's
trainer, Lou Duva, made a noisy protest in the ring to Assemenios
that the punch was not late.
</P>
<P>
   If the protest succeeds, then the IBF can order a rematch. But
if it fails, then Tua will become the No. 1 contender for the IBF
heavyweight championship, awaiting the outcome of the unification
bout between Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis on March 13 at
Madison Square Garden. With a World Boxing Association defense up
first for the Holyfield-Lewis winner, it could be early 2000 before
Tua gets a title shot.
</P>
<P>
   Mayweather stopped Manfredy in his tracks and put a crimp in his
plans to rule the 130-pound division. Mayweather, 21, is trained by
his father, Floyd Sr., once a promising welterweight, and his uncle
Roger Mayweather, a former world champion in two weight classes.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Arum, the promoter of Top Rank Boxing, has laid out an
ambitious schedule for Mayweather for the early part of 1999. He
will defend his title in his hometown of Grand Rapids, Mich., in
February. In April he will defend it against Julio Cesar Chavez,
and in June he will go against Goyo Vargas.
</P>
</TEXT>
