<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HASTERT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASTERT HAS EARLY HOLD ON HOUSE SPEAKER'S JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ His many supporters call him a peacemaker, a
bridge-builder, a mentor. The man in line to be the next speaker of
the House of Representatives, says one political ally, ``is a Teddy
bear.''
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake. Representative J. Dennis Hastert can be a
grizzly.
</P>
<P>
   In a lightning-fast, one-day show of politicking, Hastert on
Saturday made himself the presumptive speaker for the next
Congress, only hours after the stunning resignation of the
Republicans' first choice, Robert L. Livingston. Hastert has not
formally been elected but any competitor would face long odds.
</P>
<P>
   His backers said Sunday that he has already accumulated enough
votes to ensure election. And Republicans across the ideological
spectrum said his team-building ability _ some still call him
``coach'' from his days as a wrestling teacher _ makes the Illinois
Republican the right man to lead a chamber that has been riven by
the impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have to be the star,'' said Representative David
Hobson, Republican of Ohio. ``He doesn't have to be in the
limelight all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   With his gray hair and rumpled clothes, the former high school
history teacher can come across as a friendly uncle but he seems
unsuited to play the role of telegenic spokesman for the Republican
Party.
</P>
<P>
   He cuts a softer figure than the current speaker, the
often-bombastic Newt Gingrich. But those who work with him on
Capitol Hill say his conservatism and partisanship run just as
deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the capacity to bring Republicans together,'' said
Ronald Pollack, executive director of the health-reform group
Families USA, ``but I've never seen him give an inch, actually, to
bipartisanship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been responsible for keeping the Republicans organized
around their most important issues. But thus far, he has primarily
been a bridge-builder inside the Republican Party,'' said
Representative Edward Markey, Democrat of Massachusetts, implying
Hastert's reach toward the Democrats has been minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, 56, wins high grades from conservative groups like the
Christian Coalition, which this year gave him a perfect rating for
conservative votes on such issues as limiting abortion rights and
ending legal protections for homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he is a close ally and senior deputy to House whip Tom
DeLay, a divisive figure who resuscitated the effort to impeach
Clinton when other leaders had abandoned it. Some Democrats even
privately question whether Hastert will act as a front-man for
DeLay, a charge both men's supporters deny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you're speaker, you're speaker,'' Representative Tom
Ewing, another Illinois Republican, told the Associated Press.
``Denny is not considered to be a puppet.''
</P>
<P>
   A captain in many partisan battles, Hastert led the effort to
block the Democrats' ``Patient's Bill of Rights,'' which would have
imposed new requirements on health-maintenance organizations. And
he is a principal player in the GOP fight with the White House over
how to conduct the next census, a largely arcane dispute with high
stakes because it will determine the shape of new congressional
districts.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert was closeted in his Capitol office Sunday, working with
a group of lawmakers to solidify his support. His office claimed
135 ``firm public commitments'' to vote for him as speaker; he will
need only 112 of the 223 Republicans who will serve in the House
that convenes in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's making phone calls to thank his supporters,'' said
Hastert's spokesman, Peter Jeffries. ``He's taking a flood of phone
calls from well-wishers. He's signing a lot of thank-you notes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, who is heading into his seventh House term, represents
a rust belt district outside Chicago that has been given new
vitality by high-tech companies. Before he entered the House, he
was active in state politics. He has two sons.
</P>
<P>
   As chief deputy whip, Hastert's job has been to count votes on
legislation and stay in touch with Republican lawmakers. Within
minutes of Livingston's surprise announcement Saturday that he
would not stand for speaker because of his marital infidelities,
Hastert's allies congregated in his office.
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour, Jeffries said, more than 40 members had
approached Hastert to support him for speaker. By 7 p.m., his team
claimed enough votes to give him the job.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have tentatively set Jan. 5 to choose the next
speaker. Gingrich technically remains in the job until Jan. 6, but
he withdrew from the daily tasks of managing the House soon after
the GOP suffered unexpected losses in the Nov. 3 election.
</P>
<P>
   If he becomes speaker, Hastert's ability to mediate among
Republicans will be tested, as his party is sorely strained by
rifts between conservatives and moderates. But a capacity to reach
out to Democrats could be even more important.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans will have only an 11-vote majority in the next
House, making it nearly certain that GOP leaders will have to work
with members of both parties to pass legislation.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Hastert has shown mostly that he can bring together his
Republican troops. Earlier this year, for example, Clinton and
Democratic lawmakers were rallying around the ``Patient's Bill of
Rights,'' which would give Americans new powers when fighting with
their health insurers for coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich and other Republicans opposed the legislation. But by
mid-year, GOP pollsters warned that the bill was popular, and that
Republicans might pay at the polls if they blocked it.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert had been leading the House Republican effort on health
care, and a panel led by him soon produced a GOP alternative.
Still, the Republican bill was roundly criticized by health-reform
advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, Hastert's bill went backwards,'' stripping
patients of rights they already have, said Pollack of Families USA.
He said Hastert ``has not demonstrated that he's a bipartisan
bridge. He seems to almost always find his way toward rather
conservative ground, without achieving some kind of a middle
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Markey said he and Representative Thomas Bliley, a Virginia
Republican, were trying to find support this year for a bill that
brought greater competition to the satellite industry. The bill
failed in the Senate, but not before Hastert had rallied enough
Republicans to move it through the House Commerce Committee and the
full House.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, he's a masterful inside player,'' Markey said. ``He's a
consummate vote-counter.'' But so far, he has worked mostly within
the GOP ranks, Markey added.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more to the point _ as both parties enter a new year in
which the question of partisanship may be paramount _ was this
assessment Sunday by Representative J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, the
fourth-ranking House Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times that you've got to draw a line in the sand,''
Watts said on ABC's ``This Week'' program. ``I don't think Dennis
Hastert will be afraid to do that . . . I hope no one mistakes his
kindness as a weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   (Globe correspondent Louise D. Palmer contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
