<DOCNO> NYT19981220.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-20 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9390 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-GOVERN-BOS &LR;      12-20 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-GOVERN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHED PRESIDENT WILL BE ABLE TO GOVERN, AIDES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With President Clinton impeached and facing a
Senate trial, the White House says he will be able to govern, even
with a Republican-controlled House that closed ranks to try to
remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton himself said he is ``still committed to working with
people of good faith and good will of both parties to do what's
best for our country.''
</P>
<P>
   But assuming he remains in office for the final two years of his
term, political analysts predict that issues that build legacies,
like overhauling Social Security or Medicare, are likely to elude
Clinton this year due to the lack of a shared perspective with the
Republican-led Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that political gulf and the brittle feelings that exist
following impeachment, Clinton's senior aides Sunday expressed
confidence that Republicans facing tough reelection challenges in
2000 may want to work with the president.
</P>
<P>
   They said the advent of new GOP leaders in the next Congress may
produce more cooperation if the party seeks to reconstruct its
image, which has taken a beating, according to opinion polls,
because of the House Republicans' handling of the impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House has done a lot of damage to itself and there will be
incentive with the new leadership there to repair that damage and
foster a period of bipartisanship,'' said White House press
secretary Joseph Lockhart. ``That alone will be powerful incentive
for bipartisan cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said the first test of any such cooperation
will occur next month after the president unveils his poll-tested
agenda in his State of the Union address. His initiative is likely
to include proposals for overhauling Social Security, some health
care programs, and, perhaps, campaign finance laws, improving
public schools and sustaining the nation's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is going to continue to work on the agenda the
American public supports. Republicans who are in political danger
in the year 2000, I fully expect to join us in working on this
agenda,'' said Clinton senior adviser Doug Sosnik.
</P>
<P>
   As in years past, Clinton plans to travel around the country,
sometimes in the company of Vice President Al Gore, to promote his
policy priorities, following his State of the Union address and in
February, after he submits his 1999 budget to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, the Senate is likely to be holding a trial on
the two articles of impeachment passed Saturday by the House. White
House aides Sunday said they hoped that even if the trial starts,
it will not have to run its full course and that a move to censure
will occur.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the administration's optimism about Clinton's ability to
govern during a Senate trial, Robert Dallek, a presidential scholar
at Boston University, said that the likelihood of major legislative
accomplishments ``seems to be pretty questionable'' without what he
described as a ``strange conjunction of interests'' between him and
the Republican majority.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than cooperate with Clinton on his legislative
priorities, Dallek said, the possibility also exists that
Republicans will propose their own ideas, forcing Clinton to veto
them.
</P>
<P>
   Those vetoes, he said, could become the ``source of campaign
rhetoric for Republicans,'' who could use them to portray Clinton
as an ``unbending president who was wrongheaded.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlin Fitzwater, former press secretary to Presidents Reagan
and Bush, said that on the big issues, like Social Security and
Medicare, Clinton is likely to become the equivalent of a
``lame-duck'' president.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can pass the budgets, and do the basic work of
government, but anything that has political controversy or great
partisan differences my guess is they will come to a halt,''
Fitzwater said. ``It will be very tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzwater said that feelings between Republicans and Clinton
could further harden if the Senate aborts a trial before a vote on
conviction is taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a governing standpoint, he would be better off to go to
trial and get a no conviction vote at the end of the process than
he would to get a censure kind of plea-bargain arrangement,''
Fitzwater said.
</P>
<P>
   Senior White House aides said that though Clinton's relationship
with the Republican majority may be at a low point following his
impeachment, it has long been tenuous, especially with the party's
more conservative wing.
</P>
<P>
   Following the impeachment vote, Clinton said he ``wanted the
American people to know'' that he continued to be committed to
working with Republicans. ``It's what I've tried to do for six
years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Lockhart, the president's spokesman, said: ``The
president reached out a hand Sunday, and the question is whether
they will be smart enough to take it,'' adding: ``That's a high bar
for that group.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
