<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, A SIMPLE PLAYOFF SYSTEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If it were all this simple.
</P>
<P>
   Combining forces for the greater good of the game _ and, come
on, say it, for all mankind _ CBS SportsLine and The FANSonly
Network have whipped up a simulated 16-team college football
playoff that will determine a winner in the VCS _ the Virtual
Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Online College Football National Championship
(http://www.fansonly.com/virtual/) does use the final BCS poll, but
only to seed the teams and pit them in a single-elimination
tournament that ends on Jan. 4 in a Virtual Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The games are played with software called ``3-in-1 Football,'' a
computer simulation game produced by Lance Haffner Games
(http://www.lhgames.com). CBS SportsLine executive editor Mike Kahn
provides analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Since there are no final exams to take into consideration, the
tournament is already down to the final four. Tennessee and Ohio
State meet in the Rose Bowl and Florida State faces Kansas State in
the Sugar Bowl on Dec. 26. (K-State avenged its Big 12 Conference
title-game loss to Texas A&AMP;M with a 32-8 win.)
</P>
<P>
   As for UCLA, well, even in cyberspace, the Bruins' defense
crashes hard.
</P>
<P>
   In the first round two weeks ago, the fifth-seeded Bruins were
upset by 12th-seed Virginia 31-3 in the Holiday Bowl, which is the
gateway to the Citrus Bowl. Cade McNown was picked off twice and
sacked four times and the Bruins managed just 41 yards rushing.
Virginia's Thomas Jones ran for 92 yards and three TDs.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't you know, UCLA was the only team to lose to a
lower-seeded opponent in the first round. Must have been a residual
effect from the (begin ital)real(end ital) loss in Miami. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
