<HEADER>
A9404 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-BASRA-BOS &LR;      12-20 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-BASRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGHT SECURITY IN BASRA SHIELDS ANY POSSIBLE DISSENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BASRA, Iraq _ In the oil-rich plains 250 miles south of Baghdad,
US and British forces carried out concentrated air strikes that
could set the stage for a rebellion here against Saddam Hussein's
regime.
</P>
<P>
   On a tour Sunday of Basra, the city where Shiite Muslims mounted
a failed uprising in the wake of the 1991 Gulf War, Iraqi military
and intelligence officials made it impossible for reporters to
detect any signs of dissent.
</P>
<P>
   But the tight media control and the heavy Iraqi military
presence in the area revealed Saddam's sensitivity to a seething
opposition among Iraq's Shiite majority who live in the squalid mud
huts and modern slums that dot the alluvial plain between the
Tigris and Euphrates rivers.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Iraq's ambassador to the United Nations said
Sunday that the attacks had killed or wounded thousands of people.
According to the latest reports, at least 42 Iraqis were killed and
96 wounded in the strikes, the most severe since the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   The regime has effectively suppressed this opposition since the
end of the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   In the small towns along the Basra road Sunday, young Shiite men
waved bright green and red flags in a public display of loyalty by
southern Iraqi Shiite tribes to Saddam, while the tribal elders sat
under the traditional reed huts of these marshlands.
</P>
<P>
   The young men shouted pro-Saddam slogans for television cameras.
But diplomats here and opposition groups abroad say the public
support belies growing unrest in Iraq's Shiite south, explaining
that eight years of sanctions have eroded Saddam's authority and
increased dependence on the loyalty of tribal leaders.
</P>
<P>
   There have been sporadic incidents, including occasional
killings of government officials and the torching of two major
power stations last summer. Government troops have only limited
control after dark.
</P>
<P>
   Ghassan Attiya, publisher of the London-based opposition journal
Iraqi File, said, ``These tribes are very important. If they see a
chance of winning in a rebellion, even those who are working with
Saddam now will turn against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Attiya is a Shiite from a tribe near Basra. He added, ``But if
it comes, it would happen quickly. Until then it will be difficult
to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Basra lies inland on the confluence of the Euphrates and Tigris
rivers. The Shiite Muslim population, which makes up 60 percent of
Iraq's roughly 30 million people, is concentrated here.
</P>
<P>
   The Shiite movement, which was founded in Iraq in the Eighth
century, distinguishes itself from the Muslim world's Sunni
majority by its allegiance to religious leaders who are direct
descendents of the Prophet Mohammed. Saddam's secular regime is
built around the power base of the Baath Party, but is made up of
Baghdad's largely Sunni ruling elite.
</P>
<P>
   The Baghdad regime's tight control over the Shiite population is
evident. There are white stucco fortresses every few miles along
the Basra road with Islamic slogans stenciled on them. Military
officials maintain they are defensive positions to guard against
invasion. But the machine guns are pointed at the impoverished
Shiite villages on the opposite sides of the road.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's stated aim of four days of missile attacks was to
degrade Saddam's ability to produce chemical, nuclear and
biological weapons in the wake of his refusal to permit United
Nations weapons inspectors to carry out their work.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the chosen targets suggest an attempt to destabilize the
Saddam regime. One of the more obvious was the sprawling Baath
Party headquarters in downtown Baghdad, which absorbed at least
three direct hits from cruise missiles. They left the cluster of
buildings where some 500 of his political operatives worked in
charred skeletons.
</P>
<P>
   But many analysts in the region and in Washington stress that
the objectives were never clearly stated.
</P>
<P>
   One Western observer based in Baghdad asked in frustration,
``First of all, what was the objective of this campaign? What is
the real goal?''
</P>
<P>
   He also surmised that part of the long-term strategy appeared to
be the separation of the northern part of the country from the
southern part to help foment a rebellion against the Baghdad
regime. But he cautioned that this is a potentially dangerous path
because it could Balkanize the country along sectarian lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they have been thinking about this,'' he continued.
``Let's assume the Shiites overthrow Saddam and come to Baghdad. Is
the US going to support the Shia movement?''
</P>
<P>
   In Basra, the allied attacks were aimed at Saddam's elite
Republican Guard and a communications network that was damaged
enough to sever television and telephone communication with the
north. They also hit oil refineries which the allies charge have
been used in the export of oil in violation of the UN embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Attiya said the US and British strikes were a ``half-hearted''
attempt to trigger an uprising. He pointed out that they destroyed
local communication stations but not the central systems. Leaflets
were dropped by air warning the Republican Guard not to defend the
``Baghdad regime.'' But they stopped short of encouraging revolt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US showed that it is wary of sparking a rebellion, and
they are smart in this sense,'' Attiya continued. ``If something
starts in the south and is crushed again as it was in 1991, then
Saddam will be more deeply entrenched than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   He said of the airstrikes, ``This was a prepatory mission to
weaken the regime and to prepare for a more concrete and dramatic
effort in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   In central Basra, all that was left of a telephone and postal
satellite station was rubble. Bulldozers labored to clear the slabs
of concrete, mangled wires and machinery that, until the bombing,
serviced 10,000 phone lines. According to witnesses at the scene, a
security guard and a military official stationed there were killed.
Four others were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Standing amid the rubble, Abdul Zahara, 40, the mananger of the
communication center, said, ``This is for civilians. What did the
US hit this for? They are trying to cut us off from the rest of the
country. This must only be because they hate the Iraqi people.''
</P>
<P>
   His statements were made in the presence of armed military
guards and ``minders'' from the Ministry of Information assigned to
reporters. Zahara initially said that one of the two killed was a
military officer. But the ``minders'' pulled him aside at one point
and corrected himself when he returned, saying that both of the
dead men were civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were civilians,'' he said. ``They killed civilians
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, the Ministry of Information officials took reporters to
the entrance of the regional Iraqi oil industry offices. Reporters
were told of extensive damage to oil refineries there. But they
were refused access.
</P>
<P>
   Both of these scenes reflect how difficult it is to assess the
damage and the total number of casualties caused by the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   As Iraqis counted their casualties and dug out of the rubble,
the regime defiantly declared victory after the confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Victorious again!'' crowed the banner headline in Iraq's
Al-Musawir Al-Arabi weekly. ``Iraq deserves only victory with God's
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing in a taped message on Qatar-based television, Saddam
told Iraqis Sunday that they had achieved victory over the
``enemies of God and humanity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-98 2032EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
