<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-20 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9406 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-TROOPS-BOS &LR;      12-20 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-TROOPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TROOPS SURPRISED BY QUICK END TO DESERT FOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEAR THE IRAQI BORDER, Kuwait _ For a chopper pilot, Lieutenant
Brian Pierce of Brunswick, Maine, the miracle of the four-day
campaign against Iraq was that he never had to perform his most
important job _ rescuing downed aviators.
</P>
<P>
   All through the long nights of the short conflict, his Army unit
of attack Apaches and Blackhawk support helicopters hovered on the
edge of enemy air space as fighter-bombers hammered targets in
Iraq. The radio call the chopper crews dreaded most was the one
signaling an American or British plane had taken a critical hit,
forcing a bailout.
</P>
<P>
   That distress signal never came in hostilities where all the
blood was spilled by one side. Pierce flew reconnaissance missions,
a dangerous job in its own right, but never had to retrieve a
stricken airman. For that he offered thanks Sunday, as something
like peace returned to the troubled Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk about Christmas gifts, that's as precious as they come,''
he said. ``We're just extremely grateful there were no
casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   The operation called Desert Fox wasn't quite a war. And the
suspension of the air attacks is not quite the same as peace. By
and large, American fighting men and women massed in the region
seemed doubtful Sunday that the conflict is truly over or their job
is fully done.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is we've done what we were asked to do, hit
Saddam Hussein hard and fast,'' said Air Force Lieutenant Colonel
Roy White, who flew his A-10 ground attack craft on bomb and
missile strikes deep in Iraqi territory. ``We're all hopeful that
this is all we'll need to do. That's really up to Saddam Hussein.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, however: ``But I can't say anyone is convinced the US
is finished with Saddam. He remains a menace and a source of
uncertainty for the world. And we're ready to hit again on a
moment's notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was no mistaking the sense of surprise and relief
as word spread that hostilities were suspended for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace is better than war, even to a Marine,'' said Lance
Corporal Steven Gilleo, 19, of Wakefield, Mass. ``Maybe Saddam is
learning a lesson. Probably not. I guess the US can always try to
teach him another.''
</P>
<P>
   American and British forces on land and sea remained in a state
of high alert. But in foxholes and on flight lines, the mood was
far more relaxed than in the past four days, if still something
short of jubilant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adrenaline's down a bit, exhaustion's setting in, but it
was good to find a minute to go to chapel service and give thanks
that no Americans had to die this time,'' said Army Sergeant Robert
Taylor of Waxhaw, N.C., who'd worked virtually non-stop since last
Wednesday refueling and re-arming the combat helicopters of Army
Air Task Force 130.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, sure, everyone is kind of feeling high, but it's foolish
to think it's over,'' he said. ``We'll probably have to go back to
kicking Saddam's butt after Ramadan is done.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramadan, the Islamic holy month, started Saturday, and the
continuation of bomb attacks against Hussein during this season
infuriated even America's closest allies in the Muslim world.
Mistakenly or not, there seemed a strong impression among US
fighting forces that the termination of hostilities was a gesture
of respect for Islamic sensitivities, not a true end to the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the United States and Britain will be keeping a close
eye on Iraq. ``We'll still be enforcing the southern `No-Fly'
zone,'' said White. ``We'll still be using our assets here to keep
Saddam in line, although it's hard to predict what our exact role
is going to be a month from now, or even a day. It obviously
remains a volatile spot. Anything can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary speed of the campaign meant most American
forces in the region worked with only a few hours of sleep and a
few hurried meals throughout the four-day operation.
</P>
<P>
   So there was more weariness than wonder at the latest twist in
the ordeal with Iraq. ``Was that a war that just whizzed by, or
what?'' asked Army Staff Sergeant Frederick Delaine of
Fayetteville, N.C. ``I'm up for a nice long sleep and a slow
breakfast, if I'm lucky. But, fact is, here on the line, we're
still going to be geared up and going flat out.''
</P>
<P>
   American combatants said Sunday they had been far too focused on
the strikes against Saddam to focus on the political troubles back
home. Many seemed barely aware that their commander-in-chief,
President Clinton, had been impeached by Congress and is locked in
a struggle for his political life.
</P>
<P>
   And even those with a fairly clear notion of the last two days'
doings in Washington reacted with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd guess, other than the job immediately at hand, the thing
uppermost in mind for most of us is that Christmas is coming on,
and we are a long, long distance away from our families,'' said
White. ``I'm thinking of my wife and three kids. I'm thinking how
much I miss them. I'm thinking how much I love them. And I'm
thinking these things a lot harder than I'm thinking about politics
in Washington.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
