<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-20 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9413 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-POLITICS-BOS &LR;      12-20 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-POLITICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT HISTORY, GOP FOCUSES ON IRAQ POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the fury over impeachment continues, President
Clinton faces another partisan debate, this time over the attack on
the Iraq airstrike.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the four-day assault against Saddam Hussein Saturday
was greeted by tough questions from Republicans in Congress, who
sharply questioned the effectiveness of the operation and the
administration's long-term policy. Democrats stood firm behind
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, at the end of 70 hours, Saddam Hussein
is still in power, as he has been for the last number of years,
despite our threats, despite our attacks and so forth,'' Republican
Senator Richard Shelby of Alabama, chairman of the Senate
Intelligence Committee, said Sunday on CNN's ``Evans and Novak.''
</P>
<P>
   The questions largely echoed those of military analysts and a
few members of Congress when President Bush halted the 1991 Persian
Gulf war while Hussein retained power and much of his
weapons-production facilities.
</P>
<P>
   But this time there was a twist: Several of the president's
Republican critics have raised questions about the way the military
operation and the House impeachment hearings coincided.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing question (is) not my question, it's a question that
is widely abroad,'' Representative Porter Goss, chairman of the
House Intelligence Committee, said on ``Fox News Sunday.''
``Eyebrows have been raised by what I would call a confluence of
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the toughest words about the timing came Wednesday, with
the start of the bombing, from Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
who was later criticized by his own colleagues for his remarks. He
did not comment Sunday on Clinton's decision to stop the
airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Former senator Jack Kemp, the Republican party's 1996 candidate
for vice president, issued a statement calling the operation
``ill-conceived.'' And in an interview Sunday, Carnes Lord, who
served as national security adviser to former Vice President Dan
Quayle, said the attack appeared to do only slight damage to Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of raises questions about the timing,'' said Lord, an
assistant professor at the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at
Tufts University.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats generally supported the operation, known as Operation
Desert Fox. Representative Ed Markey, a Democrat from
Massachusetts, said the important question was not why the bombing
took place but why the House insisted on going ahead with
impeachment hearings as a military operation was being conducted.
``The reason that the impeachment couldn't be postponed was because
the Republican members wanted to go home for Christmas,'' Markey
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Norm Dicks, the top-ranking Democrat on the House
Intelligence Committee, said he had no doubts about the timing of
the strikes on Iraq. ``I think it was strictly done on the
merits,'' he said on ``Fox News Sunday.'' ``I think it should have
been done. I supported it. I think it's been effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph R. Biden Jr., who is a member of the Senate Judiciary
Committee and the top-ranking Democrat on the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, said the timing seemed odd at first. ``I have
to acknowledge to you, if I read this in a book, I'd say, well, no,
it's more than coincidence. . . . This is surreal. This is
absolutely bizarre, the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Biden said he had no doubt tha the president ordered the
strike on Iraq because his national security team decided that it
was time to surprise Hussein and set back Iraq's weapons
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody assumes this president is politically sharp as can
be,'' he said. ``Nobody in this town would have advised him to bomb
while he's trying to get votes from, you know, Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   (Aaron Zitner of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
