<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-OBSESSION-IRAQ-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHAT IS IT ABOUT IRAQ THAT OBSESSES AMERICA?'  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This incisive 850-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k''
commentary news files.)  
  
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ I called up a Saudi journalist friend of mine Thursday
and told him Downing Street was claiming the attack on Iraq was
intended to protect the Arab Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zbeili,'' he shouted down the phone to me. ``Zbeili'' is
Arabic for garbage. ``Why do you want to kill more of those poor
people?''
</P>
<P>
   The spin doctors are trying to present the Anglo-American
assault on Iraq in all its old 1991 Gulf War purity. Iraq's
neighbors are under threat and must be safeguarded from his weapons
of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   But with the exception of Kuwait _ some of whose citizens
repeated their now-familiar routine of fleeing over the Saudi
border every time the Iraqi crisis reemerges, the Arab Gulf states
wanted none of the West's protection Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the West Bank, where President Bill Clinton's visit this
week had produced the largest American banners ever seen in the
Arab world, they were back to burning the U.S. flag and shouting
``death to Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had sung with a Palestinian choir in Bethlehem three
days ago; Thursday, crowds near Manger Square were throwing stones
at Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought he (Clinton) carried a message of peace,'' a
disgruntled Palestinian girl said. ``But now it is clear he is a
murderer.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to underestimate the degree of cynicism and
distrust that is now felt in the Arab world towards the United
States and the only ally to support Washington in the attack on
Iraq, Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Why, the Saudis were asking privately this week, did America and
Britain continue to pretend that the Saudis supported the
bombardment when as long ago as last February, Saudi Arabia had
refused permission for the United States to use its air-bases for
raids on Iraq?
</P>
<P>
   It now transpires that when the U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen sought Saudi help during November's crisis with Iraq, Crown
Prince Abdullah not only refused assistance but suggested that the
United States might soon be asked to remove its aircraft from Saudi
air bases altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The painful truth is that most of the Arab dictatorships are
more fearful of their own people than they are of Saddam Hussein _
especially when ordinary Arabs are angry with their governments
because of their support for Washington.
</P>
<P>
   An example of this came in Cairo where 3,000 students poured
onto the streets to protest at the American attack. State security
police patrolled the university district.
</P>
<P>
   Even Iraq's traditional enemies expressed revulsion at the
bombardment. In the Iranian capital, Tehran, a foreign ministry
official said the attacks ``will lead to even more pain and misery
for the people of that country and will bring about insecurity in
the region.''
</P>
<P>
   The pro-Iranian Hezbollah guerrilla movement in Lebanon
condemned what it called ``American-British aggression'' which, it
feared, would be used by Saddam Hussein's regime ``as an excuse for
further atrocious massacres against the Iraqi people.''
</P>
<P>
   The word ``aggression'' _ `iitidak' in Arabic _ was used, too,
by Esmat Abdel-Meguid, the Secretary General of the Arab League,
and by Selim el-Hoss, the Lebanese prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we condemn this attack on Iraq,'' el-Hoss said, ``we are
astonished by the fact that Israel alone among the regional states
is free from the constraints and controls of possessing mass
destruction weapons.``
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, hypocrisy was what came across in many Arab newspaper
headlines. ``Desert Fox operation postpones Clinton's
impeachment,'' the Lebanese daily ``As Safir'' announced. ``Once
again, it is our flesh that is being eaten, and it is our blood
that is being shed. Let the perpetrators (of the air strike)...go
to hell.''
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton launched air strikes against Afghanistan and Sudan
at the height of the Monica Lewinsky scandal, the Arabs refused to
believe it was coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has attacked Iraq at the moment of impeachment hearings,
there is probably not a soul in the Arab world who does not believe
Iraqis are dying and suffering to save the Clinton presidency.
</P>
<P>
   America's failure to ensure that Israel honors the Oslo and Wye
agreements _ what is seen as Clinton's cowardice in the face of the
Israeli lobby in Washington _ is contrasted with his gung-ho,
bellicose attitude towards Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it about Iraq that obsesses America?'' my Saudi friend
asked. ``There are plenty of terrible people in the region. Do you
want to destroy Iraq and its people?''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to many news reports, American fixed-wing aircraft _ as
well as Cruise missiles _ were flying over Baghdad on Wednesday
night. ``We heard the planes very clearly as well as the missiles
which were literally whooshing over our heads in the darkness,''
one Westerner told me from Baghdad. ``There were a lot of impacts
near us _ and they weren't all from missiles.''
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft may well have flown from the one Arab Gulf state
which wants to help any American strike at Iraq and which still
hates and fears Saddam: Kuwait. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 850-word article, it must be purchased
from New York Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in
New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at
212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
