</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-METRO-PERFUME-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARIS METRO TO SMELL SWEETER  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 350-word ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``t'' travel news files.)  
  
 By JOHN LICHFIELD  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The smell of the Metro _ something between burned air
and rotting bananas _ is a characteristic Parisian experience: as
much a part of the city for generations of visitors as the Eiffel
Tower or the Champs Elysees.
</P>
<P>
   The magic formula is, or used to be, a delicate blend of
scorched rubber, sweat and sewers. It also included the heavy scent
of Gauloises and Gitanes, until cigarettes were banned from the
Paris underground a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, that trademark aroma has deteriorated for other
reasons. Some of the homeless people who spend their days in Metro
stations treat the corridors and, even the platforms, as
lavatories.
</P>
<P>
   The Regie Autonome des Transports Parisiens (RATP), the
state-owned company which runs all public transport in the French
capital, commissioned an opinion poll to discover why Parisians
were using the Metro less. One of the most common replies was: ``ca
pue.'' (It stinks).
</P>
<P>
   The company decided to put things right in time for the
centenary of the Metro in 12 months' time.
</P>
<P>
   In an experiment which will probably be extended to the whole
system the RATP began Friday to suffuse one Metro station with a
scent, especially designed by one of the big French perfume
workshops.
</P>
<P>
   The perfume, called ``Madeleine,'' was created by Quest
International France, a laboratory which normally works for the
fashion designer and parfumeur, Thierry Mugler.
</P>
<P>
   The fragrance, described as having a ``hint of spring flowers,''
will be mixed with the existing cleaning agents and applied daily
to the platforms, corridors and floors of the Invalides station.
</P>
<P>
   If the experiment is a success, it will be applied to all 366
stations on the Metro system, and all 64 on its sister regional
network, the RER, in the course of next year.
</P>
<P>
   The RATP is also working on a more technologically advanced
solution: the use of ultraviolet light to smash the molecules
hanging in the air which create bad odors.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the old Metro smell seems likely to go the way of
berets and yellow car-headlights. Another ``exception francaise''
is about to disappear. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 350-word article, it must be purchased from New
York Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York
at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-98 2057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
