<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-20 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9470 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-BOS &LR;      12-20 1477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN SENATORS SAY IMPEACHMENT TRIAL WILL BE HELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Top Republican senators insisted Sunday that
President Clinton will stand trial on two articles of impeachment,
as the White House stepped up its quest for a censure alternative
and senators in both parties faced the prospect that a lurid trial
on the sex-related charges could shatter the dignity of all three
branches of government.
</P>
<P>
   Amid new polls that show growing support for Clinton despite his
impeachment, Senate GOP leaders said they will not shirk what they
consider their constitutional duty to begin only the second trial
of a president since the nation's founding.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Senate leaders left no doubt they recognize the
potentially explosive impact of a nationally televised trial on the
perjury and obstruction of justice charges stemming from Clinton's
consensual sexual affair in the White House with a young former
intern, Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Presided over by William Rehnquist, chief justice of the Supreme
Court, the trial could unfold largely as a ``he said, she said''
saga.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Mitch McConnell, a Kentucky Republican who is expected
to play a pivotal role in the proceedings as chairman of the Senate
Rules Committee, echoed other GOP leaders in asserting the Senate
is obligated to try Clinton on the impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   But McConnell said the Senate, which has been embarrassed by
episodes such as the confirmation hearings of Supreme Court Justice
Clarence Thomas, could prevent further distress by taking private
testimony from the most controversial witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will not be a spectacle,'' McConnell said. ``It will not
demean the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the process may be thorny in the Senate, as advocates for
removing Clinton from office now lack the 67 votes required to
convict him and the president's supporters have yet to secure the
51 votes they would need to dismiss the charges. Republicans
outnumber Democrats in the Senate, 55 to 45.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton endured his first full day Sunday as the first
impeached president in 130 years, an angry parishioner shouted at
him as he left church services in Washington with his daughter,
Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damn you, for what you've done to the nation!'' the man said.
``Please resign for the good of the world!''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Chelsea did not acknowledge the protest, waving
instead to dozens of supporters who cheered and raised signs that
said, ``God Bless Our Prez'' and ``Complete Your Term.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Clinton had no intention of
resigning, despite fresh appeals from Republican senators for him
to step down. The senators appeared on news shows on several
television networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think it would be honorable for the president to
resign,'' said Senator Kay Bailey Hutchison, a Texas Republican.
``From the things that he has admitted doing, he has degraded the
office of the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   An NBC poll conducted immediately after Clinton's impeachment
showed his approval rating rising to 72 percent from 68 percent,
with 62 percent saying he should not relinquish his office. A poll
taken the same day by CBS and the New York Times found that 66
percent believed Clinton should not resign.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, a poll released by CNN and USA Today showed that only 29
percent want the Senate to remove Clinton from office, with 68
percent opposed to his ouster.
</P>
<P>
   However, Senator Jon Kyl, an Arizona Republican, cited a
separate poll showing that 45 percent thought Clinton should
resign. Kyl suggested the percentage may increase as GOP senators
continue to call for Clinton to step down. ``I believe the
president wants to avoid that number getting to 50 percent at all
costs,'' Kyl said.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides cited Clinton's pledge on Saturday to serve
his term ``until the final hour,'' which evoked memories of his
1992 vow in New Hampshire to persevere ``until the last dog dies.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, White House lawyers already were preparing Clinton's
defense, as the president's political aides worked behind the
scenes to forge support for a censure. The political team was
building on recent phone calls from Clinton to several influential
Democratic senators, including Edward M. Kennedy, and John B.
Breaux of Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux is a close friend of the Senate majority leader, Trent
Lott of Mississippi, and often plays a key role in creating
bipartisan coalitions, often with GOP senators from New England.
``I think the appropriate and proper penalty is a strong censure
resolution,'' Breaux said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But persuading at least six Republicans and all 45 Democrats to
short-circuit a formal trial may be problematic. Several Democrats,
particularly Senator Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia, are strict
adherents to constitutional standards, and they consider some form
of trial necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Some potential Republican allies also are far from open to a
censure plan. Senator Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania expressed no
interest in an alternative to a trial and said ``resignation might
be a possibility'' later in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``A censure is really not worth a tinker's damn,'' Specter said.
``When this trial starts, anything can happen. We've already seen
so many turns and twists in the road, and I think we're going to
see a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   Morever, GOP leaders are not expected to tolerate moderate
Republicans quickly breaking ranks to stave off a trial, although
the leaders indicated they will try to satisfy the bipartisan
desire to complete the ordeal relatively quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Constitution says if you receive these articles, you'll
have a trial,'' said Senator Don Nickles of Oklahoma, the assistant
majority leader. ``I think it can be done very quickly. Trent Lott
has said originally maybe three days to three weeks. I think he has
it about right. I think it could be done in three weeks if the
White House wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent Republican senator who has expressed
willingness to consider a censure is Orrin G. Hatch of Utah,
chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee. If Republicans cannot
muster more than 55 votes against Clinton, Hatch said Sunday,
``then there has to be some consideration to what do you do that is
the best under the circumstances to resolve this matter and in the
best interests of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments after the House impeached Clinton, Lott sent all 100
senators a 26-page document outlining historical precedents for a
Senate trial. The memo is based largely on the last presidential
impeachment trial, when the Senate acquitted Andrew Johnson by a
single vote in 1868 amid the bitter partisanship of the
Reconstruction era after the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   No president has been convicted in a Senate trial. But the
Senate has voted for conviction on 30 articles of impeachment for
lower-ranking public figures, from US District Judge John Pickering
in 1804 to US District Judge Walter Nixon in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the House approved 13 members of the Judiciary
Committee to prosecute the Senate trial, led by the chairman, Henry
J. Hyde. Clinton's defense team will be spearheaded by the White
House counsel, Charles F.C. Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Ruff's failure to prevent the Judiciary Committee from
approving four impeachment charges against Clinton, two Democrats
on the panel said his job will be easier in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts representatives Barney Frank and William D.
Delahunt said the charge that Clinton lied to a federal grand jury
relates almost entirely to details of his sexual relationship with
Lewinsky and will be hard to prove because the president
acknowledged to the grand jury that he had engaged in
``inappropriate intimate contact'' with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Frank and Delahunt also predicted the obstruction charge would
be hard to prosecute because witnesses largely support the
president's testimony, particularly his personal secretary, Betty
Currie, and his close friend Vernon E. Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest charge for Clinton to overcome, according to Frank
and Delahunt, would have been the allegation that he repeatedly
lied under oath about a number of issues in the sexual harassment
case that Paula Corbin Jones filed against him and settled last
month for $850,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guts of the case have been ripped out,'' Delahunt said.
``The evidence on these two articles will never meet the higher
standard of the US Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Several senators said the case is as critical to the Senate's
image as it is for Clinton. ``In many ways, the Senate's on trial
here, too,'' said Senator Christopher J. Dodd, a Connecticut
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Criticizing the nearly party-line impeachment vote in the House,
Senator Patrick J. Leahy, a Vermont Democrat said, ``I think we can
restore political sanity in the Senate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-98 2059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981220.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-20 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9465 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLY-`FOX'-CLINTON-IRA     12-20 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLY-`FOX'-CLINTON-IRAQ-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYNICS MAY FORGIVE CLINTON'S DESPERATION IF STRIKES GET SADDAM  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 600-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 19 Dec. 1998) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1998 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A sense of desperation attends the decision to launch the latest
wave of air strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The man who took the decision, Bill Clinton, was facing an
imminent vote in the House of Representatives on his impeachment;
what better way to show that he was worthy of the office of
President of the United States than to exercise, in a statesmanlike
way, the authority it gives him as commander-in-chief of his
country's armed forces?
</P>
<P>
   The man against whom the decision was taken, Saddam Hussein, is
desperate too, constrained by sanctions, dogged by arms inspectors,
hated by everyone and, eight years after the end of the Gulf war,
still without hope of shaking off his pursuers.
</P>
<P>
   As for the wider world _ in different degrees frightened of
Hussein, worried about the spread of weapons of mass destruction,
apprehensive about the use of force against a sovereign country _
it too has grown exasperated, ever more conscious that the Iraqi
dictator presents problems that never seem to go away and that have
no straightforward solution.
</P>
<P>
   If all this is unsatisfactory, so too perhaps was the trigger
for Operation Desert Fox, a report by Richard Butler, the head of
the team of U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   This showed that Hussein had not fully cooperated with the
UNSCOM inspectors, as he had promised to, but it was not
unambiguously clear that his lack of cooperation had in fact been
designed to prevent UNSCOM from doing its job.
</P>
<P>
   Another, awkwardly plausible interpretation is that Hussein's
obstructiveness may have been designed to stop the inspectors, and
the Israelis to whom he assumes they pass all the information they
gather, from learning about all sorts of secrets not directly
related to weapons-making.
</P>
<P>
   Still, America _ and Britain, which has also joined the
operation _ had always said that any failure by Hussein to keep his
word would bring an attack, without further ado, and the Iraqi
therefore commands little real sympathy, whatever the public
denunciations of the decision to launch the air strikes by China,
Russia, some Arabs and, to a lesser extent, France.
</P>
<P>
   Even Arab sympathizers lost patience with Hussein on the last
occasion, in November, when he stopped cooperating with the U.N.,
and most people, whether friend or foe of Iraq, must have felt that
there was an inevitability about these strikes.
</P>
<P>
   That they should have come now, at Clinton's hour of need _ just
as an earlier strike, in August, against an apparently innocent
factory in Sudan came at another hour of need for the American
president _ is unfortunate, to say the least. Yet they should be
judged, in the end, on their effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   If they succeed in achieving their stated aim, that will be
welcome. But merely to ``degrade Saddam's capacity to develop and
deliver weapons of mass destruction and to degrade his ability to
threaten his neighbors,'' is not ambitious, and will not solve the
long-run problem.
</P>
<P>
   This, as Clinton and other American officials have been making
ever more explicitly clear, is Hussein himself.
</P>
<P>
   No one can be sure how, or when, Hussein will leave office. He
could be thrown out tomorrow, or hang on, as Fidel Castro has in
Cuba, to infuriate American presidents for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   But if this round of air strikes should prove to be the lever
that prises him from power, the world will surely judge them a
success. It may even swallow some of its cynicism about the man who
ordered them at such a fortuitous time. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
