economic collapse as unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, before the sudden fame of a woman called Monica, so
too would have been a vote to impeach President Bill Clinton, or,
indeed, widespread calls for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Oil at $10 a barrel? Bill Gates on the defensive? The overthrow
of President Suharto of Indonesia? The fall and then private-sector
rescue of Long-Term Capital Management? George Soros arguing that
speculators should be restrained?
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion seems inescapable: if you are taking something
for granted, don't.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of things are, nevertheless, still taken for granted. Is
it really right to assume, as many do, that nuclear weapons will
never be used by states, that democracy will continue to spread,
that China will not break up, that shares are always the best
long-term investment?
</P>
<P>
   Those unthinkables are likely to be challenged over a period of
years or even decades. As soon as 1999, however, a different but
just as widespread assumption will face its stiffest challenge yet:
the idea that globalization is irreversible.
</P>
<P>
   That ugly, 13-letter word has become a mantra of business, of
politics, even of culture.
</P>
<P>
   This decade has seen a remarkable increase in the openness to
trade and investment flows of country after country: partly because
of the demise of Soviet communism and of old ideas of socialist
self-sufficiency; partly because of liberalizations agreed upon
during the Uruguay round of what was then the GATT and is now the
World Trade Organization; and partly because of the rapid,
world-shrinking spread of new information technology.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, foreign businesses, foreign investors and
foreign (especially American) culture have penetrated deeply into
most countries' domestic lives.
</P>
<P>
   Some countries have tried to slow this penetration down. But few
have resisted it altogether. The mix of unstoppable technological
change with the apparently unanswerable intellectual defeat of
central planning has made globalization appear inevitable: only its
speed and its consequences seem open to debate.
</P>
<P>
   Would that it were so. The effort to reverse this movement has
already begun. Next year, most probably, that effort will move into
a higher gear.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, at least, is plain to all, save possibly investors
in American shares: world recession. No one can be sure about the
future course of the world economy, even a few months ahead let
alone a year.
</P>
<P>
   But it does look likely that next year, economic growth for the
world as a whole is going to be even slower than for 1998, perhaps
a lot slower.
</P>
<P>
   For a Japanese, a South Korean, an Indonesian or even,
increasingly, a Brazilian, that will be no surprise. Those parts of
the world are already in a real recession, and there is little
reason to expect much of a recovery before 1999's second half, at
the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's financial troubles continue to mount, despite government
package after government package. The pace of economic shrinkage
seems to have been slowed in Korea and Thailand, but neither there
nor in Indonesia or Malaysia has much progress been made on
structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil, recently rescued by a $41 billion IMF-led consortium,
looks shaky: with public-spending cuts blocked by Congress, capital
flight has resumed and the real again looks a candidate for
devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   China, too, long East Asia's gravity-defying hero, looks likely
to slow and quite possibly to devalue.
</P>
<P>
   That is all bad, but there is nothing unthinkable there. Nor
does this yet threaten globalization. A cause for optimism during
the past two years has been the fact that, so far, none of the
recession-hit emerging markets has raised its formal trade
barriers, and (excepting small, maverick Malaysia and large,
lunatic Russia) none has revived barriers to capital flows.
</P>
<P>
   Governments may really believe that globalization is inevitable.
Or they may be so desperate for capital, from the IMF, from western
governments or from private investors, that they think they have no
short-term alternative to openness.
</P>
<P>
   So and far are two important words. The most important test will
come not in the vulnerable economies of the developing world, nor
in Japan, but in the rich, developed world that provides most of
that capital and sets the tone on trade and investment rules.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 1 the European Union will launch its single currency to
much acclaim but not, alas, amid the strengthening economic
recovery that looked likely earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment may well start to rise again in the euro countries,
posing immediately a clash between national politics and the
collective, EU interest.
</P>
<P>
   If so, the risk is either of a political dust-up between the
main euro countries, most notably France and Germany, or of a
deflection of that pressure on to the outside world, through an
increase in the EU's already strong protectionist tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   The United States will offer the biggest test of all. This year,
buoyed by consumers, its economy has been remarkably strong. A
modest slowdown in 1999 is widely expected.
</P>
<P>
   A nastier time looks possible, however, as companies cut their
capital investment and as (or if) Wall Street's stock market bubble
bursts, making consumers feel poorer and companies more worried.
</P>
<P>
   Further interest-rate cuts might limit the damage; an
expansionary fiscal policy might also help; but neither is likely
to avert a slowdown altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Already, even with American unemployment at record postwar lows
and the economy steaming ahead, industries such as steel and memory
chips have resorted to anti-dumping suits to protect themselves
against imports.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has berated Europeans for not importing more
goods from Asia and thus taking the heat out of America's growing
current-account deficit. Slower growth or a full recession can only
boost the protectionist voice.
</P>
<P>
   The real question is how strong it will get. With a wounded
presidency and the 2000 election-campaign getting under way, the
defenses against it will be weakened.
</P>
<P>
   And if protectionism breaks through in the United States? Then,
the likelihood is that other, smaller, more genuinely vulnerable
countries would turn protectionist too, partly in retaliation but
partly also out of opportunism.
</P>
<P>
   Such a verdict is, in truth, a rather gloomy thing to write at
Christmas. But it offers a realistic way to think about 1999.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first proper test of globalization. If the test
is passed, this slowdown could prove short, the subsequent recovery
strong and fruitful. If it is failed, and markets are closed, the
recession could prove long and painful.
</P>
<P>
   That is the choice. It would take an ostrich to pretend
otherwise. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
