u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PLAYOFFS21-COX     12-20 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PLAYOFFS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Divisions get 6 new champs; 2 wild-card spots open
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Not even the late commissioner Pete Rozelle, who
introduced the concept of parity to the NFL, had these kinds of
results in mind when he decided to even the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   Three more teams _ the Atlanta Falcons, Jacksonville Jaguars and
Dallas Cowboys _ claimed championships on Sunday, completing a rare
overhaul for the six divisions. For only the second time since the
NFL adopted the 16-game schedule in 1978, all six of the division
winners are different than last season. The only other time there
were wholesale first-place changes was in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's reflective of a situation in which the talent disparity
has narrowed even further,'' said Green Bay coach Mike Holmgren,
whose Packers probably will enter the playoffs as the No. 2
wild-card qualifier from the NFC. ``The upheaval isn't all that
surprising.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's weekend results leave two playoff vacancies, the final
wild-card spots in both conferences. The Miami Dolphins can fill
out the AFC side of the bracket with a victory against the Denver
Broncos tonight.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFC, the last wild-card spot will not be determined until
next Sunday. Three teams _ Arizona, Tampa Bay and the New York
Giants _ remain in contention. Arizona can claim its first playoff
spot since the strike-shortened 1982 season with a victory against
San Diego. A loss by the Cardinals would leave the league with its
first non-winning playoff team since 1990 and only the third in two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   The league already is assured a marquee matchup in the wild-card
round. Green Bay and San Francisco, which met in the NFC title game
a year ago, will play on Jan. 2 or 3 at a site to be determined
next week. At least one of the teams has appeared in each of the
past six conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   NFL PLAYOFF PICTURE
</P>
<P>
   AFC playoff teams
</P>
<P>
   Denver (13-1): West champion, first-round bye, home field
throughout.
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. Jets (11-4): East champion.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville (10-4): Central champion.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo (9-6): Wild card.
</P>
<P>
   New England (9-6): Wild card.
</P>
<P>
   NFC playoff teams
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota (13-1): Central champion, first-round bye.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (13-2): West champion, first-round bye.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas (9-6): East champion.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco (11-4): Wild card.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay (10-5): Wild card.
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S NEXT
</P>
<P>
   Miami - In if beat Broncos or Falcons or Oilers loss.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee - Need to beat Vikings and have Miami lose.
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S NEXT
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (8-7) - In if beat Chargers or Giants and Bucs lose.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay (7-8) - Need to beat Bengals and have Cardinals and
Giants lose.
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. Giants (7-8) - Need to beat Eagles and have Cardinals and
Bucs lose.
</P>
