<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-MOORE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons felt Reeves' presence
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. _ He was gone, but he was there. ``We just had
this constant feeling that we didn't want to let Dan Reeves down,''
said Atlanta Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler, referring to the
man who used his healing heart to will his team to a 24-17 victory
Sunday from his home in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how loudly the Detroit Lions roared with their
following during the crucial stages of Sunday's action inside the
Silverdome, Reeves, in spirit, was everywhere for the Falcons to
calm their nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't you see him?'' said Falcons offensive tackle Bob
Whitfield, wide-eyed, explaining that it was Reeves leading the
blocks for Jamal Anderson, who rushed for 147 yards. It was Reeves
helping the Falcons' defense keep Barry Sanders ordinary for a day.
It was Reeves shouting toward his players to keep their minds
focused in a glorious ending against the Lions, despite a woeful
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   This was an example of the Falcons showing that they were as
potent with Reeves' system as they were with the man himself.
</P>
<P>
   Well, sort of. Even in victory, there was a mighty problem for
these soaring Dirty Birds, who spent the afternoon officially
becoming better than even San Francisco in the NFC West for a
season.
</P>
<P>
   The problem? Reeves' spirit remains slightly less powerful than
Reeves' presence. In fact, Falcons wide receiver Terance Mathis
likes to say that you can see the confidence of the man in just his
walk. Falcons President Taylor Smith agreed with misty eyes, and
then he sighed while thinking about his head coach recovering from
heart surgery this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just something special about seeing him out there on
the sideline,'' Smith said. ``That's why it was totally different
without him on the flight here. It was totally different in the
locker room. He has that way of looking at you and making you feel
good about yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   So the spirit was willing, but the flesh definitely was weak for
the Falcons as they struggled against a group of Lions who have
been toothless for most of the season. Then came that surge for the
Falcons near the end that featured many of their wonderful
attributes.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 17-10 in the fourth quarter, the relentless Chris
Chandler found the equally relentless Mathis in the end zone to
signal a comeback. Actually, the Falcons flashed signs of their
rally with a defense that kept Sanders in low gear along the way to
rushing for 95 yards.
</P>
<P>
   There also was Anderson, twisting, bursting and dancing his way
through defenders with the greatest of ease.
</P>
<P>
   Among Anderson's runs was a 26-yard gem that led to his 1-yard
plunge giving the Falcons a first-week bye in the playoffs. No, it
was Reeves' system that accomplished all of the above, and
everybody in the Falcons' locker room knew it and acknowledged it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan is such a high character person that he challenges
himself, and that makes us challenge ourselves,'' Falcons
linebacker Cornelius Bennett said. ``I had a little speech prepared
that I was going to give to the team before the game, but when I
came into the locker room and saw the look in their eyes, I just
threw it away.''
</P>
<P>
   That look in their eyes was Dan Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
