<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-20 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9512 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-LIONS21-C     12-20 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-LIONS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons soar to victory over Lions
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. _ When the moment finally came, and it seemed
like it took forever to arrive, the Atlanta Falcons' defensive end
Chuck Smith dropped to his knees at about the 30-yard line, his
arms thrust roofward in the Silverdome.
</P>
<P>
   All around him teammates were jumping up and down, rookie
linebacker Keith Brooking forgetting for the moment he had a
sprained knee. On the sidelines, reserve quarterback Steve DeBerg
hugged offensive coordinator/running backs coach George Sefcik.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Atlanta, presumably, Dan Reeves pumped his fists, and
his heart pumped as perhaps never before, and somewhere, perhaps,
Rankin Smith Sr. smiled bigger than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the words on the hats handed out on the Falcons
sideline moments after free safety Eugene Robinson intercepted a
pass with 1:39 left to play Sunday to seal Atlanta's
eighth-straight victory, a 24-17 comeback victory over the Detroit
Lions, and it all makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Champions,'' the first line read.
</P>
<P>
   ``1998 NFC West Division.''
</P>
<P>
   It's happened only once before, in 1980. And Smith has been
around the last six times in didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had this incredible burst of energy,'' said Smith, who
was frozen for nearly a minute like a statue while chaos reigned
around him. ``And when I got up, I felt like running around the
stadium forever. I'm so tired, but I could run for days. I don't
know what to say. I'm just shaking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons (13-2) likely left their coach numb back in Atlanta,
where Reeves watched on TV while recuperating from heart bypass
surgery on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves watched his team fall behind 14-10 just before halftime
and 17-10 with 1:43 left in the third quarter. But moments later,
Chris Chandler threw a perfect 27-yard touchdown pass to Terance
Mathis to force a tie.
</P>
<P>
   After that, a defense that tightened up in the second half,
allowing just 105 yards after halftime (of a total of 258), held on
two possessions. The scene was set, and the Falcons, who looked so
out of sync offensively in the first half against the 5-10 Lions,
went to a familiar script.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Jamal Anderson (30 carries, 147 yards, one rushing
touchdown, one receiving touchdown) took over. Atlanta went 56
yards in eight plays, the keys being a 26-yard run by Anderson when
he went right, cut inside defensive end Robert Porcher, angled
toward the middle of the field, and dragged at least one tackler
the final 7 or 8 yards to the 1.
</P>
<P>
   He scored from the 1 on the next play, giving Atlanta a 24-17
lead with 6:57 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit did nothing on two more possessions, the end coming when
Robinson jumped in front of a poor Frank Reich pass at the Lions'
30 and dropped to the turf to protect the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions had no timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons had the time of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Team president Taylor Smith paused in the locker room, thinking
of his father, Rankin Sr., who died in the middle of last season of
a heart attack. For years, the Smith family has been derided, as
has been this franchise.
</P>
<P>
   So much of that was forgettable on Sunday night in the Motor
City.
</P>
<P>
   Was Smith thinking of his father, who brought the NFL to Atlanta
in 1966, only to watch his team flail away year after year, with
just seven winning seasons in the first 32?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' he said, not quite misty-eyed, but able briefly
to look only at the cold concrete floor. ``I wish he was here to
share this. I'm sure he knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching the Falcons in the first half, it was impossible to
tell they came in with a seven-game winning streak while the Lions
had lost back-to-back blowouts, including 35-13 last Monday when
players were accused of quitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their game against the 49ers was the worst thing that could
have happened for us,'' defensive end Lester Archambeau said. ``We
knew they were going to come after us, and they did. But we showed
character.''
</P>
<P>
   That the Falcons did, with defensive coordinator Rich Brooks
standing in as interim head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to get (Reeves) on the speaker phone in here, but
apparently they shut the phone off at his house,'' Brooks said.
``Dan Reeves is responsible for where we all are right now. I want
to congratulate Dan back home. He's really put a lot into this the
last two years to get us where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the best feeling I've ever had except for the
birth of my children,'' Chandler said. ``It was as important or
more important to have coach Reeves have the extra week off to get
himself feeling good. I wondered what he was doing at game time.
Those kind of feelings kind of permeated the whole team.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long before the team left for its charter flight home,
quarterback coach Jack Burns was in a hallway near the locker room,
smoking a cigar as he usually does after a victory. But this was
different. He called the plays Sunday without the usual input from
Reeves, relaying them through reserve quarterback Steve DeBerg to
Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a special cigar,'' he said, looking resplendent in a
suit and tie. ``This is an Arturo Fuentes. This is special. We
showed poise. This was beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
