<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-OILERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIVED GIANTS REMAIN IN PLAYOFF CONTENTION
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ In the penultimate week of their regular
season, these Giants behaved and played like a new team, as if
confidence and know-how had slipped through the transom of the
locker-room door and drifted from player to player.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Giants find themselves giddy from the unforeseen playoff
drama that has percolated in their midst. Last week's stunning
upset of the Denver Broncos and Sunday's wire-to-wire 28-7
thrashing of the Kansas City Chiefs have emboldened the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Their playoff hopes, though still remote, grow less remote with
each victory, and it has the players feasting in the whimsy of
their situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a funny feeling about this year,'' Corey Widmer, the
middle linebacker, said with a wily smile. ``There's a vibe going
on. Strange things happen in sports. People might just see
something special this year.''
</P>
<P>
   One wonders if the rest of the National Football League would
call an 8-8 playoff team special, but the Giants are coming from
the perspective of a team that was 3-7 five weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   With Kent Graham at quarterback, the Giants have won four of
their last five games and three in a row. Sunday's domination of
Kansas City has turned optimism to conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this thing could happen just the way we want it to,''
said Graham, who had his second consecutive strong effort Sunday,
guiding the Giants to a 28-0 lead by the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   This is the way the Giants (7-8) want it: First, Tampa Bay (7-8)
must lose at Cincinnati early next Sunday afternoon, and later that
same day, the Giants must win at Philadelphia and Arizona (8-7)
must lose at home to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Because of various tie-breaking procedures, any other
combination of results in those three games means the Giants do not
make the playoffs. If the Giants win and Tampa Bay and Arizona
lose, the Giants will play in the first round of the playoffs at
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   That the Giants are still involved in the high drama of a
playoff chase at this late stage of the season had Coach Jim Fassel
marveling at the team's turnabout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is amazing, it really is,'' he said after Sunday's victory,
which came in the franchise's 1,000th regular-season game. All we
can do is take care of our last game. If it works, it works. If it
doesn't, it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The team the Giants most resembled Sunday was last year's
Giants, whose ferocious pass rush and opportunistic secondary. On
the first play of the game, Kansas City quarterback Rich Gannon was
sacked and had to leave the game with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, Gannon's replacement, former starter Elvis
Grbac, threw behind wide receiver Derrick Alexander, the ball
deflecting off Alexander and ricocheting to safety Percy Ellsworth,
who caught the ball at the Chiefs' 43-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth returned the interception virtually untouched for a
touchdown. It was the second interception return for a touchdown
this year by Ellsworth, who add an interception in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' first possession was 12 plays and covered 83 yards,
concluding with a 12-yard touchdown pass from Graham to Amani
Toomer, the same combination that won game against Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants added to their 14-0 lead in the second quarter on a
one-yard touchdown run by Gary Brown, who rushed for 103 yards on
25 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants also benefited from nine penalties against the
Chiefs, who are the most penalized team in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody gave us a shot,'' said Graham. ``People said our
schedule was too tough. And it has been tough. But we've won these
games. And right now, the playoffs could happen for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
