<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-PRISON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A VENEZUELA PRISON, EVERY CRANNY HOLDS A CLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CIUDAD BOLIVAR, Venezuela _ The prison here is called a center
for rehabilitation, but perhaps nowhere in Venezuela do the words
have less meaning than inside its gate.
</P>
<P>
   Even the prison administration dares not cross the portal, to
the area inside where 1,200 men and 32 women have blasted holes
through walls, taken over a schoolroom and thrown up cardboard
shacks, cramming themselves into a space built for 400. The
prison's corridors and yards, carrying names like ``The Ranch'' and
``The Tank'' are like neighborhoods, but with armed borders.
</P>
<P>
   A new neighborhood may begin at a stairwell or a bend in the
corner, where groups of inmates _ their makeshift guns, knives and
sabers flashing from their belts _ stand guard. Virtually every
inmate is scarred and many are bandaged. With antibiotics scarce,
wounds fester.
</P>
<P>
   But within the miniature worlds the prison contains, there also
are surprising visions of grace: healthier inmates nursing those
who are sick, one carving figures and jewelry from black stone, two
groups that have devised ovens to bake cakes.
</P>
<P>
   With street crime surging, along with popular frustrations that
have led to lynchings of crime suspects, Venezuela has been sending
growing numbers of people to prison. Its 33 prisons, built to house
15,000 inmates, now hold more than 24,000. The system largely
ignores minimum standards of hygiene, medical care and security.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the most violent, most dangerous prisons in the
world,'' said Joanne Mariner, counsel for Human Rights Watch in New
York. ``Every aspect of the system is overloaded and not
functioning.''
</P>
<P>
   At Ciudad Bolivar prison one night, a turf war broke out, and
stones and bullets flew. The tension eased briefly through the
visiting hours the next day, but exploded again in gunfire as
relatives and friends left for home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't respect anything in there, not even visiting day,''
said Zaida Salazar, 40, who had just visited a brother who was
serving 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   The prisons mix inmates charged with armed robbery and murder
with university graduates who have been convicted of white-collar
crimes. Prisoners with 15-year sentences share cells with those
awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, you either find God or you lose all hope,'' said Sister
Socorro Quintana, 53, a Roman Catholic nun from Spain who ministers
to the inmates here. ``And there are many who are completely
without hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Violence, mostly among inmates, has skyrocketed. Last year, 336
prisoners were killed, up from 207 in 1996. By comparison, of the
1.7 million convicts in U.S. prisons, 67 were killed by other
inmates last year.
</P>
<P>
   About three out of four people in Venezuelan prisons have not
been convicted. Some, like Adan Toledo, 40, a former bank employee
charged with fraud, have waited more than a year for trial, unable
to scrape together bail.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like America Carmen Bustillo, 42, are here apparently
for no reason. Ms. Bustillo was accused of selling drugs but said
the case against her was dropped in April. In September, she was
still there, waiting for another bureaucratic step to regain her
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the government blew up Catia prison in the
capital, Caracas, which had been a symbol of the violence and chaos
in the criminal justice system. Optimists saw that action as
heralding a new era of reform. But there have been few signs of
improvement since then. And outrage over mounting crime has thrown
prison conditions off the list of voter concerns.
</P>
<P>
   At the prison in Ciudad Bolivar, 370 miles southeast of Caracas,
the authority of the state ends at the door. The National Guard,
responsible for security outside the prison, searches visitors. The
prison administration, with a handful of guards for the entire
prison, restricts itself to two offices at the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   The other offices house ``refugiados,'' prisoners without allies
inside, who huddle near the administration offices for safety. They
include white-collar suspects like Toledo, and, earlier this year,
a group of convicts sent here from the prison in El Dorado. The
newcomers had been involved in a fight that killed 29 men, many
with friends in Ciudad Bolivar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Practically speaking, they sent us to the guillotine to die,''
said Jorge Luis Rey, 26. When the group arrived last August, one of
them was killed almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The consequences of being cut or shot are serious here, too,
given the virtual absence of medical care. Raul Millan, 30, was
shot in his left leg three years ago by an inmate with a homemade
gun. With no treatment for the infection, his leg had to be
amputated.
</P>
<P>
   Seizing weapons does little good, said Eulice Villamonte, the
weekend prison director. Within days the weapons reappear. ``Where
they're coming from, I don't know,'' she said. ``I won't say my
guards are saints, but I don't believe they're bringing in
weapons.'' She acknowledged, however, that she has no control over
the National Guard stationed outside.
</P>
<P>
   Within the fiercely protected borders of their fiefdoms,
prisoners seem to strive for something near normal lives. In El
Reyo pavilion, the inmates have opened a bakery, fashioning an oven
from an old metal cabinet, with a hot plate on the ground to heat
the chamber. One prisoner gently lifted a towel and untied the
cloth scraps that shut the door. A cake was baking on the metal
shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Most women sent here quickly choose common-law husbands among
the inmates, but men at Ciudad Bolivar are also allowed weekly
conjugal visits. The women say a kind of chivalry prevails, with
the men largely respecting the few female prisoners among them.
Until recently, babies were born and raised at Ciudad Bolivar.
</P>
<P>
   Meals come in vast tubs left by the authorities at the prison
gate, with inmates dividing the food among themselves. On one
recent day, it was seasoned rice and a few chunks of sausage.
</P>
<P>
   Budget cutbacks have ended rehabilitative programs, and the
inmates have taken over the building that had been used for
classes. They have strung up bed sheets to hang like translucent
walls from the ceilings. In a neighboring yard, a shantytown has
gone up, with electrical wires running in every direction. Some
huts have walls of cinderblock, others of wood or bed sheets.
</P>
<P>
   The roof of one shack, built by Luis Beltran, a 37-year-old
inmate nicknamed ``the architect,'' is a collage of tar paper and
cardboard, the holes plugged with anything that can be scavenged:
an egg carton, a beach thong, a battered thermos laid on its side.
Most of the shacks do not have mattresses, and all leak in the
rain.
</P>
<P>
   But allies are more important than mattresses. Antonio Gomez,
24, said that upon entering Ciudad Bolivar prison five years ago
for murder he first sought friends, crucial for safety, and then
decent living space.
</P>
<P>
   Now he lives with two of them in a section that used to be the
women's annex, before the male prisoners ripped out the bars that
once separated them from the women.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez carves a black stone, azaballe, that he makes into
pendants, bracelets and watchbands. One pendant shows a woman
astride a leopard. Many show Jesus. ``Here you lose your family,
your wife, your children,'' he said. ``I live through my work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
