A9524 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-UPDATE-HNS &LR;      12-20 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-UPDATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT HOLDS PUBLIC'S SUPPORT, 2 POLLS INDICATE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN C. HENRY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
c. 1998
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WASHINGTON _ In the wake of his impeachment by the House, public
support for President Clinton appeared unshaken Sunday as members
of the Senate mulled how to bring the constitutional crisis to a
quick, just end.
</P>
<P>
   While no consensus has emerged on how best to proceed _ whether
with a full trial or a plea-agreement for censuring the president _
Republican and Democratic senators agreed they will have to rise
above the partisan rancor that marked much of the House
deliberations over Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, the Senate's on trial here in a way, too,'' said
Sen. Christopher Dodd, a Connecticut Democrat. ``We're the court of
last resort, of trying to restore some civility here.''
</P>
<P>
   Voting along party lines, the House on Saturday impeached
Clinton on charges of perjury and obstruction of justice stemming
from his effort to conceal an illicit affair with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky. Another perjury charge and an
abuse-of-office charge were rejected by the House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, only the second president in history to face a Senate
trial after being impeached by the House, vowed to fight to remain
in office until his term ends in January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Clinton and daughter Chelsea went to church, and as
they emerged from Foundry United Methodist in downtown Washington
they were confronted by an angry parishioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damn you, for what you've done to the nation!'' the man
barked. ``Please resign for the good of the world!''
</P>
<P>
   Initially taken aback, Clinton turned with Chelsea and began
waving to about 100 people who were cheering and holding up signs
saying: ``Complete Your Term'' and ``God Bless Our Prez.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's determination to remain on the job was endorsed
by a substantial majority of Americans in two separate polls taken
after Saturday's impeachment vote by the House. One of the surveys
found Clinton's job-approval rating at an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
   An NBC poll found 62 percent of adult Americans saying Clinton
should serve out his term, up from 51 percent earlier in the week
before the House impeachment debate began.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS/New York Times poll released Sunday found 66 percent of
adults saying Clinton should remain in office, compared to 69
percent before the House vote.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Americans favor by a 2-to-1 margin censuring the
president rather than putting him through a Senate trial for his
behavior in the Lewinsky matter, according to the CBS/New York
Times survey.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's approval rating rose after the vote to 72 percent,
according to the NBC poll, which earlier in the week showed him
with a 68 percent job approval rating.
</P>
<P>
   White House Chief of Staff John Podesta said Sunday it would be
wrong for Clinton to step down, given the partisan nature of the
House debate and the impeachment vote against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president were to resign under these circumstances it
would weaken the presidency. It would weaken the Constitution,''
Podesta said on CNN television's Late Edition.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on the same program, Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, a
Texas Republican, said Clinton's admission of a long-running White
House affair with Lewinsky and his lies to his family, aides and
the public have ``degraded the office of the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling Speaker-elect Bob Livingston ``courageous'' for
announcing that he will quit the House over his own marital
infidelities, Hutchison said Clinton should do the same. ``It would
be honorable for the president to resign,'' the senator said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders in the Senate said they expect to begin
Clinton's trial on the perjury and obstruction-of-justice charges
when the new Congress convenes Jan. 6. If convicted on either of
the articles of impeachment, Clinton would be removed from office
immediately, and Vice President Al Gore would move into the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   While most, but not all, Republicans favor a formal trial,
Democrats argue that a trial will prolong the public agony over the
sex-and-perjury scandal. Democrats favor censure as the quickest
out.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, called on Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott to take a quick survey of the 55 Republican and 45 Democrats
in the Senate and determine whether there is anything near the 67
votes required to convict Clinton and remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   If neither of the impeachment articles are favored by 55
senators, the question facing Republicans is whether to go to trial
``knowing that... the result may be acquittal, or do you find
something like censure, like most of the members of the public say
they want,'' Hatch said on NBC's Meet the Press.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., counseled against short-circuiting a
trial by trying to reach a censure agreement with Democrats and the
White House. ``Censure is really not worth a tinker's damn,''
Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this trial starts, anything can happen. Already we've
seen so many turns and twists in the road, and I think we're going
to see a lot more,'' Specter predicted on CBS's Face the Nation.
``While (Clinton's) resignation is not realistic today, a plea
bargain where he'd leave office is not in the cards today... stay
tuned.``
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., said the Senate was obligated to
hold a trial, but predicted it would be tamed somewhat by requiring
some witnesses to testify behind closed doors. ``This will not be a
spectacle,'' McConnell said. ``It will not demean the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodd, appearing on Meet the Press, said censure is preferable
because a trial would ``tie up three branches of government for the
next four months.'' In addition to occupying much of the
president's and the Senate's time, a trial would require the daily
presence of Chief Justice William Rehnquist and 13 of the 21
Republican members of the House Judiciary Committee selected as
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Lending support to an agreed censure resolution is the lack of
support in the Senate for ending Clinton's presidency, said Sen.
Robert Torricelli, D-N.J. ``There is extraordinary solidarity among
Democrats in the Senate and increasingly a desire among some
Republicans in the Senate to have this matter ended,'' Torricelli
said.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Senate held a trial for the nation's chief
executive was in 1868, when President Andrew Johnson was acquitted
by a single vote after a 74-day trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-98 2129EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
