<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIBBY BEMOANS CHANGING ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When USC point guard Kevin Augustine suddenly quit
the team last week, it once again underscored to coach Henry Bibby
the attitude differences that have taken place since he played at
UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a totally different basketball player today,'' Bibby
said. ``I dared not question Coach (John) Wooden, (assistant
coaches) Denny Crum or Gary Cunningham about my playing time. I was
afraid of Coach Wooden.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby feels the biggest problem today is that players are
constantly influenced by advisers, sometimes a club coach, who feel
their player is not receiving enough playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many people in the background that push these
kids,'' Bibby said. ``We have so many outside factors playing into
these guys, telling them they are the greatest players.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby's also noticing the difference between college basketball
and his stints coaching in the Continental Basketball Association,
where he could deal with problem players.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the CBA, I got rid of them,'' he said. ``(In college) the
kids can leave anytime they want, but we can't do anything. I think
we should give both sides the same option.''
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily a point guard: Although Augustine's departure
leaves USC with two point guards _ freshman Brandon Granville and
junior Quincy Wilder _ Bibby said he will not feel compelled to
sign another point guard with Augustine's scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for the best guy available,'' Bibby said. ``The
best possible player we can get. It opens a whole new ballgame for
us. It gives us another opportunity, maybe to get something we're
lacking.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby is also confident that Wilder, who has been unhappy with
his playing time, will emerge now that he is clearly the No. 2
point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings a lot to the team if he's focused and accepting,''
Bibby said. ``I like Quincy's size, his athleticism and strength.
He's a bigger version of Kevin Augustine for us. He can play
against bigger guards.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner at the point? Bibby is also considering moving 6-foot-8
forward Jarvis Turner to point guard, much like he converted small
forward Rodrick Rhodes two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things I'm knocking around,'' Bibby said. ``My
assistants think I'm crazy. If I have to go with Brandon, Quincy
and Jarvis next year, we can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lesson from loss: Forward Brian Scalabrine said there was at
least one positive aspect of the Trojans' blowout 107-78 loss to
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still scored 78 points even though we shot the ball
terribly and had 29 turnovers,'' Scalabrine said. ``That's a lot of
points for the number of times we turned the ball over against
Kansas, which is a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Iron woman: Point guard Kristin Clark is back in a familiar role
for the USC women's basketball team. Clark leads the Women of Troy
in minutes played now that Erica Mashia (knee) and Kiyoko Miller
(shoulder) are out for the season with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Clark is playing 36 minutes per game and no longer playing
shooting guard, which is her natural position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I'm used to,'' Clark said. ``Now, it's back to
the same old, same old.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark also averaged 36 minutes per game last season. Clark is
averaging 17.0 points, 2.86 steals and 3.4 assists per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our last game we dressed eight people,'' Clark said. ``It's
just devastating to me. We were supposed to have a great year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
