A9552 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-BROOKS21-     12-20 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-BROOKS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guiding Falcons to title win adds `more to the mix' for Brooks
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. _ The Fox TV Network caught two glimpses of Rich
Brooks at work on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Its cameras focused in on Brooks up in the Silverdome coaching
box, deep in thought during the first half, rubbing a furrowed
brow.
</P>
<P>
   And again with 1:39 to play, when Eugene Robinson's interception
wrapped up the Falcons' victory. Same Rich Brooks, interim head
coach, stoic and low-key. A division championship in the books, and
Brooks was calmly packing up his headset and binoculars.
</P>
<P>
   The smiles would come later for Brooks, who was sitting in for
Dan Reeves. The Falcons head coach, who underwent bypass surgery
last week, was remembered in a banner behind the Atlanta bench:
``Get Well Soon Coach Reeves.''
</P>
<P>
   The activity on the sidelines appeared to be business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure was on Brooks, the team's assistant head coach and
defensive coordinator, to keep the Falcons' on track. He would do
what he normally does, call the defensive plays from the press box,
with the added burden of filtering the offensive play-calling.
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to work like this: quarterbacks coach Jack
Burns, sitting with a headset on in the pressbox, would confer with
running backs coach George Sefcik and then relay the play to backup
quarterback Steve DeBerg on the sideline. DeBerg would then call
the play into his headset, transmitting it to Chris Chandler's
helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Even a casual observer could sense that something was amiss.
During an early series of plays, DeBerg gestured with his arm as if
tossing salt over his right shoulder. The secret signal? Jim
Hewitt, who does Grounds Maintenance at Suwanee and keeps track of
the headsets, walked over and pushed a button on DeBerg's controls.
They smiled grimly.
</P>
<P>
   The headsets were dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our headsets went out after the first drive,'' Chandler said.
``Steve would push the button and start talking, but I couldn't
hear him. So we'd have to signal plays in. One thing we do all week
is signal plays, just in case something like this happens. Bergie
sending them into me went just as smooth as practice goes. Once the
headset came back on the second half, it was a little bit better,
just 'cause you could talk a little better about changing
signals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were on and off in the first half. Then just before the
half they went totally out,'' DeBerg said. ``An antenna came apart
or something somewhere in the stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   In the coaching box, you could have fooled Brooks by telling him
the technology was causing a glitch. He's a defensive coach who
usually never eavesdrops on the offensive chats. That's Reeves
department under normal circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I've been on the headset with the
offense in two years here,'' Brooks said. ``I don't know how many
plays Dan influences or changes, but the system worked as it has
worked, with Jack calling the plays down to the sideline and
relayed into the quarterback. I think it worked well enough,
obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said he knew enough about the offense, with the amazing
Jamal Anderson running 147-yards strong, to leave it in Burns'
hands. ``I didn't overrule any of the offensive plays,'' Brooks
said. ``I just told them late in the game let's run it a little
more.''
</P>
<P>
   The game plan he'd hoped to pull off was supposed to dominate
the lowly Lions and give Reeves a stress-free TV experience from
home. But the Falcons didn't take control until late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it wasn't a stress-free experience for Dan watching
from home and I apologize for that,'' Brooks said. ``We just didn't
start out playing the type of defense we've been playing for the
last 6-7 weeks. We got around to it about the middle of the third
quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, the Falcons' plan to call Reeves at home and pipe the
call into the locker room seemed like nice idea. But technology, or
perhaps not enough planning by Brooks, did that one in, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set up a speaker phone system here to try to have him talk
to the team in case we won the division, but we didn't tell him, so
the phone's ringing at his house but nothing's going through,''
Brooks said. ``That's a real bad call by the old, interim head
coach.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would carry home one of the new Falcons caps, the one
embroidered, ``Champions,'' to Reeves. And he would file this game
away in his book of memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose it was a little added pressure (on me) this week,
but it would have meant a tremendous amount to me, anyway,'' said
Brooks, once the head coach of the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win a division championship in the NFL is not an easy thing
to do; to get a first round bye going into the playoffs is not an
easy thing to do. The fact that I was the interim head coach this
week doesn't make it any sweeter to me; it really doesn't. It just
added a little more to the mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
