<HEADER>
A9553 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OCTUPLETS-BORN-HNS &LR;      12-20 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCTUPLETS-BORN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON WOMAN DELIVERS ONLY KNOWN LIVING OCTUPLETS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   By T.J. MILLING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998 &QL; 
Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A 27-year-old Houston woman on Sunday became the
mother of the only known set of living octuplets.
</P>
<P>
   Nkem Chukwu gave birth to five girls and two boys by Caesarean
section about 9 a.m. at St. Luke's Episcopal Hospital. The eighth
child, a girl, was born naturally 13 days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The newborns _ who weighed between 11 ounces and 1 pound, 11
ounces _ were in critical condition and put on ventilators.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing as well as could be expected,'' said Dr. Patti
Savrick, a pediatrician at Texas Children's Hospital, where the
newborns were taken. ``She is a remarkable woman. She's very
serene, a very spiritual woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu and her husband, Iyke, a respiratory therapist, had been
trying to have children for some time, Dr. Brian Kirshon, a St.
Luke's high risk obstetrician/gynecologist. She miscarried a set of
triplets at 21 weeks of pregnancy earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   She was given a combination of hormones that induced multiple
ovulation, the same treatment that led to sextuplets here a month
ago and septuplets for an Iowa couple a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   When it was determined that she was carrying six or more
fetuses, she was referred to Kirshon, who specializes in dangerous
births. Chukwu had been in the hospital for 2{ months and on strict
bed rest for six weeks, the last two of which she was positioned on
an incline with her head down to take pressure off her cervix.
</P>
<P>
   Kirshon said a reduction, a procedure to remove some of the
fetuses to give the others a better chance of surviving, was
offered but declined. Doctors believed she was carrying at most
seven fetuses until Dec. 8, when she gave birth to the first girl.
An ultrasound view of the womb then showed there were seven more, a
fact kept under wraps for the rest of her pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, powerful drugs administered to stop uterine
contractions helped her cervix close back up so the other fetuses
could mature further, which increased their chances of survival,
Kirshon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That in and of itself is a tremendous accomplishment,''
Kirshon said.
</P>
<P>
   But doctors began to worry about the smallest fetus being able
to live much longer in the crowded womb. Kirshon said Chukwu showed
tremendous dedication to her unborn children, never complaining,
even offering to stop eating if it would provide more room for the
fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a model patient,'' he said. ``I think she is
remarkable in that she was able to tolerate such conditions. She
kept a positive attitude and was willing to do whatever it took.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday morning, Chukwu went into labor, and a crew of about 25
health-care workers became a baby brigade with Kirshon and two
other doctors performing the 45-minute operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a parade of people walking out of the delivery
room,'' Savrick said.
</P>
<P>
   The seven newborns ended up being 2{ months premature, a period
at which statistics show an 85 percent survival rate, said Dr.
Leonard Weisman, chief of neonatology at Texas Children's. They
face the problems typical of premature birth. Their lungs are
lacking in a liquid called surfactant, produced by fully developed
lungs to aid in breathing, and their hearts are weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a remarkable feat if all the babies survive,''
Kirshon said.
</P>
<P>
   Weisman said the infants may have digestive problems and have an
increased risk of infection and organ failure. Chukwu, who lives in
a modest southwest Houston neighborhood, may be allowed to go home
by the end of the week, but the babies probably will stay
hospitalized for two months.
</P>
<P>
   The five surviving infants from a set of sextuplets, born Nov.
11 to Chris Collins of Kingwood, are still at Texas Children's.
</P>
<P>
   In Carlisle, Iowa, Bobbi and Kenny McCaughey, parents of the
world's first surviving set of septuplets, were celebrating
Christmas with their church family when they heard the news of the
Chukwu octuplets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish them the Lord's blessing and a merry Christmas,'' the
couple told the Associated Press through their Tennessee-based
agent, Wes Yoder.
</P>
<P>
   The McCaughey septuplets were about nine weeks premature when
they were born on Nov. 19, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Guinness Book of World Records, the largest
multiple birth was nine babies in Sydney, Australia, in 1971. Six
of those children survived.
</P>
<P>
   Three other octuplet births have been recorded in the past 13
years.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, Rosario Clavijo, 31, of Huelva, Spain, became
pregnant with the aid of fertility drugs and gave birth Dec. 5,
1996, to six healthy babies _ four boys and two girls. Two children
died.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1996, a 32-year-old British woman, Mandy Allwood,
conceived eight fetuses and rejected medical advice to abort some
of them. Her pregnancy and her decision to have all the babies
aroused controversy after she hired a publicist to a tabloid
newspaper, which bought her story for a high sum based on how many
live births she produced. Four months into pregnancy, she lost all
the fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   A 25-year-old woman from Imzir, Turkey, gave birth to octuplets
on Dec. 20, 1985, but six died within 12 hours. The five boys and
three girls were delivered by Caesarean section, 12 weeks
premature. The mother, Sevil Capan, had been taking fertility
drugs. The remaining two babies died within three days of their
birth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
