<DOCNO> NYT19981220.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-20 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9556 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      12-20 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
HOUSE DELIVERY OF ARTICLES OF IMPEACHMENT BEGINS IMPEACHMENT TRIAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By STEVE LASH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WASHINGTON _ The trial will begin with a simple oath: ``I do
solemnly swear that in all things appertaining to the trial of the
impeachment of William Jefferson Clinton, president of the United
States, I will do impartial justice according to the Constitution
and laws. So help me God.''
</P>
<P>
   After making this pledge, Chief Justice William H Rehnquist will
perform his constitutional duty to preside over just the second
presidential impeachment trial in U.S. history. The first, which
Rehnquist himself chronicled in a 1992 book, resulted in the
acquittal of Andrew Johnson 130 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate trial of Clinton will be unlike any proceeding the
public has ever seen or will likely witness again. Many protections
afforded to criminal defendants at the local courthouse _ the
constitutional bar against being tried twice, the privilege against
self-incrimination, rules limiting trial evidence, proof beyond a
reasonable doubt and the right to appeal _ will generally not apply
to the president.
</P>
<P>
   The process was begun Saturday afternoon, when the 13 trial
managers selected by the House, led by House Judiciary Committee
Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill, delivered the two articles of
impeachment to the Senate. Formal notice was then sent by the
Senate to Rehnquist and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Acting as prosecutors, or ``managers'' in impeachment parlance,
the team led by Hyde will argue that Clinton should be removed from
office for committing perjury and obstructing justice in an attempt
to conceal his extramarital affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Defending the president will be his legal team, which tried in
vain this month to persuade the House not to impeach him. The team
will be led by White House Counsel Charles F.C. Ruff, Special
Counsel Greg Craig and Clinton's private attorney, David Kendall.
In addition, the White House has recruited former Sen. George
Mitchell to aid in the president's defense.
</P>
<P>
   If two-thirds of the Senate _ 67 of the 100 senators _ vote to
convict, Clinton's penalty will be expulsion from office. And even
if acquitted, the president could still face criminal indictment
after his term expires.
</P>
<P>
   The potential legal jeopardy after leaving office confronts
Clinton and his attorneys with a difficult choice of whether to let
the president testify before the Senate. If Clinton chooses to
testify, anything he says could and would be used against him at a
criminal trial.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to a criminal trial, the senators sitting in
judgment of the president will be free to interpret his silence as
an admission of guilt. The Fifth Amendment of the Constitution,
which does not apply to impeachment trials, prohibits judges and
juries from drawing a conclusion of guilt from a criminal
defendant's refusal to testify.
</P>
<P>
   In another stark departure from criminal proceedings, the chief
justice's status as presiding judge will afford him little
practical control over the proceedings. Nevertheless, Clinton's
prosecutors and defenders should be prepared for the 74-year-old
Rehnquist _ who regularly stops long-winded lawyers in midsentence
at the Supreme Court _ to use his gavel to prevent them from making
verbose arguments.
</P>
<P>
   This most political of American trials will bear some
resemblance to a criminal proceeding: The prosecution and the
defense will make opening statements, and witnesses may be called.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike a criminal trial, the jurors _ 100 senators _ will be
able to question witnesses, albeit indirectly. Senate rules require
lawmakers to submit their inquiries in writing to Rehnquist.
</P>
<P>
   The chief justice will rule on procedural motions and the
admissibility of evidence. However, the Senate can override these
rulings with a majority vote taken at the request of any senator.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Clinton's defense attorneys could make a motion to
dismiss the impeachment charges altogether. If Rehnquist granted
the motion, the Republican-led Senate could, and presumably would,
overrule his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating Rehnquist's judicial role is the absence of
rules defining the scope of what evidence may be admitted at the
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Civil and criminal proceedings have extensive restrictions on
the types of admissible evidence. For example, hearsay testimony _
in which a witness quotes what a person said outside the courtroom
_ is generally excluded from trials as being unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   However, such controversial statements might not only be allowed
but could comprise a large part of the Senate proceeding.
Independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report, which formed the basis
for the House's impeachment of Clinton, relies heavily on hearsay
testimony regarding what the president allegedly said to Lewinsky
and aides about his relationship with her.
</P>
<P>
   In a criminal proceeding the state must prove guilt beyond a
reasonable doubt. The Constitution does not define the level of
proof required to convict a president of an impeachable offense,
leaving it to each senator to decide how much evidence is needed.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Clinton would become the first U.S. president
expelled from office. He would have no avenue for appeal, based on
a 1993 Supreme Court decision that impeachments are political, not
legal, proceedings and, therefore, not reviewable by courts.
</P>
<P>
   The high court upheld the 1989 Senate conviction and expulsion
of former U.S. District Judge Walter L. Nixon Jr. of Southern
Mississippi for making false statements to a federal grand jury.
Rehnquist, writing for the court, said the nation's leadership
would be in dangerous limbo if a Senate conviction and removal of a
president could be appealed to the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legitimacy of any successor, and hence his effectiveness,
would be impaired severely, not merely while the judicial process
was running its course, but during any retrial that a differently
constituted Senate might conduct if its first judgment of
conviction were invalidated,'' Rehnquist wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor said the chief justice's additional
duty in the Senate will not interfere with the Supreme Court's
work. The court hears arguments in the morning, making it possible
for the chief justice to preside over a Senate trial in the
afternoon, O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   A presidential impeachment trial is the only constitutionally
defined instance in which all three branches of the federal
government are working simultaneously. The head of the judicial
branch, the chief justice, presides; the legislative branch,
represented by the Senate, acts as jury; and the executive branch,
as embodied by the president, is the defendant.
</P>
<P>
   The only other times the American people see leaders of the
three branches at once are at the president's annual State of the
Union address and at presidential inaugurations.
</P>
<P>
   During the address, the president speaks to Congress from the
House chamber, but lawmakers and Supreme Court justices are merely
spectators. At an inauguration, the chief justice administers the
oath of office to the president, often on the steps of the Capitol,
but members of Congress do not participate in the event. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
