<HEADLINE>
PUERTO MADERO WINS IMPRESSIVELY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Puerto Madero might not be a perfect Gentlemen. The
two horses have different strides and personalities.
</P>
<P>
   But Puerto Madero looks like a worthy replacement for the
retired Gentlemen in the stable of owner R.D. Hubbard and trainer
Richard Mandella.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Madero, who twice ran second to likely Horse of the Year
Skip Away earlier in the season, came back from a four-month layoff
Sunday to win impressively under Kent Desormeaux in the $100,000
Native Diver Handicap at Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, by 2{ lengths over Musical Gambler with River Keen
third, will send Puerto Madero into the Santa Anita meet as one of
the circuit's most feared older horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can go forward from this... we've got big dreams,'' said
Mandella, who expects to run the Chile-bred 4-year-old next in the
Feb. 7 San Antonio Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Native Diver served as a springboard for
Gentlemen, who went on to earn $3.6 million before retiring
recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't really think of them as the same,'' said
Mandella, who has won the Native Diver a record six times,
including three in a row. ``Gentlemen was one tough customer. He'd
kick, bite, paw you, but only just playing. (Puerto Madero) has a
lot of character, but just in a little different way.''
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Madero paid $3.40.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-day Hollywood Park meet ends this afternoon with the
jockey and trainer titles up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Jockey Garrett Gomez holds a 22-21 lead over Eddie Delahoussaye
and Alex Solis, who won twice Sunday. Gomez has the edge on closing
day in quantity and quality of mounts.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Neil Drysdale has a precarious 10-9 lead over Paddy
Gallagher, Mel Stute and Paul Aguirre, who saddled one winner
Sunday. Drysdale and Gallagher have no horses in today's races and
Stute only has one long shot. Aguirre has the edge with two
favorites among his five entrants.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Hollywood Park will finish with an average of $9 million
in daily wagering, the highest for the autumn meet except for 1997,
when the track's business got a bump from hosting the Breeders'
Cup. On-site wagering and attendance have shown little change....
Santa Anita opens Saturday.... A $54.40 upset by Top Contender in
the nightcap set up a $151,798 carryover in today's pick six....
Edward Allred's Kingman Kid, ridden by Joe Badilla Jr., won the Los
Alamitos Million Futurity late Saturday night and paid $37.30. The
$1,173,605 purse for the race for 2-year-old quarterhorses was the
largest in California this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
