<SLUG> BC-SHUSTER-PROBE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUSTER PROBE MAY HAVE FIZZLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Boston federal probe into US Representative Bud
Shuster, the powerful transportation committee chairman from
Pennsylvania, has all but ground to a halt with little prospect
that it will produce any charges, individuals familiar with the
probe said.
</P>
<P>
   Those sources said the investigation could be revived if
Shuster's former top aide and close friend, Ann Eppard, who has
been charged in the investigation, were to decide to cooperate with
investigators and offer new evidence. But short of that or the
cooperation of another key witness, sources say, the probe is dead.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, there have been indications that the Shuster
case had become increasingly inactive. For example, the lead
prosecutor in the investigation, Alexandra Leake, resigned
recently, a move that confirmed for many who know her work that the
investigation is all but over.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the grand jury probing the case apparently has not
subpoenaed documents or witnesses since early in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the US House Committee on Standards of Official
Conduct, which had suspended its inquiry into Shuster last June at
the request of the Justice Department, announced early this month
that it was resuming its own probe. The department had in June
expressed concern that the committee's work would ``pose certainly
unavoidable risks to the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuster's lawyer, Boston attorney Stephen R. Delinsky, last week
said he sees no evidence that the investigation is active.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my knowledge there's no ongoing investigation of
congressman Shuster by the US Attorney's Office,'' Delinsky said.
``I'm aware of the allegations that the US Attorney's Office looked
into, but it is my understanding that none of those allegations
concerned any impropriety by Congressman Shuster.''
</P>
<P>
   The US Attorney's Office in Boston said its policy is not to
comment on investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Eppard, who served until 1994 as Shuster's top aide and
political adviser, was indicted by a Boston federal grand jury last
spring on charges that she received $230,000 in illegal payments
from a Washington lobbyist and his client, including Boston
businessman Richard Goldberg. She and the lobbyist, Vernon Clark,
are awaiting trial this winter.
</P>
<P>
   The indication that Shuster has survived the investigation
unscathed is significant in Washington, where the Republican
lawmaker wields considerable power through his committee,
particularly with his ability to control the flow of funds for
local transportation projects.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the congressman has been a key player in helping
Massachusetts obtain the funding for the Big Dig. The investigation
into his activities had at times raised serious concerns among
state transportation officials over the future funding of the
project.
</P>
<P>
   According to the case against Eppard, Goldberg allegedly paid
her $10,000 in 1990 to protect his Park 'N Fly lot near Logan
Airport during construction of the Ted Williams Tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   The Shuster probe grew out of the federal investigation into
former Massachusetts House Speaker Charles Flaherty in the early
1990s. That inquiry focused in part on Flaherty's relationship with
Goldberg, but no charges were ever filed. In a plea agreement, the
former speaker pled guilty to an unrelated tax fraud felony charge
in 1996 and resigned.
</P>
<P>
   The Shuster investigation probed the complex professional and
personal relationship between the congressman and Eppard, who is
now a Washington lobbyist for transportation interests.
</P>
<P>
   Eppard resigned her congressional post in 1994 to lobby
Congress, but continued to be a political adviser and fund-raiser
for the veteran congressman as well as close personal friend. He
often stays at her Virginia home in an arrangement that was part of
the federal investigation, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal probe also looked at evidence that Shuster and
Eppard may have used tens of thousands of dollars in campaign funds
for personal use. Eppard is charged with embezzling $27,000 from
the campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Goldberg, the Shuster probe focused on another Boston
businessman, Nicholas Contos, who had, sources said, loaned
Eppard's son, Ralph, money to start a car dealership. That loan and
Goldberg's payments were made at a time they were asking Eppard and
Shuster to intervene on their behalf in disputes with state
transportation officials.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Goldberg's payment was given under the guise of a
consulting fee but the funds ended up in a bank account the younger
Eppard held with his mother, who reportedly signed the checks for
the accounts. Just last week, Goldberg's bid for a land swap with
the state to save his business was completed.
</P>
<P>
   Contos, owner of No Name Restaurant, has been granted immunity
by the US Attorney's Office in Boston and will testify at Eppard's
trial about his loan to the younger Eppard to buy a car dealership
in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources, Contos advanced the loan in late 1991 or
early 1992 at the urging of Clark, his Washington lobbyist and a
close friend of Ann Eppard. Just months earlier, Contos had settled
with state and federal officials in a longstanding dispute he had
over the Big Dig's taking of his land in South Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
