<SLUG> BC-ADVERTISING-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERPUBLIC ACQUISITIONS; MEDIA COMPANY REVIEWS; MICRON ON
INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ga., Idaho, Ill., Ind., Kan., Ky., Minn., N.C.,
Texas)  (rl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Interpublic Group Announces 3 Deals
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition spree by the Interpublic Group of Companies in
New York is continuing with the purchases of an agency, an agency
office and a corporate communications company.
</P>
<P>
   The agency being acquired is Austin Kelley Advertising in
Atlanta, which has estimated billings of $85 million from clients
like the Georgia Lottery and the Mercedes-Benz Credit Corp. Austin
Kelley will maintain a separate identity, reporting to the
McCann-Erickson World Group unit of Interpublic.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Nixon, 52, president and chief executive at Austin
Kelley, will stay on in those posts along with the rest of the
management team.
</P>
<P>
   The other two acquisitions involved Carmichael Lynch in
Minneapolis, which Interpublic bought in February. In one deal,
Carmichael Lynch acquired the Minneapolis office of
Valentine-McCormick-Ligibel, an agency based in Kansas City, Kan.
Craig Ligibel, 50, Scott McCormick, 52, and John Valentine, 47, the
partners who shared responsibility for the Minneapolis office, will
serve as consultants for three years.
</P>
<P>
   The office and its 38 employees, handling accounts with billings
estimated at $38 million to $40 million, will be merged into
Carmichael Lynch. That adds Carmichael Lynch to the agency roster
of Northwest Airlines as it assumes assignments the office had
handled in areas like domestic advertising and projects.
</P>
<P>
   And Carmichael Lynch Spong, the public relations division of
Carmichael Lynch, acquired another Minneapolis-based agency,
McGrath Buckley Consulting Group.
</P>
<P>
   Carmichael Lynch Spong will form a division, McGrath Buckley
Group, to specialize in services like investor relations and
employee communications. Douglas Spong, 39, managing partner of
Carmichael Lynch Spong, will head the division in that role. Dennis
B. McGrath, 61, and Betsy Buckley, 51, principals at McGrath
Buckley Consulting, will become senior partners.
</P>
<P>
   2 Big Media Accounts Placed in Review
</P>
<P>
   Two large media accounts have been placed in review. One is for
the Sprint Corp., with billings estimated at $200 million to $250
million, while the other is for Glaxo Wellcome Inc., with billings
estimated at $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   At Sprint, Mark Bonavia, a spokesman in Westwood, Kan.,
confirmed reports of the review in Advertising Age and Adweek. Most
of the media duties for Sprint have been handled by J. Walter
Thompson USA in New York, part of the J. Walter Thompson Company
unit of WPP Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has been invited to take part in the review, Bonavia
said, along with other agencies that he declined to identify. A
decision is expected by mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   At Glaxo Wellcome, the media portion of its account had been
divided into buying and planning segments. Media buying had been
handled for 18 months by the Media Edge in New York. The
media-planning duties had been divided among four agencies
including Media Edge.
</P>
<P>
   Media Edge, owned by Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc., was asked to
participate in the review, said Ramona DuBose, a spokeswoman for
Glaxo Wellcome in Research Triangle Park, N.C., along with the
other three planning agencies: the Mediacom unit of Grey; Rockett
Burkhead Lewis &AMP; Winslow in Raleigh, N.C., and Wilson Media in New
York. Agencies not on the Glaxo Wellcome roster have also been
invited to compete, Ms. DuBose said. A decision is expected at the
end of March.
</P>
<P>
   Grey Advertising And Lexmark Split Up
</P>
<P>
   Grey Advertising in New York and Lexmark International, the
maker and marketer of laser and ink jet printers, are mutually
parting ways after three and a half years, citing creative
differences. As a result, the company's corporate and product
advertising account has been placed in review.
</P>
<P>
   Lexmark has drawn up a list of agencies to take part in the
review, said Roger Rydell, a spokesman for Lexmark in Lexington,
Ky., but he declined to identify them. The list will be narrowed
next month to two or three agencies, he added, with a decision
expected by March. Rydell estimated the billings at more than $20
million; spending this year was estimated at $9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Micron Spot Goes To Internet First
</P>
<P>
   Micron Electronics Inc. in Nampa, Idaho, is introducing a
commercial that is to appear first on the Internet and then on
television. The spot, created by Bam in Austin, Texas, will feature
Jeri Ryan, who plays the character Seven-of-Nine on the series
``Star Trek Voyager.''
</P>
<P>
   The spot, part of a campaign carrying the theme ``New rules, new
tools,'' is to be introduced Dec. 28 on the Micron Web site
(www.micronpc.com), then run the next day on TV during the coverage
of the Micron PC Bowl college football game.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts
</P>
<P>
   Midas Inc., Chicago, to Carat New York, part of the Carat North
America unit of Aegis Group PLC, to handle the media buying portion
of its account, which had been handled by TN Media, New York, a
unit of True North Communications. Billings were estimated at $55
million to $60 million. The creative and strategic duties were
assigned last week to Euro RSCG Tatham, Chicago, part of Havas
Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Home Shark Inc., San Francisco, to Citron Haligman Bedecarre,
San Francisco, as the first agency to handle national advertising
for the Internet-based mortgage broker. Billings were estimated at
$10 million to $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications, Atlanta, a division of Cox Enterprises, to
BBDO South, Atlanta, a unit of Omnicom Group, to handle its image
and branding account, which had most recently been handled by
Bigelow &AMP; Eigel, Atlanta. Billings were estimated at $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Entercitement LLC, Mooresville, Ind., to Young &AMP; Laramore,
Indianapolis, as the first agency to handle creative advertising
for the theme park. Billings were estimated at $3 million.
Echopoint Media, Indianapolis, a subsidiary of Young &AMP; Laramore,
will handle media services.
</P>
</TEXT>
