<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-WEEKEND-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday 12/20/98. Photo clients
will automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or
may download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Dec. 20, 1998 -- AIDS-VOLUNTEER, 12-20 --
Troy Masters, 37, at Bellevue Hospital Center, has volunteered to
test an experimental AIDS vaccine. Masters, who is gay,
HIV-negative and sexually active, is one of the first volunteers in
New York City to qualify for the world's first full-scale test of
the vaccine known as Aidsvax. ``The virus needs a vaccine,'' he
says. ``If there is a front of activism that needs to be developed,
that's it. I'm giving my behavior over to science. This is like
signing for permission to end the AIDS crisis.'' (Suzanne
DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) KEY WEST, Fla. -- Dec. 20, 1998 -- OBIT-FISHER, 12-20 --
Mel Fisher, a former chicken farmer who became a Horatio Alger
figure among undersea treasure hunters, died on Saturday at his
home in Key West. The cause was complications from cancer. He was
76. Fisher found gold and silver coins, jewelry and bars worth
millions from old-time Spanish shipwrecks in the waters off
Florida. He hunted doggedly for years for the cargo of a single
treasure-packed galleon, the Nuestra Senora de Atocha. Eventually
his son Kane located the underwater bounty in 1985, and the
treasure was recovered. (Susan Greenwood/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Dec. 20, 1998 -- DICKENS-CHRISTMAS-CAROL,
12-20 -- Roz Ryan, left, as the Ghost of Christmas Present and
Roger Daltrey, the former lead singer of the Who, as Scrooge in ``A
Christmas Carol,'' at the Theater at Madison Square Garden. ``A
Christmas Carol'' is such a favorite, such a guaranteed revenue
producer, that according to the Theater Communications Group, an
umbrella organization for nonprofit theaters, there are 33 member
theaters producing it this season around the United States. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 20, 1998 -- IMPEACH-HASTERT, 12-20 --
Rep. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., left, conferring with his fellow
Republican Rep. John A. Boehner in June, is likely to be the next
Speaker of the House. Hastert, a six-term conservative who is the
No. 2 vote counter in the House Republican hierarchy, has a
reputation among his GOP colleagues as a conciliator, someone who
can reach out to Democrats. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 20, 1998 -- IMPEACH-SPEAKER, 12-20 --
With a brief tenure as Speaker-elect, Rep. Robert Livingston, shown
in his office after the impeachment vote on Saturday, rocked the
House on Thursday with his revelation that he had had adulterous
affairs. Livingston stunned the Capitol once again Saturday by
saying that he would not serve as speaker and would quit Congress
in six months. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 20, 1998 -- IMPEACH-LOYALTY, 12-20 --
Rep. Jose E. Serrano, who represents the South Bronx, was among the
Democratic Congressmen who appeared with President Clinton at the
White House after the impeachment vote on Saturday. But many
Democrats did not rally around their president out of heartfelt
fealty. Instead, they were registering their disapproval of how
Republicans have handled the inquiry -- as well as their belief
that impeachment is not warranted. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ALLAHABAD -- Dec. 12, 1998 -- INDIA-UNIVERSITY-2, 12-20
-- Masses of students at a recent student election at Allahabad
University. In its heyday, Allahabad was known as the Oxford of
India. Allahabad's decline is sadly symptomatic of a university
system overstuffed with students and undernourished with resources.
A campus built for 5,000 students now has 60,000. While only 3
percent of Indians ages 17 to 23 attend college, that still amounts
to 7 million students. (Barry Bearak/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ALLAHABAD -- Dec. 12, 1998 -- INDIA-UNIVERSITY-1, 12-20
-- Once known as the Oxford of India, Allahabad University is now
part of a university system overstuffed with students and
undernourished with resources. The main building, pictured, is a
graceful reminder of its golden age. A tidal wave of poor students
from the lower reaches of India's caste system has brought serious
decline to the university. A campus built for 5,000 students now
has 60,000. (Barry Bearak/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Dec. 20, 1998 -- HELLMAN-AUTHOR-PROFILE,
12-20 -- Author Rosemary Mahoney's latest book, ``A Likely Story:
One Summer With Lillian Hellman'' is about her unhappy two months
working with Ms. Hellman, ``the great lady of American letters.''
Mahoney, 37, whose ``Whoredom in Kimmage: The World of Irish
Women'' was nominated for the National Book Critics Circle Award in
1993, spent time before her senior year in high school working for
Hellman. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Dec. 20, 1998 -- 60-MINUTES-II, 12-20 -- Jeff
Fager, 44, the executive producer of ``60 Minutes II,'' and Dan
Rather helped sell the new program inside CBS. Fager's ``60 II,''
as it is nicknamed, must walk a fine line, living up to the
standards of the original ``60 Minutes'' while not imitating it.
With staff in place, Fager's greatest worry is replicating the
journalistic caliber of most ``60 Minutes'' pieces. ``That's what's
daunting about it, to look at that program, that kind of legacy,''
says Fager. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
