<HEADLINE>
LOUIS SHER, 84, EXHIBITOR OF FOREIGN FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Louis Sher, a movie exhibitor who pioneered the showing of
foreign films, died on Nov. 25 in Phoenix, Ariz. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
   Sher opened his first movie theater in 1954 in Columbus, Ohio,
and made foreign films his specialty. He eventually built a
national chain called the Art Theater Guild, which at one time
included more than 50 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to foreign films, Sher showed the work of Andy
Warhol and Shirley Clark as well as the early films of George
Lucas, Francis Ford Coppola and Martin Scorsese. He was a key
figure in the obscenity trial involving Louis Malle's 1958 film
``The Lovers,'' which brought a ruling by the U.S. Supreme Court
that the film was not pornographic.
</P>
<P>
   He was also the producer or co-producer of shows for Broadway,
including the musical ``Shenandoah'' in 1975 and a play, ``The Trip
Back Down,'' in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in Columbus, Sher attended Ohio State
University. He served in the U.S. Army during World War II and was
awarded the Bronze Star.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Helen; four children from his first
marriage, Larry of Los Gatos, Calif., Robert of Phoenix, Linda Dunn
of Chicago and Nancy Beigel Sher of New York; a stepdaughter, Cathy
Smith Sapin; a stepson, Michael Tash; 10 grandchildren and six
great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
