<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUNK-TRAGEDY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN HELD ON SUSPICION OF KILLING GIRL WITH CAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLES BOSTWICK AND LEE CONDON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALMDALE, Calif. _ Neighbors and witnesses expressed shock and
disgust as they recounted how an 8-year-old girl was rammed to
death by car driven by a woman who fended off would-be rescuers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was screaming. She just went right after us. She wouldn't
stop fighting,'' said Ben Chavez, a tow truck driver who lives a
few doors from where the crash occurred at 11:30 p.m. Saturday.
``She wanted everybody to go away. That's all she kept saying.''
</P>
<P>
   When neighbors and passing motorists arrived, 8-year-old Sara
Criado was pinned to a block wall by a 1974 Oldsmobile Cutlass and
34-year-old Doreen Gutierrez was in the driver's seat, the Los
Angeles County Sheriff's Department reported.
</P>
<P>
   The driver wouldn't listen to the good Samaritans' pleas to
shift the car's transmission from park into neutral so they could
push it out of the way, one witness said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead she took the key, got out and began fighting with the
people trying to help the dying girl, Chavez said. She yanked on
the hair of a man trying to push her car and tried to punch others.
</P>
<P>
   Deputies said Gutierrez ran Sara down after getting into an
argument with the girl's mother, Teresa Gutierrez. The two women
are not related, but they are roommates.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Gutierrez decided to walk home from a party with her son
and daughter rather than ride with Doreen Gutierrez, who she
thought was too drunk too drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they refused to accept a ride, Doreen became enraged and
drove away at a high rate of speed,'' Sheriff's Department
spokesman Deputy Michael Irving said. ``After driving a couple
blocks, Doreen put her car in reverse and drove back to where
Teresa and her children were walking. Doreen put her car in drive,
aimed it at the three victims and attempted to run them over.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking along 30th Street East in the community 62 miles north
of downtown Los Angeles, Teresa Gutierrez and the boy jumped out of
the way, but the car hit Sara, pinning her and smashing a
four-foot-wide hole through the wall.
</P>
<P>
   After fighting with the people trying to help the girl, the
driver was finally tackled by the men, Chavez said. They held her
on the ground until firefighters arrived. Another woman drove up
and said she was the suspect's sister and would take care of her,
Chavez said.
</P>
<P>
   But after the men let her up, the suspect got into a Jeep that
had pulled up and rode away with the driver, who deputies said was
a friend.
</P>
<P>
   One bystander started yelling, ``That's her,'' and another man
ran after the Jeep. He spotted a patrol car that had just arrived
and told the deputy the motorist involved in the crash was leaving,
said neighbor Tony Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy sped off after the Jeep, and officials said Doreen
Gutierrez was taken into custody a few blocks away. Gutierrez was
arrested on suspicion of murder and held without bail.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the firefighters pronounced the little girl dead
when they arrived. Neither Teresa Gutierrez nor her son were
injured, but witnesses described the mother as frantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was ... (walking) around the car, around the car, looking
at her daughter. There wasn't anything anybody could do,'' Chavez
said. ``Everybody wanted to help because they heard it was a little
girl. There was nothing really anybody could do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
